items.title: Six miners trapped after mine collapses, rescue attempt
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Wide of area outside mine, zoom in to mountain
2. Wide of mountain with zoom in 
3. SOUNDBITE (English) Jon Huntsman, Utah Governor: 
"You have to be optimistic with a situation like this. You have families not far from here, you have six miners who all could very well be alive. In fact, the experts would tell you that are. And the rescue attempts are increasingly close to the cavern where they think they are located, so yes, hope is in order at this point, heavy doses of hope."
4. Wide of helicopter carrying Utah Governor Jon Hunstman taking off
5. Wide of Robert Murray, Murray Energy Corporation Chairman at news conference
6. SOUNDBITE (English) Robert Murray, Murray Energy Corporation Chairman: 
"It's quite possible they're alive, and I want to believe that they are, and we're wasting no effort to get to them."
7. Cutaway press
8. SOUNDBITE (English) Robert Murray, Murray Energy Corporation Chairman: 
"We are turning over every stone, working very closely with the federal Mine Safety and Health Administration.  As I told you earlier, I take the safety of my employees to bed with me every night, and we will be here on our feet until we get these men out, one way or the other."
9. Wide of truck hauling mine equipment
10. Wide of truck hauling mine equipment
11. Mid of police officer talking to man in truck
12. Wide of  police car
13. Mid of police officer talking to man in car; car drives away
STORYLINE
In Huntington, Utah on Monday, hundreds of rescuers struggled with falling rock and debris in a desperate race to reach six coal miners believed trapped 1,500 feet (457 meters) below ground by a cave-in so powerful that authorities questioned whether it was caused by an earthquake.
As the rescue stretched into the night, workers were unable to make significant progress and the initial effort was declared a failure.
"Hope is in order at this point, heavy doses of hope," said the Governor of Utah, Jon Huntsman.
More than 16 hours after the collapse, searchers had been unable to contact the miners and could not say whether they were dead or alive. 
If they survived they could have enough air and water to last several days, according to Robert Murray, chairman of Murray Energy Corporation, which owns the mine.
"It's quite possible they're alive, and I want to believe that they are, and we're wasting no effort to get to them," he said.
"I take the safety of my employees to bed with me every night, and we will be here on our feet until we get these men out, one way or the other," he added.
Rescuers planned to spend the night bulldozing a road outside the mine to make way for a drilling rig that can punch holes large enough to improve ventilation and determine whether the men were alive. They also planned to continue drilling from inside and outside the mine.
The mining crew was believed to be about four miles (6.4 kilometres) from the mine entrance. 
About a mile (1.5 kilometres) from the mine's entrance, there was an all-day procession of trucks hauling heavy machinery headed toward the site to claw at rock and raw earth.
Federal mine-safety inspectors, who have issued more than 3-hundred citations against the mine since January 2004, were also on hand to help oversee the search.
The mine is built into a mountain in the rugged Manti-La Sal National Forest, 140 miles (225 kilometres) south of Salt Lake City, in a sparsely populated area.
The collapse did not appear related to an explosion. 
University of Utah seismograph stations recorded seismic waves of 3.9 magnitude around early Monday in the area of the mine, causing speculation that a minor earthquake had caused the cave-in.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/27186329d05cd05e656025a8eeeedd74 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Scenaries at La Jolla Cove
items.description: Images captured at La Jolla Cove near San Diego, CA. Taken on the day Chile has a 8.3 Earthquake. The California Coast was on Tsunami advisory. We later found that there was a one foot tall wave.

items.title: Library Live 2015, Marie Mutsuki Mockett
items.description: Marie Mutsuki Mockett’s family owns a Buddhist temple 25 miles from the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear power plant. In March 2011, after the earthquake and tsunami, radiation levels prohibited the burial of her Japanese grandfather’s bones. As Japan mourned thousands of people lost in the disaster, Mockett also grieved for her American father, who had died unexpectedly.

Opening to the Show 

Good morning Rubidoux, welcome to R Falcon Show DAILY! I’m (say FULL NAME) ___________and Im__________. And now please stand for the Pledge of Allegiance.  
 
Pledge

ESLR QUOTE (CHANGES EVERYDAY) - 
As an Outstanding Citizen, remember to work with others, respecting their thoughts and opinions.  Teamwork is successful when all members are dedicated to the task and courteous to one another.

Congratulations to the following Fabulous Falcons Winners for this week. Thank you for representing Rubidoux as an Outstanding Citizen. (SHOW GRAPHIC in GOOGLE DRIVE).

Girl's Basketball preseason workouts will begin Monday October 12th THAT’S TODAY!. Meet in room 101 at 2:15. All girls who are not currently in a sport may attend, but you must be cleared in order to participate.

All girls interested in trying out for girl's soccer, the official tryout dates will be Wednesday & Thursday October 21st & 22nd, on the baseball fields from 3:00-5:30.  You absolutely MUST be cleared in order to tryout...with all paperwork completed including an up to date physical.  If you are currently playing volleyball, tennis, or cross country, you will be given a one day tryout when your season ends. (SHOW VOICEOVER VID)    (RUN10/12-10/16 AND Monday 10/19-10/20)

Falcons be sure to wear your IDs and Lanyards ensuring that your ID is visible. Not wearing your ID is like a fisherman without a fishing pole. 

ID BADGE COMMERCIAL

Falcons: Here is the lunch menu for the month of October for the cafeteria. (LUNCH CALENDAR show Graphic)

Falcons would you be prepared in the event of  the next BIG ONE. I’m not talking about when Mr. Bailey passes gas. I am talking about the next big earthquake. Will you be ready?? The next video will inform you of The Great California ShakeOut, which is an annual opportunity to practice how to be safer during big earthquakes: "Drop, Cover and Hold On." The ShakeOut has also been organized to encourage you, your community, and your school to review and update emergency preparedness plans and supplies, and to secure your space in order to prevent damage and injuries. Let’s take a look. 

California Shakeout Video

ASB will postpone the side walk sale because the BREAST CANCER PINK SHIRTS will go one sale this Tuesday.  The breast cancer awareness  game will be this Friday night.  Kick off is @ 7:00. WEAR YOUR PINK and BREAST CANCER PINK SHIRTS to the game.

items.title: Maritime Museum - Fascinating Maritime History
items.description:
http://sandiegoboattours.com/   The San Diego Maritime Museum is home to a large variety of historical yachts and history relating to both San Diego and maritime traditions as well.

It is also home to the "Star of India" sailing vessel which has been around the world 23 times and is the worlds oldest steel still sailing ship.

The HMS Surprise has been at the museum since 2004.  It is a replica of the 18th century Royal Navy frigate Rose and was used in the movie "master and Commander" staring Russel Crow.

The Berkeley the largest ship at the museum is a 1898 steam ferry boat.  It was used during the 1906 earthquake in San Francisco to carry survivors to safety.

Everyone at San Diego Boat Tours encourages you to visit the museum and to come out on a yacht charter with us to see the sites in San Diego bay.

items.title: Scenes at dawn in devastated area, tsunami survivors
items.description:
1. Wide of dawn at Rikuzentakata where one tree survived the tsunami
2. Tilt up from water to tree
3. Mid of people praying, snow falling
4. Wide of people praying
5. Close of woman praying
6. Wide of woman leaving flowers on ground
7. SOUNDBITE: (Japanese) Mika Hashikai, resident of Rikuzentakata who lost her parents in the tsunami, and whose brother lost his wife and daughter:
"I only wish for my brother's happiness - now that he's lost everything and is alone. Maybe one day he can remarry and have children again."
8. SOUNDBITE: (Japanese) Naomi Fujino, resident of Rikuzentakata who lost her father in the tsunami:
"I wanted to save people but I couldn't. I couldn't even help my father. I cannot keep on crying. What can I do but keep on going."
9. Mid of Fujino walking away
10. Close of Santa Claus doll sitting on the ground, next to flowers, at roadside memorial to victim
11. Wide of Santa and the flattened land in the background where once buildings stood before the tsunami
STORYLINE
Dawn broke on Sunday over what remains of the fishing community of Rikuzentakata, which was devastated by the tsunami which hit Japan's north-east coast a year ago.
People came to pray in front of the symbolic pine tree that survived the tsunami and stands alone where the city used to be, just one building alongside it.
A magnitude 9.0 earthquake triggered the monstrous tsunami which roared across the coast, killing nearly 19-thousand Japanese people, and transforming once thriving towns into debris-strewn wastelands.
Rikuzentakata was one of the cities flattened, with a loss of more than 1,500 lives, and 41 people are still missing.
It was calculated that 3,159 houses were completely washed away and hundreds more were battered.
On the first anniversary of the tsunami, people returned to the spots where their houses used to be, to place flowers and small gifts for the loved ones they lost.
Mika Hashikai lost both her parents in the tsunami, and came to leave flowers in remembrance.
Her brother also survived the tsunami but lost his wife and daughter.
"I only wish for my brother's happiness - now that he's lost everything and is alone. Maybe one day he can remarry and have children again."
Resident Naomi Fujino was in tears recalling what had happened to her family on March 11 last year.
She was with her parents when they heard the sirens warning of the tsunami coming.
With her mother, she escaped to the closest hill and had promised to meet up with her father there.
Mother and daughter watched as the giant tsunami swept away their home, praying that the father had escaped.
They waited all night but he never came to meet them.
Two months later, with help of DNA testing, his body was found.
"I wanted to save people but I couldn't. I couldn't even help my father. I cannot keep on crying. What can I do but keep on going," Fujino said.
Later on Sunday, memorials will be held in all the locations that were destroyed, and tens of thousands of residents will come together in silent prayer at the exact moment when the earthquake struck, at 14:46 local time.
The devastating tsunami enveloped the north-eastern coast shortly afterwards.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/7e846cda2dbe399b0eca08cc87ca6380 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Billionaire investor Warren Buffett arrives to inaugurate new factory
items.description:
1. Wide of billionaire investor Warren Buffett's car arriving at the site
2. Mid of Buffett getting out of car and shaking hands with Tungaloy President Yoshito Uehara and others
3. Mid of chairman of the IMC group Eitan Wertheimer (left), Buffett (middle), Uehara (right) posing for photos 
4. Close of Buffett 
5. Wide of Buffett walking towards Tungaloy employees
6. Wide of Buffett and Tungaloy employees holding banner that reads: (English/Japanese) "Never give up, Fukushima"
7. Close of Buffett and banner
8. Wide of Buffett walking
9. Wide of Tungaloy staff posing for camera
10. Buffett walking into room, greeted by Israeli Ambassador Nissim Ben Shitrit
11. Buffett greeted by Fukushima Prefecture Vice Governor Masao Uchibori
12. Wide pan from photographers to Buffett and guests
STORYLINE:
Billionaire investor Warren Buffett inaugurated the opening of a new factory of one of his investments, Tungaloy Corporation, on Monday. 
The company is located in Iwaki, near the 20 kilometre (12.4 miles) exclusion zone of Fukushima. The ceremony was originally scheduled for March 22 with Buffett to attend, but was delayed due to damage caused by the March 11 earthquake disaster.
At the welcome ceremony held on Monday morning, Buffett was greeted by Tungaloy President Yoshito Uehara, Israeli Ambassador Nissim Ben Shitrit and the Vice Governor of Fukushima prefecture Masao Uchibori.
Tungaloy, a maker of cutting tools mainly used in auto and aircraft manufacturing, split from Toshiba through a management buyout in February 2004. It was then acquired by Holland-based IMC (International Metalworking Companies) in November 2008. 
Buffett's investment company Berkshire Hathaway holds a majority stake in IMC.
The new 2-storey plant is a mass-production facility for one of its key toolmaking product, TAC inserts. 
The company says the factory's restoration work from damage caused by the disaster is almost complete, and that the new plant is scheduled to operate at full capacity by the end of this month.
Buffett will tour the new tool factory and hold a news conference later on Monday together with the chairman of the IMC group, Eitan Wertheimer.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/b1242d1faa88d6ea00c8bfd1b1ddb8b6 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: AP look at slow pace of reconstruction in Miyagi Prefecture
items.description:
Life has been put on hold for most residents of a small Japanese fishing town following the devastating earthquake and tsunami on 11 March.  
Three months after the disaster struck, Minamisanriku in Miyagi Prefecture largely remains flattened, with many complaining of painstakingly slow reconstruction efforts. 
Rubble still blankets the ground, while residents sit patiently in makeshift tents waiting for their homes to be rebuilt. 
"It's been three months�and I feel that time has frozen since the day of the disaster," construction manager Shoji Sato says.
As post-tsunami Japan strains under the enormous task of rebuilding many towns like Minamisanriku, the sheer extent of the devastation means resources are stretched. 
Some residents have tried to use debris lying around to rebuild their homes, including school teacher Yasuaki Yoshida. 
Out of a population of 17,666, at least 542 Minamisanriku residents have been confirmed dead and 664 still missing. 
Over four thousand people are still scattered in shelters. 
Others have moved themselves into temporary homes or left Minamisanriku to stay with relatives.   
The port city was once a busy town with supermarkets, shopping centres, banks, offices, schools and over 5-thousand houses.   
The tsunami swept away nearly every business, every job. 
Electricity returned in mid-May, but enough water is only running for washing dirty clothes and flushing toilets.   
The water contains too much salt to cook, but residents say they take baths in it anyway because that is all they have.    
Ikuko Abe lost her home and her livelihood, working in a hair salon, following the disaster. 
Now she works everyday as a volunteer making lunch and dinner for people living in an evacuation centre in the town.  
"How long will it take for us to get back everything that used to exist, like supermarkets, hospitals, the town hall�I have no idea how long it will take for us to get our town back. Probably decades," she says wearily.
Every day, bulldozers organise debris into separate piles; wood to be used as fuel, or piles of scrap metal to be hauled away.    
But no one knows when the city will get back on its feet and local residents don't appear hopeful about their town's future.
"I wonder if it will be any different in August," says a 92-year-old town resident, now living in temporary housing accomodation.
The pulverised coast is still being hit by hundreds of small aftershocks each day. 
Japan is located on the Ring of Fire, an arc of volcanoes and fault lines spanning the Pacific Basin, and is regularly hit by earthquakes.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/63a2c8952cada5979f6ce8f0c6df4150 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: AP cover: Japan holds moment of silence one month after the disasters
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Various of Japanese Self Defence Force (JSDF) holding a moment of silence for the victims of earthquake and tsunami in Kesennuma, Miyagi Prefecture, AUDIO: Siren
2. Mid of workers observing a moment of silence, AUDIO: Siren
3. Close of evening sun
4. Various of rubble with members of JSDF clearing debris and searching for bodies
5. Two members of JSDF talking
6. Member of JSDF standing on top of rubble
7. Member of JSDF shovelling mud
8. Interior of JSDF commanding operation centre
9. Colonel Toshiki Fujioka, regimental commander showing a map to another member
10. Close of JSDF member watching
11. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Colonel Toshiki Fujioka, Regimental commander:
"We are in a very difficult situation (in the search for missing) because it is impossible for us to remove the mass of rubble by just manpower, so we have to use heavy equipment but must do it very carefully. We are trying to retrieve bodies as cleanly as possible."  
12. Various of trucks at search operation
STORYLINE:
Sirens wailed and people bowed their heads and wept along Japan's devastated northeast coast on Monday as they marked a month since the tsunami that killed up to 25-thousand people and unleashed a persistent nuclear crisis.
In Kesennuma, among the worst-hit cities in Miyagi prefecture, members of Japan's Self Defence Force carrying out the search operation for the missing, gathered for the moment of silence ceremony at 2:46 p.m., (05:46 GMT) the exact moment of the magnitude-9.0 quake that spawned the tsunami March 11.
After an announcement by the city government on a speaker, soldiers and civilians stopped their work and took off their helmets as the noisy clatter of searching equipment ceased briefly.
With thousands of bodies yet to be found, a tsunami-flooded nuclear power plant still spewing radiation and more than 150-thousand people living in shelters, there was little time for reflection on Japan's worst disaster since World War II.
In Kesennuma, about 700 are confirmed dead and about 1,400 are still missing, according to city officials.
About 600 members of the Self Defence Force continue to search for bodies.
"It is impossible for us to remove the mass of rubble by just manpower, so we have to use heavy equipment but must do it very carefully. We are trying to retrieve bodies as cleanly as possible," Colonel Toshiki Fujioka, Regimental commander said.
The earthquake and tsunami flattened communities along hundreds of miles (kilometres) of coastline, causing what the government estimates could be as much as 310 (b) billion US dollars in damage. 
More than 158-thousand people are still without electricity and 210-thousand have no running water, although some of that is because of a 7.1-magnitude aftershock that rattled the area last week.
Adding to the misery is radiation spewing from the Fukushima Dai-ichi nuclear complex 140 miles (220 kilometres) northeast of Tokyo, which lost its cooling systems when water from the tsunami washed over it.
Government officials have already ordered the 70-thousand to 80-thousand people who live within 12 miles (120 kilometres) to leave.
On Monday Japan's government said it is urging even more people to evacuate the area with Chief Cabinet Secretary saying that residents of five additional communities, some more than 20 miles (30 kilometres) from the plant, are being urged to leave within a month.
He said it's not an emergency, but that high radiation levels have been detected in some places and there are concerns about long-term health risks as the crisis drags on.
Meanwhile workers at Fukushima Dai-ichi continue to struggle to remove contaminated water that has prevented them from restoring cooling systems. 


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/b2a2ec304778f0b847f53eca0a0c997c 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

10. Various shot of damaged car being loaded onto truck
11. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Kanno Hiroki, Volunteer Firefighter:
" When we first got here, we found around 200 bodies, all together in one group " 
12. Mid shot of Japanese police carrying stretcher
13. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Kanno Hiroki, Volunteer Firefighter:
" Maybe a lot of people we found... just didn't think the wave could reach this far " 
14. Mid shot of Japanese police with stretcher 
STORYLINE
Police, soldiers and volunteer recovery workers in the devastated town of Rikuzentakata in northern Japan, continue the grim task of clearing the debris caused by the March 11 earthquake and tsunami. 
They say around two hundred bodies have been found in the area so far.
Recovery workers say they hope to find more bodies, by moving huge piles of debris using mechanical diggers, and sifting through the rubble by hand.
The tsunami and the magnitude 9.0 earthquake that triggered it has claimed at least 11,578 lives in 12 Japanese prefectures and has left at least 16,451 people officially unaccounted for as of Friday morning.
Many of those who remain missing are believed to have been carried offshore after the tsunami struck the Pacific coast following the quake, which occurred off northeastern Japan.
The Japanese Self Defence Forces (SDF) and US military have started a three-day intensive search for those still missing.

items.title: Tsunami aftermath showing homes, businesses completely destroyed
items.description:
SHOTLIST
++QUALITY AS INCOMING++
Japan Earthquake
1. Pan of destruction
2. Various of damaged cars and debris
3. Wide of cars piled up in front of house, zoom in
4. Various of houses and debris
5. Pan of damage
6. Various of damaged cars and debris
STORYLINE:
The aftermath of Friday's earthquake and tsunami was all too clear on Sunday the the town of Iwaki, where the streets were littered with destroyed vehicles and buildings.
Residents were leaving due to concerns over dwindling food and fuel supplies. 
The town had no electricity and all stores were closed. 
Local police took in about 90 people and gave them blankets and rice balls but there was no sign of government or military aid trucks.
So far the estimated death toll has climbed past 10,000 and authorities have raced to combat the threat of multiple nuclear reactor meltdowns and hundreds of thousands of people struggled to find food and water. 
Prime Minister Naoto Kan said it was the nation's worst crisis since World War II.

items.title: US teachers talk about being caught up in tsunami nightmare
items.description:
Japan Earthquake
1. Wide top shot of devastated area of Minamisanriku 
2. Various top shots of damaged buildings and debris 
3. Wide of American teachers Mary Caitlin Churchill and Canon Purdy 
4. Mid of Churchill 
5. Wide top shot of devastation 
6. SOUNDBITE: (English) Mary Caitlin Churchill, 22-year old school teacher from Boston, Massachusetts: 
"It didn't quite feel real at that time, It was like 'I don't want to die, I don't want to die', it was kind of just 'run for your life' sort of moment, which I never really thought I'd have to deal with. It was still terrifying once we got to the top, we didn't know if more water was going to come, if there was going to be another tsunami, so we were kind at the highest point that we could get, so the whole evening was kind of terrifying, not knowing if we were high enough."
7. Wide of Churchill and Purdy 
8. Exterior of Shizugawa Junior High School, which was used as evacuation centre on hilltop when tsunami hit 
9. Wide of Churchill and Purdy in front of evacuation centre 
10. SOUNDBITE: (English) Canon Purdy, 25-year old teacher from San Francisco, California: 
"It, I mean, I wish I had a picture of what it used to look like as a beautiful healthy town. It was probably the most devastating thing I've ever seen, and I didn't lose my home, I didn't possibly lose a family member. So it was just overwhelming and I think everyone was so shocked and just couldn't believe what had happened."
11. Wide top shot of devastation and debris at Minamisanriku 
STORYLINE:
Mary Caitlin Churchill is a school teacher in Minamisanriku. She was in a school when the earthquake hit last Friday. She was in the teacher's room, with colleagues, when there was a tsunami warning, and they went out on the field. 
They thought they were safe at the field, but when they saw the water rising and going up the school, they had to run to higher ground, up in the mountains, behind the school. 
When she was in the mountains, she saw water filling up the fields, cars were floating, car alarms were going off, and the gym next to school was completely destroyed. 
She spent the rest of the day mostly in shock, but also tried to comfort elementary students terrified of what was happening to their home town. 
"It was still terrifying once we got to the top," Churchill said and she went on: "we didn't know if more water was going to come, if there was going to be another tsunami, so we were kind at the highest point that we could get." 
Canon Purdy was in Minamisanriku to attend a graduation ceremony for some of her former students at Shizugawa Junior High School. 
The school was located on top of a hill and is being used as an evacuation centre whenever a tsunami warning is raised. 
She was in the school when the quake hit. The students went out to the school grounds, and people started coming from the town. They all stayed in the gym.  
Twenty minutes after the warning, she came out to see what was happening and the valley where the town was located had already filled with water. 
She said she was overwhelmed by the experience, which seemed unreal. She never expected to see something like that. Everyone in the gym was shocked, people were worried, but people also immediately tried to get help. 
"It was probably the most devastating thing I've ever seen, and I didn't lose my home, I didn't possibly lose a family member. So it was just overwhelming," Purdy said. 
In Minamisanriku, 10-thousand people are still missing, according to a government spokesman. That is nearly two-thirds of the population.

In Minamisanriku, 10-thousand people have not been heard from since the tsunami wiped it out, according to a government spokesman.

The death toll from last week's earthquake and tsunami jumped on Tuesday as police confirmed the number killed had topped 2,400, though that grim news was overshadowed by a deepening nuclear crisis.

items.title: Survivors begin cleaning up damaged homes following tsunami
items.description:
SHOTLIST :
Japan Earthquake
1. Police checking damaged cars
2. Tilt up of police cleaning debris under damaged cars
3. Local resident pushing wheelbarrow with debris, UPSOUND: (Japanese) "Would someone help me to clean up my house?"
4. Wide of other damaged cars
5. Pan of house damaged by tsunami with debris outside
6. President of private elementary school, Mr Koyanaki, pointing at his damaged school
7. Close of broken door
8. Debris inside the private school
9. SOUNDBITE: (English) Mr Koyanaki, president of private elementary school:
"Waves come, with all people took shelter the third floor."
10. Pan of local residents cleaning up their flooded house
11. Close of debris, shovel pushing debris
12. Wide of cars driving by a damaged car
STORYLINE: 
Local residents in the city of Iwaki were clearing away debris on Sunday, following a devastating tsunami that was unleashed by Japan's biggest recorded earthquake.
The magnitude-8.9 offshore quake triggered a 23-foot (seven-metre) tsunami and was followed for hours by more than 50 aftershocks, many of them more than magnitude 6.0. 
The powerful tsunami also caused an explosion at one of the country's many nuclear reactors.
The explosion at the nuclear plant, Fukushima Dai-ichi, 170 miles (274 kilometres) northeast of Tokyo, appeared to be a consequence of steps taken to prevent a meltdown after the quake and tsunami knocked out power to the plant, crippling the system used to cool fuel rods there.
The Japanese government said radiation emanating from the plant appeared to have decreased after Saturday's blast,
which produced a cloud of white smoke that obscured the complex. But the danger was grave enough that officials pumped seawater into the reactor to avoid disaster and moved 170,000 people from the area.
Japan's nuclear safety agency then reported an emergency at another reactor unit, the third in the complex to have its cooling systems malfunction.
Meanwhile teams searched for the missing along hundreds of miles (kilometres) of the Japanese coast, and thousands of hungry
survivors huddled in darkened emergency centres that were cut off from rescuers and aid. 
At least a million households had gone without water since the quake struck.  Large areas of the countryside were surrounded by water and unreachable.
The government said 642 people were missing and 1,426 injured.  But there were grim signs that the death toll could soar. One report said no one could find four whole trains.  Others said 9,500 people in one coastal town were unaccounted for and that at least 200 bodies had washed ashore elsewhere.

items.title: Temporary homes built to house those displaced by quake and tsunami
items.description:
SHOTLIST :
1. Wide pan from evacuation centre to construction site
2. Various of workers building prefabricated homes
3. Close up of builder on construction site 
4. Set up of construction manager, Tsutomu Nakai looking at map
5. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Tsutomu Nakai, Construction manager :
"The day before yesterday, on 19 March, at Rikuzentakata municipal junior high school, we started the construction of the housing and we plan to build one hundred and thirty six homes. Now it's the first stage so only thirty six homes will be built. We hope to complete the first stage by the end of March and in early April thirty six families will move into the houses."
6. Wide pan of people in evacuation centre
7. People, including evacuee Akiko Oikawa, in centre
8. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Akiko Oikawa, Evacuee :
"I think it will be difficult for us to move into the housing in early April but if the situation permits we'll move later and we'll have some privacy."
9. Akiko and family in evacuation centre
STORYLINE:
Construction of temporary housing has begun in Rikuzentakata, a coastal city which was severely damaged by last week's devastating earthquake and tsunami in which thousands of people were killed.
The 30 square metre (215 square feet) prefabricated houses, capable of accommodating two to three people, were being built in the grounds of a junior high school.
The port city of Rikuzentakata, was home to 20-thousand people before the disaster.  Now most of them have left the area or are staying in evacuations centres.
The construction site for the temporary housing is next to one of the area's largest evacuation centres.
Construction manager Tsutomu Nakai said they were building the first phase of housing and hoped it would be ready in April.
Evacuee Akiko Oikawa said she would be surprised if the housing was ready by then.
"I think it will be difficult for us to move into the housing in early April but if the situation permits we'll move later and we'll have some privacy," she said.
Japan is continuing to grapple with the overwhelming consequences of the cascade of disasters caused by a 9.0-magnitude earthquake on March 11.
The quake caused the tsunami which ravaged Japan's northeastern coast and also damaged the Fukushima Dai-ichi nuclear plant, which has since been leaking radiation.

items.title: Mass grave prepared for bodies of disaster victims
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Soldiers carrying coffin to mass grave, outskirt of Higashi Matsushima City
2. Soldiers putting down coffin 
3. Relatives praying beside mass grave
4. Close of woman weeping
5. Soldiers carrying coffin 
6. Wide of relatives standing next to coffins
7. Close of flower being placed on dead body
8. Woman crying
9. Pan interior of Higashi Matsushima city hall
10. Officials working
11. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Takashi Takayama, 55 years old official:
"We have to get permission form the relatives before we send the dead victim to the mass grave."  
12. Wide of family members burying the victims
13. Close of coffin being buried
14. Woman burying her dead relative while crying
15. Low angle shot of soldiers carrying coffin 
STORYLINE
Relatives gathered to bury their loved ones during a burial ceremony at a mass grave in the outskirt of Higashi Matsushima city on Tuesday.
Hundreds of dead have washed ashore on Japan's devastated northeast coast since the earthquake and tsunami struck Japan earlier this month. 
Others were dug out of the debris earlier by firefighters using pickaxes and chain saws.
Funeral homes and crematoriums are overwhelmed, and officials have run out of body bags and coffins.
The tsunami triggered by the powerful earthquake on March 11 has killed 658 people and left more than 1000 people missing in Higashi Matsushima city in Miyagi prefecture.
Local city official Takashi Takayama said half of the city was flooded and they were trying to deal with the shortage of water, electricity and fuel.
Miyagi prefecture bore the full force of Friday's tsunami, and police has said several bodies were found scattered across its coast. 
In Miyagi, the police chief has estimated 10,000 deaths in his province alone.
Most Japanese opt to cremate their dead, and with so many bodies, the government has waived a rule requiring permission first from local authorities before cremation or burial to speed up funerals, according to a Health Ministry official.
But the permission from the victim's family is required before they send the bodies to the mass grave. 
According to Takayama, the city of Higashi Matsushima has only one crematorium that can handle a limited number of bodies a day.
The city government plans to hold burial ceremony four times a day and they have helped to bury 22 dead victims on Tuesday.

items.title: Doctors battle shortages in evacuation centre clinic
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Pan shot from Japanese Red Cross car to Japanese Red Cross Clinic
2. Close-up of medical staff working in clinic seen through window
3. Mid of sign for clinic in corridor with medical worker wearing face mask and patients in background
4. Tracking shot of patient Tetsuro Murakuni, being examined by doctor
5. Tilt up from chart to doctor's face
6. Pan from medical staff to doctor talking to Murakuni
7. SOUNDBITE: (Japanese) Tetsuro Murakuni, 73, patient:
"This clinic is very helpful for me. I don't have gasoline, roads are closed because of debris. It's really helped me." 
8. Various of medicine on shelf
9. Medium of nurses working
10. Close-up of nurses' hands
11. SOUNDBITE: (Japanese) Dr. Usui Tomomichi, 46, doctor at the Morioka Red Cross Hospital:
"It has been one week since the big earthquake hit the area. The situation here is calming down. The biggest problem here is shortage of medicine. The confusion among patients is calming down, because seriously injured patients are sent to big hospitals. The main mission of the clinic is to give regular medication to our patients." 
12. Cutaway of medical staff
13. SOUNDBITE (Japanese): Dr. Usui Tomomichi, 46, doctor at the Morioka Red Cross Hospital:
"I think numbers of patients with mental illness will increase from now on. They've lost their house, they've lost their family members, and they survived somehow. But they'll think how am I going to live from now on? What has happened to my goals for the future?' They will wonder, 'What's the purpose of my life?'" 
14. Wide of vehicles outside evacuation centre which houses the clinic
STORYLINE
A clinic in the northeastern Japanese city of Rikuzentakata was full to bursting point on Saturday with patients who need medicine, but that medicine was in short supply. 
The clinic has been set up by the Japanese Red Cross to treat survivors of last week's devastating earthquake and tsunami in which an estimated more than 10-thousand people were killed.
The port city of Rikuzentakata, was home to 20-thousand people before the disaster.
Tetsuro Murakuni, 73, said the clinic has been his lifeline.
He needs daily medicine for high blood pressure, but the tsunami ruined most of his supply. 
Murakuni could not drive to the hospital as there was no gas for his car, and even if there had been, the piles of debris clogging the road would make the journey impossible.
"This clinic is very helpful for me," he said. 
Transportation between Tokyo and the tsunami zone has been disrupted, meaning supplies aren't getting to those in need fast enough.
There are two shelves stocked with various boxes of pills, and two suitcases filled with gauze, syringes and bandages. But there is hardly enough to meet demand.
"The biggest problem here is shortage of medicine," said Dr. Usui Tomomichi, from the Morioka Red Cross Hospital. 
Tomomichi said it is not just the patients' physical health that is suffering, it is their mental health as well. 
Doctors are beginning to see a rise in both depression and anxiety.
"They've lost their house, they've lost their family members, and they survived somehow," said Tomomichi. 
"But they'll think how am I going to live from now on? What has happened to my goals for the future?' They will wonder, 'What's the purpose of my life?'" 
Japan is continuing to grapple with overwhelming consequences of the cascade of disasters caused by a 9.0-magnitude earthquake on March 11.
The quake caused a tsunami that ravaged Japan's northeastern coast, killing more than 7,200 people and knocking out backup cooling systems at a nuclear plant in Fukushima, which has been leaking radiation.

items.title: Fishing boat which became symbol of 2011 tsunami to be dismantled
items.description:
A symbolic landmark of the Japan's devastating tsunami - a 360-ton (330 metric ton) ship stranded inland - was shown to the media on Saturday for one last time before it is completely dismantled.
In March 2011, a magnitude 9.0 earthquake offshore of northeastern Japan, and the ensuing tsunami, killed more than 18-thousand people and devastated the coastline for hundreds of miles (kilometres).
The destruction caused by the tsunami came to be symbolised in a handful of iconic landmarks - including the 60 metre-long and 360-ton fishing vessel, the "No.18 Kyotokumaru." 
Workers began dismantling the stranded fishing boat early last month after a citywide vote showed the majority of the residents voted to have the ship destroyed.
A non-profit organisation based in Hokkaido was contracted for the dismantling process. 
Kazumichi Shimizu, Professor at the Muroran Institute of Technology who heads the non-profit organisation, said the dismantling process had taken longer than expected, but was nearly done.
"Within a week, most of the dismantling will be complete," he said.
Shimizu said the biggest task was to separate the large amounts of foam material used for padding in the ship's water tanks, from the scrap metal. 
This will need to be done by hand.
Workers began the dismantling process last month by first pumping out fuel and oil from the ship, followed by the dismantling of the ship's wheelhouse on the upper deck, cabin interiors, and the engine room, using gas burners to tear the steel apart.
Currently, large construction cutters are being used to cut away the central section of the ship.
All this is done behind a 3-metre-high enclosure, built as a safety precaution and in consideration for local residents.
About 500 metric tons of scrap metal from the ship will be recycled for various uses within Japan including vehicle parts, Shimizu said.
The dismantling comes after much debate among the city's residents and government officials over the fate of the "Kyotokumaru."
Kesennuma's mayor spent the last two years urging the ship's owners to allow the city to keep the vessel as a memorial for the devastation caused by the tsunami, but neither the ship's owner, nor many of the city's residents agreed.
Opinion on the ship had been so divided it had been put to a vote by the city residents in July. 
Of the 14,083 responses, 68 per cent, or 9,622 people, voted to have the ship destroyed. 
Only 16 per cent voted to keep it.
In light of the results, in August the city announced the vessel would be torn down.
Toshiko Chiba, a 73-year-old resident of Kesennuma, had voted to keep the ship, saying the vessel could have served as a reminder for future generations.
"That tsunami brought such an enormous ship (inland), and so I wished that people could see the sheer strength (of the tsunami)," she said.
For now, she keeps a postcard of the "No.18 Kyotokumaru" at home.

items.title: Sunrise over Kesennuma, a city devastated by the quake and tsunami two years ago
items.description:
11 March 2013
1. Wide of sunrise over Kesennuma city, Miyagi prefecture 
2. Pan across flattened city, covered in snow, during sunrise 
3. Wide of stranded ship on land 
4. Low shot of flowers placed on ground near ship
5. Tilt up of remains of buildings 
6. Pull focus from plant to excavator in distance 
7. Wide of remains of buildings, excavator 
8. Pan across Koushirou Sato, Kesennuma resident, walking along snow-covered street
9. SOUNDBITE: (Japanese) Koushirou Sato, 85, Kesennuma resident:
"The size of the community is going to be much smaller, but people who have been working in the fishing industry, the businesses, they know how to do it best here, so I think they'll stay."
10. Various of Kenichi Oi, Kesennuma resident, taking photos in port area
11. SOUNDBITE: (Japanese) Kenichi Oi, 75, Kesennuma resident:
"It's scary living here. When there is an earthquake, it's scary, but I don't plan to go anywhere else. I want to give my very best, somehow, towards the reconstruction of the city."
FILE: 13 March 2011
12. Various aerial shots show damage across Kesennuma city 
FILE: 11 March 2011
13. Various of the moment the tsunami hit the shoreline, cars in water
14. Various of fires burning
STORYLINE:
As Japan marks the second anniversary of a devastating earthquake and tsunami, residents of one affected city have been reflecting on the scale and complexity of the recovery effort. 
The 11 March 2011 disasters, which were followed by a nuclear catastrophe, left more than 1,000 people dead in Kesennuma in Miyagi prefecture. 
On Monday, a thin blanket of snow covered vast swathes of land in the city where buildings once stood. 
More than 15,000 homes were either damaged or destroyed, forcing survivors to live in temporary accommodation further inland.
Despite the scale of devastation, some residents hope they will be able to move back and rebuild their community - one that made its living from the fishing industry. 
"The size of the community is going to be much smaller, but people who have been working in the fishing industry, the businesses, they know how to do it best here, so I think they'll stay," said resident Koushirou Sato.
Kenichi Oi, who was born in Kesennuma, runs a fishing company. 
The tsunami washed away his boats in 2011, but he has since bought two new vessels and hopes to get his business up and running once again.  
"I want to give my very best, somehow, towards the reconstruction of the city," he said. 
Across all affected areas, more than 300,000 people are still displaced and virtually no rebuilding has begun.
The government plans to spend 25 trillion yen (268 billion US dollars) for the entire reconstruction effort. 
However, less than half of the eight trillion yen (85.7 billion US dollars) allocated so far has been used.
Memorial services are planned on Monday in Tokyo along the battered northeastern coast to mark the moment the magnitude-9.0 quake struck.
It was the strongest recorded in Japan's history, unleashing the massive tsunami that killed a total of nearly 19,000 people.
Some 160,000 evacuees remain uncertain if they will ever be able to return to abandoned homes around the Fukushima Dai-ichi nuclear power plant, where rectors melted down after the tsunami.
On Monday, about 800 people plan to file a lawsuit against the government and utility owner demanding compensation and that all land and homes be restored to their state before 11 March, 2011.



You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/5b7007344c76a6262d64d9c6707a6c38 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: US Ambassador Caroline Kennedy inspects Fukushima plant
items.description:
The US Ambassador to Japan got a firsthand look inside the Japanese nuclear plant devastated by the 2011 earthquake and tsunami on Wednesday.
Caroline Kennedy toured the Fukushima Dai-ichi plant for about three hours, wearing a yellow helmet and a white protective suit with her last name emblazoned on it as she was shown around.
The plant was damaged beyond repair by the disaster in March 2011. 
Decommissioning the reactors is expected to take decades.
Kennedy expressed gratitude to those who continue to work at the plant and said the US "stand ready to help in any way we can."

items.title: Tsunami disaster - young apprentices help rebuild fisherman's ruined business ++REPLAY++
items.description:
LEADIN
The fishing industry in Northern Japan is still struggling with the challenges of recovering from the earthquake and tsunami disaster of 2011.
One fisherman has spent the last three years rebuilding his oyster farm.
Now, he's enlisted the help of a handful of young apprentices in the hope they'll bring some much-needed fresh blood to the industry.
STORYLINE
Like thousands of fishermen along the Pacific coastline of Northern Japan, oyster farmer Hiromitsu Itou lost his home, his fishing boats, and his farm of oysters to the tsunami of 2011.
With much of the distribution routes and fish markets still to be rebuilt, many fisheries are struggling to survive, 
But Itou is one of a small group of fishermen who are charting new paths with the hopes of expanding their business.
Having taken over his father's oyster farm in Ogatsu around a decade ago, Itou had just taken out a loan for new equipment when the quake hit.
With nothing remaining after the tsunami, he had to start his entire business from scratch, but he did so in a way unheard of in a small town known for passing the legacy of fishing down through generations.
Itou and a handful of business partners in the fishing industry formed their own company, and started selling straight to customers online and raising money through memberships.
The money raised meant some local fishermen could rebuild - and for Itou, an opportunity to expand his direct sales - a rarity in an industry which usually relies on a tradition of customs and rules.
"This year is the real deal, it's the make-it-or break-it year.  I think we do have the marketing power, but I want to expand on that and go head on," says Itou.
"Many people say we're in the phase of reconstruction, but we're really still in recovery phase - we're still far off from reconstructing. Real reconstruction will take 5 or 10 years, and then perhaps then, we may be able to look back and say "I'm glad I worked hard back then" - that's what reconstruction is."
To expand operations, Itou has enlisted the help of a handful of young city dwellers - one of them being his own nephew.
23-year-old Yuuki Miura had no plans to follow in his family's footsteps and was training to become a cook in Sendai city when the quake struck. 
The devastation prompted him to rethink his role in keeping the family business - he left his job just 8 months after the quake struck to join his uncle.
"When I was small, I lived with my grandfather and I grew up watching him work. But the tsunami came right after the business was handed over to his next generation - and so I thought, I have to help." says Miura.
The quake hasn't just brought one local youngster back into the industry, it's spurred a host of industry outsiders to get involved.
31-year-old Mitsuhiro Inoue worked as a forklift operator at a warehouse in Sendai city for more than 10 years, before an acquaintance introduced him to part-time fishery work - a position which turned full time last July.
Still less than a year into the job, he's hoping to do more.
"I'd like to try and haul the oysters myself - but I don't have a license yet, so all I can do is to get on the boat with them," he says.
28-year-old Sendai city native, Takayuki Yokota, was jobless when he met Itou at an oyster festival. 
A former baseball player, Yokota says he felt the younger generation had their part to play in sustaining the area's fishing industry.
He claims fishermen - like Itou - are often "stubborn" and not always the best at marketing when dealing directly with restaurant managers.
"I think we're right in the middle - in the sense that we can be a bridge between the wishes of fishermen and wishes of restaurants, and by doing so expand on marketing and find more clients," he says.

items.title: Tsunami disaster - young apprentices help rebuild fisherman's ruined business
items.description:
LEADIN
The fishing industry in Northern Japan is still struggling with the challenges of recovering from the earthquake and tsunami disaster of 2011.
One fisherman has spent the last three years rebuilding his oyster farm.
Now, he's enlisted the help of a handful of young apprentices in the hope they'll bring some much-needed fresh blood to the industry.
STORYLINE
Like thousands of fishermen along the Pacific coastline of Northern Japan, oyster farmer Hiromitsu Ito lost his home, his fishing boats, and his farm of oysters to the tsunami of 2011.
With much of the distribution routes and fish markets still to be rebuilt, many fisheries are struggling to survive, 
But Ito is one of a small group of fishermen who are charting new paths with the hopes of expanding their business.
Having taken over his father's oyster farm in Ogatsu around a decade ago, Ito had just taken out a loan for new equipment when the quake hit.
With nothing remaining after the tsunami, he had to start his entire business from scratch, but he did so in a way unheard of in a small town known for passing the legacy of fishing down through generations.
Ito and a handful of business partners in the fishing industry formed their own company, and started selling straight to customers online and raising money through memberships.
The money raised meant some local fishermen could rebuild - and for Ito, an opportunity to expand his direct sales - a rarity in an industry which usually relies on a tradition of customs and rules.
"This year is the real deal, it's the make-it-or break-it year.  I think we do have the marketing power, but I want to expand on that and go head on," says Ito.
"Many people say we're in the phase of reconstruction, but we're really still in recovery phase - we're still far off from reconstructing. Real reconstruction will take 5 or 10 years, and then perhaps then, we may be able to look back and say "I'm glad I worked hard back then" - that's what reconstruction is."
To expand operations, Ito has enlisted the help of a handful of young city dwellers - one of them being his own nephew.
23-year-old Yuuki Miura had no plans to follow in his family's footsteps and was training to become a cook in Sendai city when the quake struck. 
The devastation prompted him to rethink his role in keeping the family business - he left his job just 8 months after the quake struck to join his uncle.
"When I was small, I lived with my grandfather and I grew up watching him work. But the tsunami came right after the business was handed over to his next generation - and so I thought, I have to help." says Miura.
The quake hasn't just brought one local youngster back into the industry, it's spurred a host of industry outsiders to get involved.
31-year-old Mitsuhiro Inoue worked as a forklift operator at a warehouse in Sendai city for more than 10 years, before an acquaintance introduced him to part-time fishery work - a position which turned full time last July.
Still less than a year into the job, he's hoping to do more.
"I'd like to try and haul the oysters myself - but I don't have a license yet, so all I can do is to get on the boat with them," he says.
28-year-old Sendai city native, Takayuki Yokota, was jobless when he met Ito at an oyster festival. 
A former basketball player, Yokota says he felt the younger generation had their part to play in sustaining the area's fishing industry.
He claims fishermen - like Ito - are often "stubborn" and not always the best at marketing when dealing directly with restaurant managers.
"I think we're right in the middle - in the sense that we can be a bridge between the wishes of fishermen and wishes of restaurants, and by doing so expand on marketing and find more clients," he says.

items.title: Tsunami Ishinomaki-shi 石巻市 Japan 2011年3月11日 — Remastered
items.description: AS THE TSUNAMI HIT: People gather for safety atop the roof of the Ishinomaki Gas Company offices and nearby parking garages in Ishinomaki-shi 石巻市 Miyagi Prefecture, Japan on 2011年3月11日 — The tsunami hit under 30 minutes after a record breaking 9.0MW earthquake hit Northeastern Japan.

items.title: Tsunami Kuji-shi 久慈市 Miyagi, Japan 2011年3月11日 — Remastered
items.description: The official Japan Coast Guard 海上保安庁 video of the March 11, 2011 post 9.0MW earthquake tsunami making landfall striking Kuji City in Miyagi Prefecture, Japan at around 3:25 p.m. [JT]. The seismic events struck the Tōhoku Region on the Northeastern coastline of Japan. The earthquake was the largest in that nation’s written history. The video was released to the public in April 2011 by the Japan Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism that has oversight of the Coast Guard.

items.title: Tsunami Oirase-chō  おいらせ町 Japan 2011年3月11日 — Remastered
items.description: The March 11, 2011 tsunami arrived at 3:48 p.m. [JST] at Oirase, Aomori Prefecture, Japan. The port area was hit an hour, two minutes after the 9.0MW earthquake struck the Tōhoku Region on the Northeastern coastline of Japan. The videographer survived, one of the few who did in that location — on a tsunami evacuation ladder. The breakers in the town were more than 10 meters high.

items.title: Tsunami Sendai-shi 仙台市 宮城県 Miyagi, Japan 2011年3月11日 NHK Live — Remastered Video
items.description:
On Friday, March 11, 2011 at 2:46 p.m. (JST), a 9.0 magnitude earthquake struck Japan. It was located in the Pacific Ocean 231 miles northeast of Tokyo at a shallow depth of 15.2 miles. It was the largest and longest earthquake in Japan's recorded history. The earthquake caused the most damage in the Tōhoku Region hitting the Miyagi Prefecture the worst.

The earthquake causes a tsunami that started hitting Japan's Northeastern coast between 10 to 50 minutes after the primary shaker ended. The tsunami waves reached nearly 70 feet in some seaside cities and towns and destroyed major harbors and ports.

items.title: Tsunami Ōtsuchi-chō  大槌町 Iwate, Japan 2011年3月11日 — Remastered
items.description:
On Friday, March 11, 2011 at 2:46 p.m. (JST), a 9.0 magnitude earthquake struck Japan. It was located in the Pacific Ocean 231 miles northeast of Tokyo at a shallow depth of 15.2 miles. It was the largest and longest earthquake in Japan's recorded history. The earthquake caused the most damage in the Tōhoku Region.

The earthquake caused tsunami started hitting Japan's Northeastern coast between 10 to 90 minutes after the primary shaker ended. The tsunami waves reached nearly 70 feet in some seaside cities and towns. Many major harbors and ports, including their breakwaters and dikes, were destroyed entire.

Ōtsuchi-chō is a town located in Kamihei District, Iwate, Japan. Since 1973, the University of Tokyo has maintained a marine research laboratory in Ōtsuchi. It is now called the International Coastal Research Center (ICRC) and is managed by the Atmosphere and Ocean Research Institute of Japan.

items.description:
Kesennuma-shi 気仙沼市
Miyagi Prefecture, Japan
Kesennuma Bay
Ōkawa River
 2011年3月11日 

On Friday, March 11, 2011 at 2:46 p.m. (JST), a 9.0 magnitude earthquake struck Japan. It was located in the Pacific Ocean 231 miles northeast of Tokyo at a shallow depth of 15.2 miles. It was the largest and longest earthquake in Japan's recorded history. The earthquake caused the most damage in the Tōhoku Region on Honshu Island the worst.

The earthquake caused tsunami started hitting Japan's Northeastern coast between 10 to 90 minutes after the primary shaker ended. The tsunami waves reached nearly 70 feet in some seaside cities and towns. Many major harbors and ports, including their breakwaters and dikes, were destroyed entire.

After the tsunami fuel used by the fishing boats spilled from ruptured storage tanks and caught fire. The flames engulfed the tanks containing the fuel and burned tsunami debris floating on the not completely receded waters. The fires spread and burned for four days. Officials said as of April 22, 2011 the city had confirmed 837 deaths with 1,196 missing.

The island of Oshima and its 3,000 residents are included in the city Kesennuma city limits. Oshima was isolated after the tsunami due to damaged ferry connections.

2011年3月11日

On Friday, March 11, 2011 at 2:46 p.m. (JST), a 9.0 magnitude earthquake struck Japan. It was located in the Pacific Ocean 231 miles northeast of Tokyo at a shallow depth of 15.2 miles. It was the largest and longest earthquake in Japan's recorded history. The earthquake caused the worst damage in the Tōhoku Region on Honshu Island.

The video recording here was made by a teenage schoolgirl at 南三陸町 Minamisanriku-chō in Miyagi Prefecture 宮城県 from the hill where her school was located. Nearly 90 percent of Minamisanriku was destroyed by tsunami. The neighboring cities of Mesennuma and Ishinomaki in Miyagi were also greatly impacted by the tsunami.

The earthquake caused tsunami started hitting Japan's Northeastern coast between 10 to 90 minutes after the primary shaker ended. The tsunami waves reached nearly 70 feet in some seaside cities and towns. Many major harbors and ports, including their breakwaters and dikes, were destroyed entire.

items.title: 【駅トホ53】多賀城駅(仙石線)から末の松山へ-Tagajo【青春18きっぷ2015夏-2】
items.description:
震災の被害から完全復活！全線再開した仙石線の駅を途中下車。最初は多賀城駅です。
駅周辺には和歌の題材に使われた名所が数多くあるらしく、今回は末の松山や沖の井へ行ってみました。
----------------------------------------
Tagajo Station is located in Miyagi Prefecture in the Tohoku region .
When the Great East Japan Earthquake , tsunami flow back to Sunaoshi River near the station , the town was flooded .

items.title: 【駅トホ54】野蒜駅の旧駅舎(仙石線)2014年夏訪問-Nobiru【青春18きっぷ2015夏-3の1】
items.description:
青春18きっぷで仙石線巡り。多賀城駅の次に訪問したのは東名駅と野蒜駅なのですが、新駅舎をアップする前に2014年に訪問した
野蒜駅の旧駅舎を紹介します。復旧前に旧駅舎を見たことがきっかけで仙石線が気になり、2年連続で訪問しようと決めたので、流れ的に旧駅舎は先にご紹介したかったのです。
----------------------------------------
This video has been shooting the old station building of Nobiru Station . Nobiru Station was the base of the Okumatsushima tourism .
However , Nobiru Station received a serious damage by the Great East Japan Earthquake .
Currently , the old station building of Nobiru Station has been used as a resting place of citizens .

items.title: 【駅トホ55】新駅舎の東名～野蒜駅間を散策(仙石線)＆ラーメン-Nobiru【青春18きっぷ2015夏-3の2】
items.description:
前回の野蒜駅旧駅舎に引き続き、野蒜駅と東名駅の新駅舎です。2駅間では新たな町づくりが進んでいるみたいで駅前は絶賛開発工事中でした。
途中にラーメンが美味しいと有名な店があるそうなので、訪問。潮の香りがたっぷりのアサリラーメンを食べました。美味しかったです。
野蒜駅の新駅舎はまだまだ新築の香りがします。小高い丘の上にあるので、奥松島を見ることができました。キレイだったな。
----------------------------------------
I travel the Miyagi Prefecture . I walked between the Touna station and Nobiru Station .
Touna Station and Nobiru Station received a serious damage in the Great East Japan Earthquake of March 11, 2011 .
The old station building becomes unusable , now I have been using the new station building .
Currently , the previous is progressing land development new station building .

items.title: Massive 9.0 Earthquake and Japan Tsunami Iwate Prefecture March 11, 2011
items.description: I was visiting northern Japan as a volunteer for Ric O'Barry's Dolphin Project on March 11, 2011 when a record breaking 9.0 earthquake rocked the Japanese coast.   I was standing outside of my rented car when the quake initially struck and it was nearly impossible to remain standing, but over the next 3-minutes I was able to get back to the car to retrieve my camera and began documenting the shaking.  Without hesitation, I immediately sought a high point as a vertical shelter in case of a tsunami - that decision saved my life!  I documented the resulting tsunami from atop of a hill that overlooked Otsuchi Harbor.  This is a small percentage of the entire video that I recorded.

items.title: 【駅トホ56】石ノ森ワールド☆石巻駅(仙石線)-Ishinomaki【青春18きっぷ2015夏-4】
items.description:
石ノ森萬画館で有名な石巻駅は駅も町も石ノ森章太郎さんのキャラクターでいっぱい！
駅も町も可愛い感じになっています。宿泊のための下車だったので朝と夜しか散策の時間がとれず石ノ森萬画館は行けませんでした。
その代わり、朝から240段の階段をのぼって羽黒山鳥屋神社に参拝に行ってきました。
----------------------------------------
I visited Ishinomaki , Miyagi Prefecture .
Ishinomaki is famous as the land of the great cartoonist Shotaro Ishinomori of Shoen . 
Ishinomaki has received extensive damage in the Great East Japan Earthquake , now has regained vigor .

items.title: Unique Expedition Batu Tara Volcano July 2015 - Indonesia - Documentary report, Time-lapse
items.description:
Unique and intense #footage of the #volcano "#Batu Tara" (Burning Stone) on the island of Komba (Pulau Komba) in the #Indonesian #Flores Sea during a volcano expedition in #June and July of #2015. 

Among other things, the film presents striking images of #strombolian #eruptions emanating from the volcano during the day and the night, images of the #Milky Way, a glimpse into everyday life at the #base camp, and unique #time-lapse footage of the Batu Tara volcano.

One particular highlight of the #expedition was the opportunity to film a #pyroclastic #lava #flow which was triggered by an eruption of ash during which a piece of the# crater rim collapsed causing lava to race down the side of the volcano at around 150 km/h into the open #sea! This footage was taken in the early morning hours of July 3, 2015 at a distance of about 100 meters after focusing the camera in the crater for more than twelve hours.

Click on the following link to view the complete video: 

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TvYZqc9pPfc

All images contained in the video are property of Martin Siering.

© www.martinsieringphotography.de

To view more of my work, please visit my homepage:

www.martinsieringphotography.de


German:
Einzigartige und beindruckende Impressionen mit #dokumentarischen Hintergrund vom #Vulkan „Batu Tara“ (Brennender Stein) auf der Insel #Komba (#Pulau Komba) in der #Flores Sea – Indonesien während einer #Vulkan-Expedition im #Juni/Juli #2015

Unter anderem sind in dieser kurzen Reportage verblüffende Fotos von #strombolianische  #Eruptionen des #Vulkans am Tage und während der Nacht, von der #Milchstraße und dem #Alltag im #Basecamp, kurze #Video-Mitschnitte und noch bisher #einmalige #Zeitraffer-Aufnahmen vom #Batu #Tara Vulkan zu sehen!

Ein besonderes Highlight der #Expedition war die Gelegenheit einen #pyroklastischen Strom per Video von nahe festhalten zu können. 
Dieser wurde durch eine imposante #Asche-Eruption ausgelöst bei der ein Stück des #Kraterrandes einstürzte, raste anschließend mit ca. #150km/h die #Feuerrutsche hinunter und suchte sich seinen Weg über das offene #Meer! 
Nach mehr als 12 Stunden Wartezeit mit #Fokus auf den #Krater, entstand diese Aufnahme als eine der Letzten in den frühen #Morgenstunden des #3.Juli 2015. 
Die Entfernung betrug ca. #100-150m  von meinem Standpunkt aus.

Hier der #Link zum #Video zum kompletten #Video: 

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FLLZc1zKUt4
oder
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TvYZqc9pPfc

Alle Fotos, Zeitraffer und Videos wurden von mir, Martin Siering, angefertigt.

items.title: Two dead, houses burned as youths rampage, NZealand troops
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Various of burning house 
2. Man whose house has burned down crying
3. Man pulling out body of burnt animal from wreckage
4. Body of burnt pig
5. Body of burnt dog
6. Wide of scene 
7. Portuguese UN police arrive at scene 
8. UN police at site
9. Various of armed forces from New Zealand at scene 
10. Australian forces at scene with dog
11. Local residents talking to forces 
STORYLINE:
Hundreds of rampaging youths torched houses and clashed across East Timor on Thursday, leaving at least two people dead in violence sparked by the appointment of independence hero Xanana Gusmao as prime minister, the UN said.
Authorities fired tear gas and made at least 14 arrests as political rivals clashed in several parts of the country, including the capital Dili. 
Some wielded machetes, steel darts and bows, while others set fires to buildings, police and witnesses said. 
In one town near Dili, international peacekeepers "managed to control the situation, but the market was almost completely destroyed in the fighting," the UN said.
Two people were killed in violence in the central district of Ermera, the UN said, without providing further details. 
Dozens of houses were set ablaze in the town of Metinaro, 25 kilometres (15 miles) east of the capital, police said. 
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony that gained independence in 2002, descended into chaos last April when communal violence left 37 people dead and sent 155-thousand people fleeing their homes.
It is struggling to restore political stability amid extreme poverty and severe food shortages.
Unrest flared again on August 6, after three rounds of elections, when Gusmao was named the head of a new government. 
The move angered supporters of the former ruling party, Fretilin, which won most votes in a parliamentary poll in June.
Hundreds of homes, schools, aid agencies and offices were burned in the eastern districts of Viqueque and Baucau in recent weeks.
UN police are also investigating the alleged rape of girls at a Roman Catholic convent.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/a37da372246a879f03496f058cb7d7d0 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Rebels involved in attack on PM surrender, Ramos-Horta reax
items.description:
SHOTLIST

1. Wide of East Timor government building 
2. Australian soldiers guarding building
3. Australian Black Hawk helicopter flying over building
4. East Timor rebel leader Gastau Salsinha (wearing baseball hat), being escorted into building by military
5. Rebels in military fatigues waiting in room for president
6. Close up of rebels' faces
7. Soldiers bring in box for rebels to use to symbolically lay down their arms
8. Various of guns being handed over to soldiers and being placed in box
9. President Jose Ramos-Horta shaking hand with rebels
10. Rebel leader Gastau Salsinha symbolically handing over weapon to senior army officer
11. Guns placed into box
12. Wide shot of ceremony
13. Close up of Ramos-Horta
14. SOUNDBITE (English) Jose Ramos-Horta, East Timor's President:
"As an individual, I harbour no hatred, no desire of revenge towards anyone. The gentleman who shot me, I was unarmed, and he knew the efforts I did for two years, the attention I paid to them, always going up to the mountains, to the jungle looking for them, talking with them. He knows what I did to help them and still he shot me in cold blood on February 11. I wouldn't shoot a dog, a pig, just for the sake of it, for fun, let alone a human being. But as an individual, I forgive him. If today he is hungry, his family is hungry, has no clothing, no shelter, I'll give it to them. But as a head of state, I am saying he has to face justice."
15. Salsinha
16. Ramos-Horta shakes hands with rebels

STORYLINE

A dozen rebels accused in the February assassination attempt on East Timor's President Jose Ramos-Horta surrendered in the capital Dili on Tuesday, including the alleged gunman, who wept and kissed the president's
hand. 

Ramos-Horta also shed tears when the suspects were brought before reporters at the Presidential Palace. 

He welcomed their surrender, which ended a massive manhunt by East Timorese soldiers and international peacekeepers following the February 11 ambush that nearly killed the Nobel Peace Prize laureate.

In coordinated attacks on February 11, rebel soldiers ambushed both Ramos-Horta and Prime Minister Xanana Gusmao, who was unscathed. 

Ramos-Horta was shot twice in the torso in the attack, which took place near his residence.

The 12 men, suspected in both attacks and led by rebel commander Gastau Salsinha, surrendered to authorities
on Tuesday and handed over automatic weapons and thousands of rounds of ammunition, said army Lieutenant Fernando Gausege. 

The detainees were later brought to the Presidential Palace to meet Ramos-Horta, who returned to the country last week after recovering in an Australian hospital from the gunshot wounds.

"The gentleman who shot me, I was unarmed, and he knew the efforts I did for two years, the attention I paid to them, always going up to the mountains, to the jungle looking for them, talking with them. He knows what I did to help them and still he shot me in cold blood on February 11," Ramos-Horta said.

"I wouldn't shoot a dog, a pig, just for the sake of it, for fun, let alone a human being. But as an individual I forgive him. If today he is hungry, his family is hungry, has no clothing, no shelter, I'll give it to them. But as a head of state I am saying he has to face justice," he said.

The assassination attempts showed the continuing volatility of East Timor since it declared independence in 2002, following decades of harsh rule by Indonesia and a period of U.N. administration.

It is also plagued by regular clashes between government troops and hundreds of mutinous soldiers who said they face discrimination. 

Tens of thousands of people fled their homes and still live in squalid tent camps in the capital.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/0b65e571a0c18197aeae5e46cb5dbe95 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Powerful earthquake hits tourist islands, dozens injured
items.description:
1. Wide shot of a damaged roof, pull out to workers cleaning debris at local hospital
2. Mid shot of a damaged hospital
3. Close up shot of cracks on the road
4. Various shots of debris on the ground
5. Wide shot of a damaged roof of hospital
6. Wide shot of policemen at an emergency tent
7. Mid shot of temporary beds for quake victims
8. Various shots of a man injured on his head
9. Mid shot of a man with a broken arm
10. Close up shot of a broken arm
11. Wide shot of rescue workers
12. Close up shot of a damaged roof, pull out to emergency tents below
13. Close up shot of sign of "District Court of Amlapura", pull out to the damaged court building
14. Wide shot of a damaged court entrance
15. Various shots of debris on the court entrance
16. Close up shot of a hole on the wall
17. Various shots of damage inside courtroom
18. Close up shot of sign of "District Prosecutor Office of Amlapura," pull out to the damaged office
19. Various shots of damage inside prosecutor's office
20. Various shots of government officials inspecting damage

STORYLINE:
A powerful earthquake shook Indonesia's tourist islands of Bali and Lombok on Friday, injuring nearly 30 people and damaging dozens of buildings.

The undersea quake measuring 6.1 on the Richter scale struck shortly before dawn in the Straits of Lombok, about 30 kilometers (18 miles) off the east coast of Bali.

On Bali, at least seven people were injured as they ran in panic from their houses in the town of Karangasem.

The town's hospital was also damaged, and officials were setting up a tent in the grounds of the building to treat patients.

A police officer in Karangasem said «up to 100» homes, schools and places and worship may have been damaged, but declined to give precise figures. 

Both Bali and Lombok are popular with foreign tourists, but initial reports said the quake did no damage in areas frequented by holiday makers.

On Lombok, one elderly man died, apparently of shock as a result of the quake and at least 22 people were injured, including a 12-year-old boy whose legs were broken when a house fell on top of him.

items.title: Students clash with police during protest
items.description:
1. Police pushing students back at demonstration
2. United Nations (UN) vehicle stops and UN police get out of the vehicle 
3. Various of stand-off between riot police and students
4. Various of students shaking fence of parliament house building
5. Crowd running away from police as they chase them 
6. Stones being thrown
7. Police arresting students as they throw stones
8. Various of students throwing stones at police
9. Students chasing police
10. Policeman points gun at students
11. Policeman runs away
12. Policeman pushing students away
13. Students running down street throwing stones
14. UPSOUND: gunshot in the distance 
15. UN police and students in the street  
16. Motorbike on fire
17. Stand off between riot police and students
18. East Timorese president Xanana Gusmao walks out of building to cheering crowds

STORYLINE:

At least two people have been killed and several others injured in a second day of student rioting in the East Timorese capital Dili.

Witnesses said one of the dead was a 16-year-old student who had been shot in the head.

President Xanana Gusmao arrived at the scene of the riots on Wednesday, which were centred outside the National Police Headquarters, to try and restore order.  But the fighting carried on and he was escorted inside the building.

On Tuesday police fired tear gas to disperse about 500 high school students who had taken to the streets of the capital.

The protesters threw rocks at police and soldiers and set two motorcycles on fire in a soccer field near Dili's parliament building. 

The protests, the most bloody since the poverty-stricken country became independent, were sparked by the recent arrest of a student from a school in the city.  Police say the boy was suspected of gang violence.

East Timor became the world's newest nation in May after two years of UN administration following 24 years of violent Indonesian occupation.
