items.title: RCTI Nobel Prize winner Ramos-Horta sworn in as new PM
items.description:
1. Wide of East Timor's religious leaders waiting for Jose Ramos-Horta to be sworn in as new prime minister 
2. Zoom out Nobel Peace Prize winner Jose Ramos-Horta entering the room and greeting religious leaders
3. Horta greeting and sitting down 
4. Close of Horta 
5. Close of religious leaders
6. Wide of Mari Alkatiri, former prime minister, entering the room 
7. Close of Horta
8. Close of Alkatiri
9. Horta signing book and giving pen to Alkatiri 
10. SOUNDBITE (English) Jose Ramos-Horta, former Nobel Peace Prize winner and new prime minister of East Timor:
"We will work very hard, fast, with the system of the World Bank, to see how we can expedite the procurements and tender legislation and processes, so that the budget that is allocated for assisting development in the rural areas, assisting the poor, development of the infrastructures, all of that, can be expedited. We have only 9 month and we have a significant budget: 315 million."
11. Wide of journalists waiting by the exit 
STORYLINE
Nobel Peace Prize winner Jose Ramos-Horta was sworn in as East Timor's new prime minister on Monday, and pledged to end the violence that has wracked Asia's newest nation in recent months.
Ramos-Horta replaced Mari Alkatiri, who resigned last month after failing to stop the bloodshed and amid allegations he formed a hit squad to terrorise his political opponents.
"Assisting development in the rural areas, assisting the poor, development of the infrastructures," were some of the key priorities Ramos-Horta mentioned after his inauguration at the presidential palace.
He also stressed that the consolidation of security in Dile "Our immediate task is to consolidate the security in Dili was a priority in order to restore faith and hope.
Ramos-Horta did not mention the allegations against Alkatiri and said he would listen to his advice on governing the country, which remains desperately poor seven years after it voted to break from 24-years of Indonesian rule in U.N.-sponsored ballot.
Ramos-Horta, who won the Nobel prize in 1996 for his non-violent resistance to the Indonesian occupation, said the UN should have stayed in the country longer.
East Timor's crisis began in March when Alkatiri fired 600 soldiers, more than 40 percent of the country's army, after they went on strike complaining of discrimination. 
The decision triggered fighting between the security forces that later spilled over into gang warfare, looting and arson that left 30 people dead.
The recent violence was the worst to hit the country since 1999. Though it eased with the arrival of 2,700 foreign peacekeepers six weeks ago, isolated incidents still occur and some 150,000 people are living in camps, too scared
to return home.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/3594f6dacd6522cb217d3d6d5cdc8338 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Authorities set up identification centre for victims of missing plane
items.description:
January 4, 2007
1. Exterior of Disaster Victim Identification Centre
2. Close-up of sign reading: "South Sulawesi police - Disaster Victim Identification Centre"
3. Wide of police and relatives of the passengers of missing plane at the ID centre
4. Mid of relative of passenger writing
5. Close-up of same
6. Mid of police looking at papers
7. Close-up of papers with victim identification data
8. Mid of police working at desk
9. Mid of two photographs of passengers on table
January 5, 2007
10. Set up of Doctor Budyo Sulistyo, chief of Makassar disaster victim identification centre:
11. SOUNDBITE: (Indonesian) Doctor Budyo Sulistyo, chief of Makassar Disaster Victim Identification Centre:
"It is (important) to identify correctly because it is related to human beings and because the family have the right to bring home their missing relatives if found."
January 4, 2007
12. Wide of officer typing at computer
13. Close-up of screen showing photo of missing passenger
January 5, 2007
14. Various shots of identification papers that have already been processed
15. SOUNDBITE: (Indonesian) Doctor Budyo Sulistyo, chief of Makassar Disaster Victim Identification Centre:
"In this very limited time we hope that more specific data on the passengers can soon be obtained."
16. Various of relatives in hotel lobby waiting for more information about loved ones
STORYLINE
Indonesia's South Sulawesi police have set up a victim identification unit for relatives of the passengers on board an Adam Air flight which went missing on January 1.
Over the past two days, relatives have provided the centre in Makassar with photographs, medical and dental records, and any other information which may help identify their loved ones.
The centre has collected preliminary data for about 80 percent of the passengers.
"In this very limited time we hope that more specific data of the passengers can soon be obtained," said Doctor Budyo Sulistyo, chief of the Makassar Disaster Victim Identification Centre.
Indonesia's Adam Air Flight KI-574 had 102 people on board when it took off from Java island on January 1st for Manado on Sulawesi island.
An hour into a normally short inter-island hop, the pilot reported heavy winds, then the plane vanished, sparking a massive search.
A top aviation official said the plane did not issue distress signals.
The statement contradicted earlier reports and capped days of confusion.
On Tuesday, authorities wrongly claimed they had found the plane's wreckage and a dozen survivors, causing anguish among families of the plane's passengers, including an American man and his daughters.
Thousands of soldiers have been deployed to battle rugged jungle terrain while aircraft and ships searched for a fourth day on Friday for the Boeing 737 in a 28,000-square-mile (72,500-square-kilometre) area.
Indonesia's recent, rapid expansion of budget airlines has offered cheap flights around the country's thousands of islands, but has raised some safety concerns, since maintenance on the planes is reportedly poor.

items.title: Gunfire, foreign troops, FM comments on crisis
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Wide of crowd in front of rice warehouse
2. Various of East Timorese Foreign Minister Jose Ramos Horta amongst crowd
3. Cutaway of onlookers
4. SOUNDBITE (English) Jose Ramos Horta, East Timorese Foreign Minister:
"Be orderly and we tried to distribute. Of course some listen others don't. I told them night time was coming, better start walking home, we are not going to open this because I don't want anyone to get killed. We had a stampede."
5. Various of refugees gathered outside Dili airport
6. SOUNDBITE (English) Jose Ramos Horta, East Timorese Foreign Minister:
"The shelters are very precarious. Very serious problems in one shelter, with now maybe 20-thousand people. Sanitation conditions are horrendous. I was hoping I would go there today to try to walk half of them to the soccer stadium, and they would stay there."
7. Various of burning shop
8. Australian troops arriving at burning shop
9. Various of street with people running UPSOUND gunfire
10. Various of Malaysian troops on patrol
11. Portuguese special police forces arriving at airport
12. Various of Portuguese forces loading luggage into vehicles
STORYLINE
Rival gangs roamed the streets of East Timor's capital on Sunday, torching homes and battling with machetes in defiance of foreign peacekeepers
sent to quell violence that has plunged the fledgling country into chaos.
Tens of thousands of residents fled Dili or sought refuge in churches, embassies and at the airport, leaving much of the city deserted.
Hundreds of UN employees were evacuated. 
As the numbers swelled at makeshift camps, East Timor's Foreign Minister Jose Ramos Horta said one camp was now housing some 20-thousand people. 
"Sanitation conditions are horrendous," he said. 
Smoke billowed from several areas where attacks took place on Sunday.
Australian troops rumbled toward the sound of gunfire in tanks and armoured personnel carriers, but seemed to only briefly scatter combatants.
The week-long violence has killed at least 27 people, probably more, raising concerns that one of the world's youngest nations is plunging into a
civil war, seven years after its traumatic break for independence from Indonesia.
The unrest was triggered by the March firing of 600 disgruntled soldiers, nearly half the 1,400-member army, and is the most serious crisis East Timor has faced.
After staging deadly riots last month, the sacked troops fled the seaside capital, setting up positions in the surrounding hills and threatening
guerrilla war if they were not reinstated.
What began as a break within the armed forces has spilled over to the general population.
Four people were killed Sunday, one of them burned to death while he was trying to defend his home and the others shot, witnesses and hospital
officials said.
Around 2-thousand Australian troops were either on the ground or in transit to East Timor, the Australian defence department said on Sunday. 
Seven ships and four Black Hawk helicopters were also assisting the deployment, it said.
New Zealand, Malaysia and Portugal also sent smaller numbers of troops to help.
Impoverished East Timor, a Portuguese colony for about four centuries until it was occupied by Indonesia in 1976, has received (m) millions of dollars in international aid over the last seven years, much of it focused on building up the military.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/3626381a91780df6a76059bae560850b 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: EXCLUSIVE Files on prominent Indonesian defendants in 1999 massacres stolen
items.description:
1.  Men including Longuinhos Monteiro, East Timor's  Attorney General walking along outside offices 
2. Papers on floor pan to ransacked office
3. Filing cabinet with drawers left open
4. Photos and files being picked up from the office floor
5. Close-up of photos
5. SOUNDBITE (English): Longuinhos Monteiro, East Timor Attorney General:
"This is violence over here. This also is open ( indicating cabinet)."
6. Close-up  of criminal documents
7. SOUNDBITE (English): Longuinhos Monteiro, East Timor Attorney General:
"Around 12 - 15 percent of our files over there is missing. Some of these files, in this particular room, is also taken. Particularly I and my staff collect some of the indictment files, especially all the original files against General Wiranto, Adam Damiri and all the TNI (Indonesian Military) members who we found outside of this compound. We tried to collect those files, even some pages is broken (are torn)."
8. Tilt up showing opened and damaged filing cabinet
9. Open drawer with files in 
10. Computers on the floor
11. Files and tapes on the floor
12. Opened computer server 
13.  SOUNDBITE (English): Longuinhos Monteiro, East Timor Attorney General:
"We don't know if this is part of an arrangement or it just , you know, it just happens that people are coming and then try to see what it inside."
14. Close up of skull, being placed by Monteiro into plastic bag, pull out to wide
15. Open drawers
16. Photographs on the floor 
17. SOUNDBITE (English): Longuinhos Monteiro, East Timor Attorney General:
"In reality those ones who are not here (that are missing) are the important files against the TNI's high ranking officers."
18.  Attorney General at book case with files
19. Close up of names on folders
20. SOUNDBITE (English): Longuinhos Monteiro, East Timor Attorney General:
"Again that we have to re-write everything in our history - again. For me this is the second struggle."
21. Close of padlock
22. Door of office being locked
STORYLINE:
Looters ransacked the prosecutor's office of vast numbers of files in East Timor's capital Dilli on Tuesday as the country dumped it's defence minister and the government showed signs of further unravelling, leaving desperate residents scuffling over scarce food.
Mobs on Tuesday torched houses and ransacked government offices, including that of the attorney's general where they succeeded in breaking into the Serious Crimes Unit.
Files involving all of the most prominent Indonesian defendants in the 1999 massacres that followed the East Timor's bloody vote for independence, including former General Wiranto, were stolen, Attorney General Longuinhos Monteiro told the Associated Press.
General Wiranto, Indonesia's armed forces chief at the time,  was indicted by UN-backed prosecutors for rights abuses in East Timor, a charge he has consistently denied.
The Attorney General said at least 12 percent of East Timor's entire criminal archive has been taken.
The stolen material included files, forensic evidence and computer backups, he said. 
Asked if massacre files had been specifically targeted in the looting, Monteiro replied: "We don't know if this was part of an arrangement or just happened."
The Attorney General said he saw this latest incident as East Timor's second struggle.
"Again that we have to re-write everything in our history - again," said Monteiro.
The setback comes as a week-long crisis engulfing one of the world's and youngest and poorest countries shows little sign of easing.
At least 27 people were killed in the past week in the tension, spurred by a military rebellion, that has left the capital smouldering from arsonists' fires and hundreds of foreign troops sent to help have failed to secure the city against machete and torch-wielding mobs.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/84660d26eba7d803ec03d335d0cee9e9 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Outsted PM supporters rally, Gusmao TV address, violence
items.description:
SHOTLIST
AP Television
1. Wide of supporters of East Timor's ousted Prime Minister Mari Alkatiri arriving in Dili, armoured vehicle driving in front
2. Various of Alkatiri supporters travelling on trucks and buses, watched by soldiers
3. Various of supporters of East Timor's President Xanana Gusmao holding a banner reading 'Alkatiri Go To Hell'
RTTL - Non AP Television News material
4. SOUNDBITE: (Tetun) Xanana Gusmao, East Timor president:
"Today we all know that there is a demonstration taking place here. So I appeal to all the people to stay calm because demonstration is the right of all citizens."
AP Television 
5. Member of parliament Leandro Isac on hillside looking at Dili through binoculars  ++MUTE SHOT++
6. SOUNDBITE: (Indonesian) Leandro Isac, Member of Parliament:
"An election can open the way for these two groups (supporters of Alkatiri and Gusmao) to face each other through political means." 
7. Various of house on fire 
8. Australian soldiers arresting man on street 
STORYLINE
Thousands of supporters of East Timor's ousted Prime Minister Mari Alkatiri demonstrated in Dili on Thursday amid a huge security presence by foreign peacekeepers.
International troops in helicopters, armoured vehicles and on foot escorted a convoy of trucks and buses packed with protesters along a prearranged route through the East Timorese capital.
An estimated 3,000 people travelled to Dili, many from eastern districts of East Timor, to attend the rally.
The demonstrators shouted slogans in support of Alkatiri and his ruling Fretilin party. 
Alkatiri stepped down on Monday, bowing to pressure from protesters and East Timor's President Xanana Gusmao, who is revered for leading East Timor's resistance to Indonesian occupation until it broke away in 1999.
Some supporters of Gusmao also protested separately, holding a banner reading 'Alkatiri Go To Hell'.
In a televised statement, Gusmao said citizens had a right to protest but insisted that "calm" must prevail.
Many East Timorese say Alkatiri's dismissal of 600 disgruntled soldiers in March was to blame for street battles and gang warfare in Dili that left at least 30 people dead and sent 150,000 fleeing from their homes.
Alkatiri is also battling allegations he formed hit squads to silence his political enemies.
Earlier on Thursday, Gusmao announced early elections. 
Member of Parliament Leandro Isac welcomed the announcement saying it would give supporters of Alkatiri and Gusmao the opportunity to face each other through political means.
Gusmao has not said whether he intends to invite Alkatiri's party Fretilin to play a role in forming an interim government. 
As the country's largest party, it has the constitutional right to propose a successor to Alkatiri.

items.title: 6.3 earthquake hits southeast Indonesia near East Timor capital Dili
items.description:
Earthquake in Dili East Timor Magnitudo 6,3
The earthquake, at 12:44 p.m. local time on Wednesday, was centered on the coast of Alor Island, about 77 kilometers (48 miles) west-northwest of Dili, which is located on Timor Island. It struck about 14.3 kilometers (8.9 miles) deep, making it a relatively shallow earthquake, according to the United States Geological Survey (USGS).

Witnesses on the islands reported feeling the earthquake, but there was no immediate information about possible damage or casualties.

There was no threat of a tsunami as a result of Wednesday's earthquake, according to Indonesia's seismological agency, BMKG.

items.title: Bachelet visits quake zone, promises a 'return to normal as fast as we can do it'
items.description:
Chilean President Michelle Bachelet visited Arica on Wednesday, one of the cities closest to the epicentre of the earthquake that struck the north of the country on Tuesday night.
The 8.2 magnitude earthquake killed at least six people but caused surprisingly little damage.
At a news conference in Arica, Bachelet said she had marked Arica city, the Tarapaca region and Parinacota province as disaster zones which will allow the use of emergency funds for recovery efforts.
She said the disaster zone decree would  "continue for as long as necessary."
The quake was centered 61 miles (99 kilometres) northwest of Iquique, which is home to about 200,000 people.
About 2,500 homes were damaged in Alto Hospicio, a poor neighbourhood in the hills above Iquique.
Bachelet said issues with water, electricity and fuel supply had been resolved by as much as 90 percent in Iquique and Arica.
"We're going to continue to work in these different areas, water and electricity, so schools can get back to normal as fast as we can," she said.
A mandatory evacuation that lasted for 10 hours in Iquique and Arica has been lifted.
About 900,000 people were kept out of their homes along Chile's 2,500-mile (4,000 kilometre) coastline.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/c3cc146a2636b44176cdb8942a0d8a35 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: 7.8 aftershock rattles earthquake zone; renewed evacuations
items.description:
Chile's far northern coast was hit by a second powerful earthquake, a 7.8 magnitude aftershock late Wednesday night.
Chile's Emergency Office and navy issued a tsunami warning and ordered a precautionary evacuation of low-lying areas on the northern coast.
A mandatory evacuation that lasted for 10 hours in Iquique and Arica had been lifted, but the powerful aftershock could see many people spending another sleepless night away from their homes. 
"Between the earthquake that we had in Arica yesterday night and the same again (we're tired)," said one evacuee.
The aftershock caused buildings to shake and people to run out into the streets in the port of Iquique, one of the cities that saw damage from Tuesday night's quake. 
There were no immediate reports of new damage or injuries from the latest tremor, which was one of dozens that have followed the 8.2 quake.
The aftershock was felt across the border in southern Peru, where people in the cities of Tacna and Arequipa reportedly fled buildings in fear.

items.title: Earthquake is Extreme Test for Stanford-trained Nepalese EMTs
items.description:
When Stanford emergency medicine chief Paul Auerbach and the SEMPER team heard the news about a 7.8 magnitude earthquake in Nepal, they wanted to help. The team has responded to natural disasters in Haiti and the Philippines and those experiences have built a special expertise. But Nepal was a bit different: A team of Stanford emergency medicine physicians had been there to work with Nepalis to create the first Nepalese ambulance service. The recent earthquake was a proverbial trial by fire for the service, which remains the only functioning ambulance service in the country. In this video, Auerbach shares his observations—and his feelings about what he saw and the people of Nepal.

Discover more at:
www.stanfordhealthcare.org

items.title: San Francisco before and after Earthquake
items.description:
Unique historical pre-disaster and San Francisco earthquake aftermath footage.

The 1906 San Francisco earthquake struck the coast of Northern California at 5:12 a.m. on Wednesday, April 18. Devastating fires broke out in the city that lasted for several days. As a result, about 3,000 people died and over 80% of San Francisco was destroyed.

The earthquake and resulting fire are remembered as one of the worst natural disasters in the history of the United States alongside the Galveston Hurricane of 1900 and Hurricane Katrina in 2005. The death toll from the earthquake and resulting fire remains the greatest loss of life from a natural disaster in California's history. At the time, 375 deaths were reported. Partly because hundreds of fatalities in Chinatown went ignored and unrecorded, the total number of deaths is still uncertain today, and is estimated to be roughly 3,000 at minimum. Most of the deaths occurred in San Francisco itself, but 189 were reported elsewhere in the Bay Area; nearby cities, such as Santa Rosa and San Jose, also suffered severe damage. Between 227,000 and 300,000 people were left homeless out of a population of about 410,000; half of those who evacuated fled across the bay to Oakland and Berkeley. Newspapers described Golden Gate Park, the Presidio, the Panhandle and the beaches between Ingleside and North Beach as covered with makeshift tents. More than two years later, many of these refugee camps were still in operation.

SF Cable cars
Andrew Smith Hallidie tested the first cable car at 4 o'clock in the morning, August 2nd, 1873, on Clay Street, in San Francisco. His idea for a steam engine powered - cable driven - rail system was conceived in 1869, after witnessing horses being whipped while they struggled on the wet cobblestones to pull a horsecar up Jackson Street. Hallidie entered into a partnership to form the Clay Street Hill Railroad, which began construction of a cable line on Clay Street in May of 1873. The contract to operate on city streets stated the line must be operational by August 1st. They launched on the 2nd. Even though they were a day late the cable car trials received great approval. Clay Street Hill Railroad began public service on September 1st, 1873. It was a tremendous success. Clay Street Hill Railroad was the sole cable car company for 4 years. A former horsecar company, Sutter Street Railroad, developed its own version of Hallidie's patented system and began cable service in 1877, followed by California Street Cable Railroad -1878, Geary Street, Park & Ocean Railroad -1880, Presidio & Ferries Railroad -1882, Market Street Cable Railway -1883, Ferries & Cliff House Railway -1888, and Omnibus Railroad & Cable Company -1889.

All totaled San Francisco companies had lay down 53 miles of track stretching from the Ferry Building to the Presidio, to Golden Gate Park, to the Castro, to the Mission.
April 18, 1906, the Great Earthquake & Fire devastated the city.
By this time the electric streetcar, perfected in1888 by Frank Sprague, had become the vehicle of choice for city transit. It only required half the investment to build and maintain, could reach more areas and was quicker. The cable cars were still able to traverse the steep hills better, so some of the lines were rebuilt. However, as the streetcars improved, even those lines were in jeopardy.
  
Market street, before and after. Dramatic scenes. Horse driven carriages, cable tram. Ferry terminal building. Urban history. Victorian park. Powell-Hyde line turnaround. Friedel Klussmann Memorial Turnaround.

items.title: 6915A San Francisco: Scientists are worried by the threat of another earthquake
items.description:
6915/A: SAN FRANCISCO: WILL THE QUAKE COME?

San Francisco is situated on a major geological fault,
and over the past twelve months or so scientists have
become increasingly worried by the threat of another
earthquake of the same magnitude that destroyed the
city back in 1906.  One rather wild notion current in the
area at the moment is that the whole Californian
seaboard could just slide away into the Pacific.  The
scientists are a good deal less pessimistic than that,
but there does seem to be cause for concern.  We
visited San Francisco, and nearby Hollister, "earth
quake capital of the nation", and interviewed three
scientists:  Karl Steinbrugge, a world authority on
structural damage caused by earthquakes; Richard
Jahns, Dean of Stanford University School of Earth
Sciences; and Doctor Don Tocker of the Earth Movement
Laboratories in San Francisco.

items.title: Japan Tsunami 2011 - Tohoku Earthquake Shocking Video
items.description:
Japan Tsunami 2011 - Tohoku Earthquake Shocking Video

An erupting volcanic island that is expanding off Japan could trigger a tsunami if its freshly-formed lava slopes collapse into the sea, scientists say.

The small, but growing, island appeared last year and quickly engulfed the already-existing island of Nishinoshima, around 1000 kilometres south of Tokyo.

It now covers 1.26 square kilometres.

The island's craters are currently spewing out 200,000 cubic metres of lava every day - enough to fill 80 Olympic swimming pools - which is accumulating in its east, scientists said.

"If lava continues to mount on the eastern area, part of the island's slopes could collapse and cause a tsunami," warned Fukashi Maeno, assistant professor of the Earthquake Research Institute at the University of Tokyo.

He said a rockfall of 12 million cubic metres of lava would generate a one metre tsunami that could travel faster than a bullet train, hitting the island of Chichijima - 130kms away - in around 18 minutes, he said.

Chichijima, home to about 2000 people, is the largest island in the Ogasawara archipelago, a wild and remote chain that is administratively part of Tokyo.

"The ideal way to monitor and avoid a natural disaster is to set up a new tsunami and earthquake detection system near the island, but it's impossible for anyone to land on the island in the current situation," Maeno added.

An official from the Japan Meteorological Agency, which monitors earthquakes and tsunamis, said the agency is watching for any signs of anything untoward.

"We studied the simulation this morning, and we are thinking of consulting with earthquake prediction experts ... about the probability of this actually happening, and what kind of measures we would be able to take," he said.

Japan's northeast was ravaged by a huge tsunami in March 2011, when a massive undersea earthquake sent a wall of water barrelling into the northeast coast, killing more than 18,000 people and wrecking whole towns.

Link Video http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TmGm8PlHnXs

items.description:

San Francisco - 18 April 2006
6. Tolling of bells on anniversary of earthquake
7. SOUNDBITE: (English) Gavin Newson, San Francisco Mayor: 
"Do you have any early memories of the quake?"
8. SOUNDBITE: (English) Mildred Morganstein, Quake Survivor:
"No, just that it was the biggest shock and a great deal of misery going on. People moving, losing their homes, and people having to sleep in the park and away things. Not being able to get back in their homes where they could cook and sleep and things like that."
Library of Congress - Prelinger Archive - No re-use/re-sale without clearance
9. Black & white footage of armed guard standing at intersection in San Francisco after quake
POOL
San Francisco - 18 April 2006
10. Wailing of sirens at earthquake memorial
11. SOUNDBITE: (English) Joanne Hayes White, San Francisco Fire Chief:
"And really, what today is about, as we commemorate and celebrate and look to our future, we look to a bright future, we want to make sure we''re the most prepared city that we can be. And we need all of you in our community to take that responsibility to become personally prepared, personally prepared in your homes, with your families and pets as well as in your workplaces. We want to do all we can, and, as a city collectively, we can be very prepared."
Library of Congress - Prelinger Archive - No re-use/re-sale without clearance
12. Black & white footage of makeshift housing following earthquake
POOL
San Francisco - 18 April 2006
13. UPSOUND (English) Gavin Newson, San Francisco Mayor, interviewing quake survivor Norma Norwood: 
Newson: "Well, how old are you now?"
Norwood: "I''m 99. I''m a result of the earthquake."
Newson: "Now you''re talking. I don''t want to pry into anyone''s personal life, but, what do you mean about being a result of the earthquake?"
Norwood: "I was born, I was conceived and born in a tent in Golden Gate Park."
Library of Congress - Prelinger Archive - No re-use/re-sale without clearance
17. Black & white footage of ruins of San Francisco following earthquake
STORYLINE
Sirens wailed through the city before dawn in San Francisco on Tuesday marking the moment 100 years earlier when the Great Quake shattered the city, killing thousands as it levelled buildings and touched off fires that burned for days.
A handful of centenarians who survived that devastation joined hundreds of residents for a moment of silence and a memorial ceremony to remember one of the worst natural disasters in U.S. history.
Most of the city''s 400,000 residents were still in bed when the magnitude-7.8 earthquake struck at 5:12 a.m. on April 18, 1906.
The epicentre was a few miles (kilometres) offshore of the city, but it was felt as far away as Oregon and Nevada. 
From cracked chimneys, broken gas lines and toppled chemical tanks, fires broke out and swept across the city, burning for days. 
Ruptured water pipes left firefighters helpless, while families carrying what they could fled to parks that had become makeshift morgues.
One hundred eleven year old Mildred Morganstein remembers the hardships that befell her family and neighbours immediately following the quake.
But they disagree over whether people should love the city or leave it.

items.title: A look at how the earthquake has damaged the Napa Valley wine industry
items.description:
Businesses in California's wine capital mopped up thousands of dollars in high-end vintages on Monday, after an earthquake caused 1 billion US dollars in damage, according to official estimates.
In Napa Valley, two hotels and 12 wineries were still closed on Monday, as well as many of the businesses downtown, local officials said, amid a rush to get the tourist hotspot back in shape for the summer's final holiday weekend.
With the dust still settling from Sunday's magnitude-6.0 quake, centered near the city of Napa, government and tourism officials encouraged visitors to keep flocking to the charming towns, tasting rooms, restaurants and spas that drive the Napa Valley economy.
While cleanup will take time and broken water mains remained a problem, they said, the worst damage and disruption was confined to the city's downtown, where a post office, library and a 141-room hotel were among 150 homes and buildings deemed unsafe to occupy.
The strongest earthquake to hit the San Francisco Bay Area in a quarter of a century also caused several injuries, triggered fires that destroyed or damaged six mobile homes, and ruptured gas lines.



You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/a8b54d8ea576ce2eb5864535b135d42f 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Largest earthquake in 25 years hits the San Francisco Bay Area
items.description:
A large earthquake rolled through California's northern Bay Area early on Sunday, damaging some buildings, igniting fires, knocking out power to tens of thousands and sending residents running out of their homes in the darkness.
The 6.0-magnitude quake caused six significant fires, including at four mobile homes, according to a Napa Division Fire official.
The epicentre of the earthquake that struck Northern California, the strongest in the area in 25 years, was just six miles southwest of Napa, California, the centre of California's winemaking region.
The US Geological Survey (USGS) described the tremor as the largest earthquake to shake the Bay Area since the 6.9-magnitude Loma Prieta quake in 1989.
Several other smaller fires were reported and firefighting efforts were complicated by broken water mains.
Local residents counted the cost of the damage on Sunday.
"All my valuable stuff is in the bedroom so most of everything is gone," said 83-year-old Nola Rawlins whose mobile home was destroyed by fire.
Winemakers in California's storied Napa Valley woke up to thousands of broken bottles and barrels as a result of Sunday's earthquake.
The earthquake couldn't have come at a worse time for the region, which has just started harvesting the 2014 crop.



You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/c4741cd63ab6e99c0760fc342ff541fb

items.title: San Francisco earthquake Oakland  live report
items.description:
OAKLAND -- A magnitude-4.0 temblor that rattled nerves in the East Bay on Monday morning was a very shallow but routine geologic shrug in an area notorious for seismic risk -- and yet another reminder of the threat lurking from a fault that's the Bay Area's most overdue for a major quake.

A locked-up patch of rocks a mere 3 miles under Piedmont suddenly broke loose along the Hayward Fault, triggering a wake-up call felt from Santa Rosa to Santa Cruz.

"Because it was shallower than normal, people in the vicinity felt more intensified shaking than usual for an earthquake of this magnitude," said Keith Knudsen, deputy director of the Earthquake Science Center at the U.S. Geological Survey in Menlo Park.

 USGS Map
USGS Map
Monday's quake was the second magnitude-4.0 quake on the Hayward Fault in less than a month -- and comes almost a year after the magnitude-6.0 Napa temblor that was the region's biggest in 25 years -- but there is no indication it is a precursor of the Big One. While there was a flurry of aftershocks following Monday's 6:49 a.m. earthquake, there is only a 10 percent chance that it will be followed by a larger earthquake in the next week, Knudsen said.

items.title: earthquake raw video  British Columbia
items.description:
B.C.'s South Coast was hit by an earthquake that shook many people from their sleep just before midnight, in what one seismologist called the largest quake in the region in years.

Some people near the epicentre northeast of Victoria reported their homes shifted, and others were knocked off their feet.

"The house moved seriously to the right, came back, it was loud. The aquarium had a mini-tsunami and overflowed. We were in the kitchen and got tossed into the counter," wrote one commenter on the CBC website.

Many reported feeling a large impact that felt like a truck hitting their homes, while others in Metro Vancouver reported windows rattling and items on walls shaking.

"I'm about 6 km from the epicentre and it felt like a truck had crashed into my house," wrote another commenter.

"I felt it in the West End here of Vancouver and I looked out my window to see if a truck had hit the side of my building! It was quite a sharp jolt that made my walls bend and creak, but nothing really shook or swayed," wrote another.

Cihou Fort or Cihou Battery in Kaohsiung (Taiwan)
items.description:
Cihou Fort or Cihou Battery is a historic fort in Cijin District, Kaohsiung, formerly guarding northern entrance to Kaohsiung Harbor. 

First fortifications were built in 1720 (during Kangxi's reign and Qing rule). After Japanese expedition in 1874 Chinese authorities constructed a modern fort, which in 1880 had new Armstrong's guns installed. It played no part in the Sino-French War; the fighting in Taiwan took place around Keelung and during blockade French ships did not approach the port.

Taiwan was ceded to Japan according to the Treaty of Shimonoseki in the aftermath of the first Sino-Japanese war. The local troops, however, fought on. On 12 October 1895, escadre commanded by admiral Arichi Shinanojo (cruisers Yoshino, Naniwa, Akitsushima, Yaeyama, Saien (ex Chinese Jiyuan, captured in Weihaiwei) and corvette Hiei) arrived at Kaohsiung and prompted the foreigners to evacuate, as they would conduct the attack on the next day. The foreigners boarded gunboat HMS Tweed and two tugs and withdrew (only to return once the fight was over). At 7 am, 13 October, Japanese ships "opened fire on the Takow [Kaohsiung] forts at a range of about 6,000 yards. For the first half hour, the forts responded, but after this their guns were silent...The forts fired twenty four rounds, the best shot being from the 8-inch B.L. Armstrong guns in Apes' Hill fort, which struck the water about 500 yards from the Naniwa Kan." The Japanese troops seized the forts in early afternoon, suffering no casualties (4 Chinese soldiers were killed).

During the Japanese era the fort was not used.

After World War II the hill was fortified by Chinese army: light gun and machine gun nests cut in the rock can still be found there.

items.title: Taiwanese prepare to celebrate the Year of the Pig
items.description:
++DAY SHOTS++
1. Wide of crowds in dried food market
2. Mid of crowds in dried food market
3. Wide of stall selling dried squid
4. Mid of stall selling dried squid
5. Mid of people buying dried persimmon 
6. Close-up of dried persimmon 
7. Mid of booth selling smoked pork 
8. Close-up of smoked pork being cut 
9. Woman trying a piece of smoked pork 
10. Wide of stall selling sweets 
11. Close-up of sweets
12. Mid of various Chinese New Year decorations
13. Close-up of yellow pig decoration
14. Mid of paper pig decoration swinging 
15. Man shouting through mega phone
16. Close-up of fruits coated with red syrup 
17. Various of children trying the fruits 
18. Wide of stall selling roasted squid 
19. SOUNDBITE: (Mandarin) Mr Lin, Vox Pop: 
"Of course I hope business here goes well.  If everyone has good business and we have good business, then all of us can have a happy new year."
20. SOUNDBITE: (Mandarin) Mr Huang, Vox Pop: 
"It's cold in Chinese New Year. I am going to buy my dog a red coat so it looks cheerful."
++NIGHT SHOTS++
21. Wide of ancient vessel burning inside in front of temple 
22. Close-up of flame
++DAY SHOTS++
23. Wide of crowds inside flower market 
24. Wide of giant pig made of flowers 
25. Close-up of face of pig made of flowers 
26. Various of people buying flowers
27. SOUNDBITE: (Mandarin) Chang Chia-ming, Manager of flower market: 
"The year of the pig represents an agricultural and traditional atmosphere. So the theme of this year is to give an image of a wealthy and peaceful village by using peonies."
28. Various of crowds in flower market
29. Various of flowers
STORYLINE:
Taipei's markets were attracting large crowds ahead of Chinese New Year which starts on 18 February.
Market stalls were piled high with many different delicacies including dried squid, dried persimmon, smoked pork, and sweets wrapped in colourful papers.
2007 is the year of the pig and a variety of pig decorations and ornaments were also on sale at the markets.
"I hope the business here goes well. If everyone has good business and we have good business, then all of us can have a happy new year," said one vendor, Mr Lin.
One man looking at the brightly coloured markets stalls said he knew what he wanted to buy.
"It's cold in Chinese New Year. I am going to buy my dog a red coat so it looks cheerful," said Mr Huang.
The flower market was also popular as people in Taiwan counted down to the New Year.
Flowers are believed to be symbolic of wealth and high positions in one's career and every year families go to the flower market to hunt for the best new year flowers and plants.
It is traditional for Chinese families to put a blooming plant in their home at New Year and traditional holiday flowers include peach blossoms and orchids.
A three-metre (about ten foot) tall pig made from several thousand chrysanthemums was on display in the middle of the flower market to mark the start of the year of the pig.
The manager of flower market, Chang Chia-ming said the year of the pig represented "agricultural and traditional atmospheres".
The pig is the last of the 12 animals in the Chinese zodiac. Legend has it that the pig finished last in the race that determined the zodiac's order.
Despite losing the race, the pig symbolises good luck and that inspires many Chinese to have children during a pig year.
Chinese fortune tellers say pig years can be turbulent because they are dominated by fire and water, two of the five elements that Chinese mystics say are the basis of the universe.

items.title: Taiwan agrees to participate in Olympic torch relay, Chinese officials say
items.description:
1. Wide of billboard showing 2008 Olympic games countdown clock 
2. Various of billboard 
3. SOUNDBITE: (Mandarin) Wang Shu-hui, Democratic Progressive Party Legislator: 
"If the route is from Beijing to Taiwan then back to Beijing or other places, I think Beijing is using this time (during the Olympics) to publicise that Taiwan is one of China's provinces. That would undermine Taiwan as a (sovereign) country ." 
4. Various of street scenes 
5. SOUNDBITE: (Mandarin) Law, Taiwan Resident, Voxpop: 
"I think the torch (travelling from Beijing) to Taiwan, is good. At least this is a friendly (gesture by China and) breakthrough in terms of politics regarding two sides on the Taiwan Strait." 
6. Various street scenes
7. SOUNDBITE: (Mandarin) Huang, Taiwan Resident, Vox Pop: 
"There is no need to think too much (about this). Nowadays a lot of political matters are turned into a political show. It is just too much. This is not necessarily a political matter, it is a big sporting event." 
8. Various exteriors of National Council on Physical Fitness and Sports building
STORYLINE:
There was mixed reaction in Taipei on Tuesday to news that Taiwan has agreed to participate in the 2008 Beijing Olympic torch relay, despite political tensions with Beijing.
Wang Wei, vice president of the 2008 Beijing Olympic organising committee, told reporters in Beijing on Monday that both sides have agreed on terms allowing the Olympic torch to pass through Taiwan. 
He gave no further details, but said the torch relay route would be announced on Thursday. 
It is expected to be approved by the International Olympic Committee's executive board, which is meeting in Beijing this week.
The chairman of Taiwan's Mainland Affairs Council which handles policy toward China, declined to confirm the deal, saying the torch route was still under discussion. 
On Tuesday, Wang Shu-hui a Legislator for the Democratic Progressive Party told the Associated Press the Olympic torch route was an effort by Beijing to undermine Taiwan's sovereignty. 
"If the route is from Beijing to Taiwan then back to Beijing or other places, I think Beijing is using this time (during the Olympics) to publicise that Taiwan is one of China's provinces. That would undermine Taiwan as a (sovereign) country," said Wang.  
But public opinion in Taipei was divided. 
Some residents like, Law, saw the torch route as a "friendly (gesture by China and) breakthrough in terms of politics regarding two sides on the Taiwan Strait." 
While others resented the fact that the Olympics were being politicised. 
"There is no need to think too much (about this). Nowadays a lot of political matters are turned into a political show. It is just too much. This is not necessarily a political matter, it is a big sporting event," said Huang, another resident.  
Taiwan, a self-ruled island, is reported to have rejected a proposal under which the torch would enter Taiwan from Japan, South Korea or another Asian nation, and would depart to Hong Kong, which is part of China.
Reports suggest Taiwan may want the torch to enter and leave through two Asian nations - neither of them China.
Taiwan split from the mainland in 1949, although China still claims it is part of Chinese territory.
The torch route next year is also expected to reach the top of Mount Everest, although some environmentalists have opposed the trip through Tibet.
For China, the torch relay route could be used to underscore Chinese claims to Tibet - a Himalayan region under Beijing's control since 1950 - and Taiwan.

items.title: Taiwan celebrates national day with call for peace
items.description:
SHOTLIST
POOL
1. Wide top shot of celebration outside Taiwan's presidential office
AP TELEVISION
2. Aircraft performance in the sky 
3. Various of motorcade
POOL
4. Wide of presidential office 
5. Marching ban performing gun patterns
AP TELEVISION 
6. Taiwanese president, Ma Ying-jeou, walking to podium
7. Marching band 
8. SOUNDBITE (Mandarin) Ma Ying-jeou, Taiwanese president:
"We hope that the two sides can apply wisdom to shelve disputes and chart courses to steadily extend the political reconciliation achieved in cross-strait relations to the international arena. We hope to thereby eliminate unnecessary conflict and confrontation between the two sides in the international community, and create a win-win situation for Taiwan, mainland China, and the world community." 
9. Guests on stage 
10. SOUNDBITE (Mandarin) Ma Ying-jeou, Taiwanese president:
"In the course of exchanges between Taiwan and mainland China, this administration will surely uphold the principle of 'putting Taiwan first for the benefit of the people.' Taiwan's interests cannot be compromised, and the dignity of its people must be staunchly defended."
POOL 
11. Wide of presidential office and parade area
AP TELEVISION
12. Float parade on street 
13. Close-up of Ma waving 
14. Wide of float parade 
15. Woman dancing and waving feathers
STORYLINE
Taiwan substituted folk dancers for soldiers on Friday as President Ma Ying-jeou observed the island's National Day with calls for peace with rival China and courage in overcoming the global financial crisis.
Ma's remarks - delivered in front of the ornate presidential office building in perfect late-summer weather - contrasted with the martial tone of last year's National Day celebrations led by Chen Shui-bian, his pro-independence predecessor.
At Chen's insistence, Taiwan mounted a large-scale military parade - Taiwan's first on National Day since 1991 - using streaking jet fighters and modern armoured vehicles to underscore the island's readiness to beat back a possible invasion from China, from which it split amid civil war in 1949.
But this year the expansive presidential office plaza was dominated by folk dancers and acrobats, reflecting Ma's insistence that if his policies of seeking reconciliation with Beijing are carried out, an invasion will not occur.
Addressing a crowd of beaming dignitaries and an island-wide television audience, Ma said his efforts to alleviate tensions across the 100-mile (160 kilometre) wide Taiwan Strait would hopefully "create a win-win situation for Taiwan, mainland China, and the world community." 
Ma also addressed the growing international financial crisis, which constitutes a grave threat to Taiwan's export-based economy because it threatens reduced orders for Taiwanese goods from customers in North America, Europe and Asia.
Minimising the crisis' dangers, Ma said it offered the island a chance to further consolidate its democratic system and high-tech economic infrastructure.
Taiwan's national day, which follows China's by nine days, marks the 1911 Nationalist revolt that toppled the imperial Qing dynasty to establish China's first republic.
The Nationalists were later defeated by Communist forces in 1949 and driven to Taiwan.
Despite relief that Chen is out of office and a relatively sympathetic, anti-independence figure has replaced him, Chinese leaders still hew to their traditional position that Taiwan is part of the mainland.
Nor have they renounced their repeated threats to attack if Taiwan ever moves to make its 59-year break with the mainland permanent.

items.title: Former pres says new leader will 'tread carefully' in dealing with China
items.description:
1. Tilt down exterior of house of Lee Teng-hui, former president of Taiwan 
2. Close of Lee; tilt down to his hands 
3. Close of painting of Lee hung on wall
4. Wide of Lee being interviewed
5. Close of Lee's hand
6. Wide of Lee talking to reporters
7. SOUNDBITE: (Mandarin) Lee Teng-hui, former president of Taiwan: 
"Regarding the relation between (new Taiwanese President) Ma Ying-jeou and China, the relation between Taiwan and China, Ma hopes to maintain a peaceful environment. He doesn't want any disputes. It is because Taiwan suffered a big loss over the past eight years under the rule of Democratic Progressive Party." 
8. Wide of Lee talking to reporters 
9. SOUNDBITE: (Mandarin) Lee Teng-hui, former president of Taiwan: 
"My opinion on Hu Jintao is that he finds it is more important to settle the internal disturbance recently in China. It's not necessary to mention everyday that Taiwan is part of mainland China. He is very careful on this." 
10. Back shot of Lee talking to reporters 
11. Wide of Lee holding a plate of mango 
12. SOUNDBITE: (Mandarin) Lee Teng-hui, former president of Taiwan: 
"During the presidential election, Ma Ying-jeou received no big assistance from the Nationalist Party. He achieved this by himself. The Nationalist Party cannot order him to do anything. He won't say yes. The platform for talk between Taiwan and China cannot be conducted in two channels. It has to be one channel as it works better this way." 
13. Back shot of Lee talking to reporter 
14. Side shot of Lee being interviewed
15. Wide shot of Lee shaking hands with reporter


STORYLINE: 

Former Taiwanese President Lee Teng-hui said on Wednesday that the island's new leader will tread cautiously in dealing with rival China, despite pressure from some in his party to engage Beijing without delay.

Lee's comments came as Chairman Wu Poh-hsiung of Taiwan's ruling Nationalist Party was meeting in Beijing with Chinese President Hu Jintao.

The meeting heightened expectations that the new Taiwanese President Ma Ying-jeou might be ready to preside over a rapid improvement in political relations between the sides, which split amid civil war in 1949.

Ma took office last week.

But in an interview with The Associated Press at his Taipei home, Lee said Ma had the ability to withstand pressure from Nationalist hard-liners and would uphold his promise not to discuss unification during his presidency.

China still claims Taiwan as part of its territory, and has pledged to unify with the island of 23 million people - by force if necessary, by persuasion if possible.

"Regarding the relation between Ma Ying-jeou and China, the relation between Taiwan and China, Ma hopes to maintain a peaceful environment. He doesn't want any disputes. It is because Taiwan suffered a big loss over the past eight years under the rule of Democratic Progressive Party," Lee said.

He added that he didn't think Taiwan was an urgent priority for Chinese president Hu Jintao, who he believes is more focussed on dealing with internal issues such as the widespread Tibetan uprising in March and the recent earthquake in Sichuan province.

"My opinion on Hu Jintao is that he finds it is more important to settle the internal disturbance recently in China. It's not necessary to mention everyday that Taiwan is part of mainland China. He is very careful on this."

Discussing Wednesday's meeting in Beijing between Hu and Wu, Lee said progress between Taiwan and China could only come when they employ government-to-government contact, rather than meetings between representatives of their ruling parties.

"The platform for talk between Taiwan and China cannot be conducted in two channels. It has to be one channel as it works better this way," Lee said.

items.title: New president says Taiwan happy to share quake experience with China
items.description:
SHOTLIST

1. Arrival of Taiwan president Ma Ying-jeou at news conference
2. Cutaway of man taking photograph
3. Wide of news conference 
4. SOUNDBITE: (English) Ma Ying-jeou, Taiwan president: 
"Resume the negotiations between the two organisations that represent respectively mainland China and Taiwan; if we can do that, many issues, many problems could be solved over there. (Or) would gradually move to other areas. I think there is no haste for the leaders of the two sides of the Taiwan Strait to meet at this moment." 
5. Cutaway press 
6. SOUNDBITE: (English) Ma Ying-jeou, Taiwan president: 
"Now we are in power. So Mr Wu (Wu Poh-hsiung, Nationalist Party chairman) wants to resume the contact. I welcome that because the party-to-party contact could serve as a second track for cross-Strait relations." 
7. Cutaway cameraman 
8. SOUNDBITE: (English) Ma Ying-jeou, Taiwan president: 
"It is also in the interests of the Chinese mainland. If they continue to squeeze us, obviously the people of Taiwan will not have a positive image of the mainland." 
9. Cutaway press 
10. SOUNDBITE: (English) Ma Ying-jeou, Taiwan president: 
"We actually learnt the lesson nine years ago when we have also a devastating earthquake on September 21, so we will be very happy to share our experiences with our mainland counterpart." 
11. Pan of venue, Ma leaving

STORYLINE:

There is no haste for the leaders of Taiwan and mainland China to meet at the moment, said the new president of Taiwan in a press conference on Wednesday to the foreign media in Taiwan's capital, Taipei. 

Ma Ying-jeou, who was a Nationalist Party chairman before he took office as Taiwan's president on Tuesday, reiterated his position that there is no urgency to meet the Chinese leader Hu Jintao at this stage.

"Resume the negotiations between the two organisations that represent respectively mainland China and Taiwan; if we can do that, many issues, many problems can be solved over there. (Or) would gradually move to other areas," said Ma, referring to Taiwan's Strait Exchange Foundation (SEF) and China's Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS).

The Straits Exchange Foundation is a quasi-governmental body that has held talks in the past with a Chinese counterpart. 

The recent visit of SEF chairman Chiang Pin-kung and the coming visit of the Nationalist Party chairman Wu Poh-hsiung, have raised expectations of a resumption of dialogue between the foundation and China's ARATS, after a decade-long break during the presidency of Chen Shui-bian.

"Now we are in power. So Mr Wu (Wu Poh-hsiung, Nationalist Party chairman) wants to resume the contact. I welcome that because the party-to-party contact could serve as a second track for cross-Strait relations," said Ma. 

China already has started pursuing relations with Ma's party. 

Late last month, Hu met with Lien Chan, honorary chairman of the party, in Beijing and talked of "laying aside disputes." 

A visit by Lien in 2005 was the first by a Nationalist Party chairman since the Nationalists fled the mainland in 1949.

Ma emphasised that he urges Beijing to seek reconciliation with Taiwan in "the international arena" - a clear reference to the often costly competition to win diplomatic recognition from countries around the world.

"It is also in an interest of the Chinese mainland. If they continue to squeeze us, obviously the people of Taiwan will not have a positive image of the mainland," Ma said at the news conference. 

Meanwhile, Ma praised mainland China for its transparency in handling the Sichuan earthquake and said Taiwan would share its experience from an earthquake which hit Taiwan in 1999.




You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/9d9f2db6ea3b0987b8085a4593283eb0 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Taiwan pres says 'difficult to see unification talks in our lifetimes' in AP int
items.description:
SHOTLIST

1. Incoming Taiwanese President Ma Ying Jeo in interview with Associated Press (AP) 
2. Ma drinking water
3. Interview 
4. SOUNDBITE (English) Ma Ying Jeo, incoming Taiwanese president
"Well, I think the earthquake may provide a good opportunity for the two sides to work together."
5. Wide of interview
6. SOUNDBITE: (English) Ma Ying Jeo, incoming Taiwanese President:
" They (China) should really open up themselves to let foreign rescuers to come in. Well, Taiwan is in a unique position to offer help, for reasons of cultural and the linguistic advantages and there are more than 100,000 Taiwanese firms investing on Chinese mainland. Quite a lot of them are in Sichuan. They already organised themselves into many chambers of commerce and so they have already begun donating. I personally donated roughly, let me see, roughly around 6,000 US dollars. "
7. Close of Ma's hands
8. Close of Ma's face
9. Wide of interview
10. SOUNDBITE: (English) Ma Ying Jeo, incoming Taiwanese President:
"Everybody knows that it is very difficult for us to see any unification talk even in our lifetime. But we have to be pragmatic. There are so many urgent problems that need our attention. We can't spend all the time talking about whether we should call ourself republic of Taiwan or republic of China and those issues are not what our people are interested in. So, I got elected because I tell people the truth - 'let's focus on our economy, let's focus on our global outreach'.''
11. Close of Ma's hands
12. SOUNDBITE: (English) Ma Ying Jeo, incoming Taiwanese President:
"You know, Taiwanese people would like to have economic interactions with the mainland, but obviously they don't believe that their political system is suited for Taiwan."
13. Cutaway of Ma laughing
14.SOUNDBITE : (English) President Ma Ying Jeo.
"We want to rebuild mutual confidence between the United States, which has been badly damaged as a result of what I called 'diplomatic adventurism' on the part of the current administration. That period has already past."
15. Ma shaking hands with AP journalists 

STORYLINE

Taiwan's incoming President Ma Ying-jeou said on Thursday that the massive earthquake in China that killed nearly 20-thousand people could provide a good opportunity for the island to help its long time rival.

In an exclusive interview with The Associated Press, Ma said that the island's experience in dealing with a big quake in 1999 gave it the ability to help the mainland recover from the 7.9 magnitude temblor that devastated large parts of Sichuan province on Monday.

"Taiwan is in a unique position to offer help," Ma said. "The earthquake provides a good opportunity for the two sides to work together," he added.

Ma declared that his government wanted to send teams to China to help cope with the damage from the 7.9 magnitude earthquake that has decimated large areas of Sichuan province.

"For reasons of cultural and the linguistic advantages and there are more than 100,000 Taiwanese firms investing on Chinese mainland. Quite a lot of them are in Sichuan," he said.

"They already organised themselves into many chambers of commerce and so they have already begun donating," he added. 

Ma also said that he had personally contributed 6,000 US dollars to the Red Cross to help survivors.

On the subject of unification with China, Ma said he thought it would be ''unlikely in our lifetimes", adding that there were more pressing matters to address.

"We can't spend all the time talking about whether we should call ourself Republic of Taiwan or Republic of China and those issues are not what our people are interested in," he said.




Ma's comments came just five days before his inauguration.

items.title: Food shortages in village in Sichuan province
items.description:
SHOTLIST

1. Close of handing picking corn kernels out of sand and rubble on ground 
2. Wide of farmer looking through rubble for corn kernels 
3. Close of farmers' face 
4. Close of hand putting corn kernels in basket
5. Wide of farmer's wife walking out of destroyed home 
6. Framer's wife with grandson strapped to her back, looking through rubble 
7. SOUNDBITE (Mandarin/Sichuan dialect) Li Shunfang, Farmer'sa wife: 
"When it rains we can only sit outside in the open air. And now we can't find food. We can't eat rice."
8. Mid of Li Shunfang's husband looking through rubble 
9. Tilt up from close of Li Shunfang's grandson to close of her face 
10. Wide of family among ruins of destroyed home 
11. Wide of mountains, remains of destroyed house in foreground 
12. Various of destroyed home 
13. Tracking shot of Li Xinzhi walking into destroyed home 
14. Close of Li Xinzhi's face 
15. Li Xinzhi pointing out damage to home, UPSOUND: Li Xinzhi (Mandarin/Sichuan dialect) "See, my house has collapsed. My walls have fallen down, my cooking wok is broken now." 
16. SOUNDBITE (Mandarin/Sichuan dialect) Li Xinzhi, Farmer: 
"The government haven't come here yet. There is nobody asking about us. No one cares about our food and water."
17. Wide of Li Xinzhi in his destroyed home 
17. Close of plants outside home, destroyed house in background 

STORYLINE 

China began airlifting aid on Wednesday to the areas worst hit by a massive earthquake, while reporting a huge jump in deaths certain to push the death toll close to 20-thousand. 

Tens of thousands of homeless people in wrecked towns and villages across hilly stretches of Sichuan province, hit hardest by Monday's 7.9 magnitude earthquake, spent a second night outdoors.

77 year old farmer, Zhu Qingyou, lost his home in the village of Hou Zhong, when the earthquake levelled his house and destroyed his entire village. 

Zhu and his family have been living in the ruins of their destroyed home, with very little food and clean water. 

He told AP Television he is now relaying on scraps salvaged from the ruins to feed his family. 

Zhu's wife, said she and her family were lucky to be out on the porch when their home collapsed during the quake. 

Some villagers in nearby areas were buried alive, Li Shunfang told AP Television. 

Li, said her family are now stranded in the mountains, with no food, water or shelter. 

"When it rains we can only sit outside in the open air. And now we can't find food. We can't eat rice", she said. 

China's government has been clamouring to get aid to the thousands affected by Monday's earthquake. But the scale of the destruction has been so huge that despite the government's best efforts, help isn't reaching victims in time.

"The government haven't come here yet. There is nobody asking about us. No one cares about our food and water," Li Xinzhi, another farmer who lost his home told AP Television. 

China's earthquake death toll jumped to nearly 20-thousand, with over 12-thousand deaths in Sichuan province alone. Tens of thousands more are missing, and thousands more have been displaced.

items.title: Acitivists raise flag to mark "independence day"
items.description:
SHOTLIST

September 8, 2005
1. Wide shot of crowd cheering and waving flags for the arrival of flag 
2. Wide shot crowd cheering
3. Close-up of crowd  
4. Man on stage singing Taiwan's "independence anthem"
5. Flag being raised up flagpole
6. Crowd singing and waving flags
7. Close-up man in crowd singing
8. Flag at top of pole, pull out to crowd AUDIO: crowd chanting
9. Close-up "Taiwan Independence flag"
10. Crowd cheering and waving flags
11. SOUNDBITE: (English) Simon Lin, chief of Taiwan Centre Foundation of Greater Los Angeles:
"Taiwanese people should consider to start thinking what kind of flag should really represent Taiwanese people. So, today we have special meaning that all 23- (m)million Taiwanese people should consider to have a really meaningful national flag."
12. SOUNDBITE: (Mandarin/English) Dr. Fei-Kuang Tseng, commissioner of overseas affairs:
"(Mandarin) Japan renounced all the claims to Taiwan when they signed a peace treaty on 8 September,1951 in San Francisco. There was nothing saying that Taiwan should return to China. So when the peace treaty was effected Taiwan belonged to the Taiwanese people. (English) In fact, Taiwan is a independent country and the sovereignty belongs to the people living in Taiwan, the natives of Taiwan." 
13. Various of people with banner, reads: "Taiwanese American Association of Los Angeles East San Gabriel Valley"

September 7, 2005
14. James Soong, leader of People First Party, PFP (on screen left) shaking hands with Ma Ying-jeou, leader of Nationalist Party, KMT (on screen right) 
16. Close-up of hand shake
17. Wide shot of meeting

STORYLINE

Supporters of formal independence for Taiwan gathered near the presidential office in Taipei on Thursday to raise a flag and mark what they call the island's day of independence from Japan and rival China. 

The activists chose 8 September because it is the anniversary of the 1951 San Francisco Treaty, in which Japan gave up its territorial claim over Taiwan. 

Japan ruled the island from 1895 to 1945. 

China's Nationalists then took over, and retreated from mainland China to Taiwan in 1949 as they were losing a civil war with the Communists.

The Communist government in Beijing still claims sovereignty over self-ruled Taiwan. 

In March, China's legislature passed a law authorising an attack against the island if it moved toward formal independence. 

More than a thousand independence supporters chanted songs and prayed as the blue, white and green flag slowly rose above a stage erected on the main road leading to Taipei's presidential office building. 

The flag has a red sun in the middle with the Chinese characters for "Taiwan Nation." 

On Wednesday, PFP (People First Party) leader James Soong met the new Nationalist (KMT) leader Ma Ying-jeou to discuss cross strait issues and defence issues.

Soong has made it clear that he favours blocking a massive purchase of US arms supported by the government of President Chen Shui-bian.

The PFP is the junior partner in an opposition coalition that for more than a year has used its slim legislative majority to hold up a special appropriation for the arms purchase, saying it would spark an arms race with rival China that would bankrupt Taiwan.

The Nationalists and PFP favour Taiwan's eventual unification with mainland China.

9. Wide shot of President Chen on stage
10. SOUNDBITE: (Mandarin) Chen Shui-Bian, Taiwanese President:      
"Soon Taipei will have a building completed with modern technology and features that will draw international firms to Taiwan. The building will be able to provide an excellent business environment to everyone."

"Of course we have experienced natural disasters and accidents, but we are honoured that we are finally finishing the project."
24. SOUNDBITE: (English) Dugald MacKay, Director, Turner International:
"This is a very significant day for Taipei 101 project. It's the topping of the steel structure, which takes us up to a point before we start to jack the spire. With the spire in place, it will be 508 meter, which will be the tallest structure in the world."
25. Tilt up building

STORYLINE:

Taiwanese politicians and other high ranking figures attended a ceremony in Taipei on Tuesday to celebrate the placement of a steel beam on the top floor of, what officials say, will be the world's tallest building when completed next year. 

Taiwanese President Chen Shui-Bian and Taipei city mayor, Ma Ing-Jeou both signed the golden beam before it was positioned on the 101st floor of the 446.4 meter building (14,731 feet).

A 50 meter spire will be placed on top of the building later this year, and the structure will stand at 508 meters, when it is completed in April 2004, making it the world's highest building. 

But there have been concerns over the safety of the structure, given Taiwan's geographical position on two shifting tectonic plates. 

In 2002, two cranes on top of the unfinished building fell during an earthquake, killing five workers. 

Officials said the tremor may have loosened the screws binding the the cranes, causing them to fall. 

The country is hit by thousands of earthquakes each year, although most of them are centred deep under the sea and cause little, or no damage. 

However, a quake of a magnitude 7.6 killed 2378 people and destroyed more than 40,000 homes in the September of 1999.

Central Weather Bureau
10. Various of seismologist looking at the Richter scale graph
11. Pan to the graph showing Monday's quake
12. SOUNDBITE: (Mandarin) Kuo Kai-wen, Seismology Centre Director, Central Weather Bureau
"Taiwan is located where Eurasian and Philippines plates meet. Each year the Philippines plate moves seven centimetres in the northwest direction. Therefore it would cause an earthquake magnitude over six every three to five years in eastern Taiwan. This can be seen as a regular energy release from the plates."
13. Cutaway seismologist looking at Richter scale graph
14. SOUNDBITE: (Mandarin) Kuo Kai-wen, Seismology Centre Director, Central Weather Bureau
"We will see aftershocks of magnitude over five in the near future. We should be alert and prepared."

Taiwan Stock Exchange
15. Wide of investors on the stock market trading floor looking at index numbers
16. Various of investors
17. Various of computer screen showing the index numbers
18. Wide of people looking at a monitor showing the index numbers
19. SOUNDBITE: (Mandarin) Huang Lun-yu, Investor
"The quake did not affect the market. The trading is very good."
20. SOUNDBITE: (Mandarin) Lee Wen-yi, Investor
"The market was not affected at all. The index numbers are still low and there is room for a good rise. (The) Taiwan economy is sound. Our electronics and computer industries are in good shape."
21. Wide shot of leaning building

STORYLINE:

Two moderate earthquakes have shaken eastern Taiwan and triggered landslides the day after a powerful tremor killed five construction workers in a high-rise building.

The quakes, of magnitudes 4.8 and 4.5 on the Richter scale, were centred at sea about 10 kilometres (six miles) off Ilan, a coastal town 150 kilometres (90 miles) southeast of the capital Taipei, the Central Weather Bureau said.

The quakes were among more than 100 aftershocks registered following Sunday's tremor that registered a magnitude of 6.8.

The five workers were killed on Sunday when two cranes fell from the 60th floor of a high-rise building under construction.

Debris falling from the building injured about 10 people and smashed several cars.

Also affected was an old four-storey building in downtown Taipei which partially collapsed and is tilting towards the street.

Rescue workers pulled out seven people, including three children, from the building. 

Meanwhile, the Taiwan Stock Exchange reacted calmly to the disaster, falling less than one per cent on opening, but rising quickly.

Tremors frequently shake Taiwan, but most cause little or no damage.

An earthquake with a magnitude of 7.6 in September 1999 killed 2-thousand-378 people and destroyed more than 40-thousand homes.

items.title: Environmental groups stage anti nuclear march to mark Fukushima anniversary
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Various of people observing a minute of silence for the victims of Fukushima nuclear crisis
2. Wide of protesters marching at an anti nuclear energy parade
3. Man chanting slogan (mandarin) "I love my home town, nuclear waste go away", pan to protesters
4. Aboriginal protesters singing a tribal song 
5. Close of sign, reading (English) "Nuclear waste out of Orchid Island Taiwan"
6. SOUNDBITE (Mandarin) Alarun, Young Tao tribe man from Orchid Island:
"We want the government to give a clean island back to us. If an earthquake struck the Orchid Island like the one that hit Japan last year, it would trigger radioactive leakage of the waste being stored on our island, and we wouldn't be able to live there anymore."
7. Man chanting slogan (Mandarin) "Nuclear waste go away"
8. Various of protesters playing drums
9. Tilt down from protester holding sign, reading (English) "Fight nuke, Get up" to another sign, reading (English) "No Nuke"
10. SOUNDBITE (Mandarin) Sophie Su, Member of Taiwan women association:
"We must not rely on nuclear power. We could by no means sustain the disasters such as those that struck Fukushima or Chernobyl. After the Fukushima crisis, even the Japanese government was incapable of handling it. In Taiwan, we don't have the technology to handle such a disaster."
11. Protesters marching
12. Back shot of police monitoring parade
13. Top shot of parade
STORYLINE
About two-thousand people staged an anti-nuclear protest in Taiwan's capital as they observed a moment of silence to mourn the victims of the massive earthquake and tsunami that hit Japan one year ago. 
The protesters paraded in Taipei on Sunday to renew calls for a nuclear-free island by taking lessons from Japan's disaster on March 11, 2011, which triggered meltdowns at three nuclear reactors.
They want the government to scrap a plan to operate a newly constructed nuclear power plant, the fourth in densely populated Taiwan.
Scores of aboriginal protesters demanded the removal of 100-thousand barrels of nuclear waste stored on their Orchid Island, off southeastern Taiwan.
"We want the government to give a clean island back to us. If an earthquake struck the Orchid Island like the one that hit Japan last year, it would trigger radioactive leakage of the waste being stored on our island," Alarun, a 35 year old Tao tribe man said. 
Authorities have failed to find a substitute storage site amid increased awareness of nuclear danger over the past decade.
Meanwhile, Sophie Su, member of Taiwan women association urged the Taiwan government not to use the newly constructed nuclear power plant as she said there were concerns over the government's capability to handle a nuclear crisis like Japan.
"We could by no means sustain the disasters such as those that struck Fukushima or Chernobyl. After the Fukushima crisis, even the Japanese government was incapable of handling it. In Taiwan, we don't have the technology to handle such a  disaster," she said.

items.title: CHILDREN HELP CELEBRATE 10th BIRTHDAY OF RED CRANE MR BIG
items.description:
Officials at a Taiwan zoo on Monday held a special birthday gathering for their rare Japanese red-crowned crane, "Mr Big."
Staff at Taipei Zoo celebrated Mr Big's tenth birthday with cake, music and entertainers dressed in crane costumes.  
Oblivious to all the fuss, Mr Big stood calmly in his nearby cage tending to his feathers and standing on one leg.
Students from an elementary school near Taipei played Happy Birthday on their harmonicas to mark the occasion, while zoo officials handed round slices of birthday cake on Mr Big's behalf.
A businessman from a local supermarket, Big City, donated the cake for the party. He said he wanted to promote better knowledge of the rare bird amongst the Taiwanese people, to help protect the species.
Local nursery children also took an afternoon off and enjoyed the cake and music.
Japan sent a pair of endangered red-crowned cranes from Kushiro Zoo to Taiwan to thank them for the relief efforts they provided after the devastating earthquake and tsunami last year (2011). 
Japan has around 900 red-crowned cranes left, more than any other country.
The birds are native to northeast Asia but were hunted to near extinction for their feathers by the beginning of the 20th century.  
Cranes are considered a symbol of longevity and represent good luck in both China and Japan.
