items.title: Matthew 22 Audio Bible
items.description:
Jesus spoke to them again in parables, saying,
"The kingdom of heaven may be compared to a king who gave a wedding feast for his son.
"And he sent out his slaves to call those who had been invited to the wedding feast, and they were unwilling to come.
"Again he sent out other slaves saying, 'Tell those who have been invited, "Behold, I have prepared my dinner; my oxen and my fattened livestock are all butchered and everything is ready; come to the wedding feast."'
"But they paid no attention and went their way, one to his own farm, another to his business,
and the rest seized his slaves and mistreated them and killed them.
"But the king was enraged, and he sent his armies and destroyed those murderers and set their city on fire.
"Then he said to his slaves, 'The wedding is ready, but those who were invited were not worthy.
'Go therefore to the main highways, and as many as you find there, invite to the wedding feast.'
"Those slaves went out into the streets and gathered together all they found, both evil and good; and the wedding hall was filled with dinner guests.
"But when the king came in to look over the dinner guests, he saw a man there who was not dressed in wedding clothes,
and he said to him, 'Friend, how did you come in here without wedding clothes?' And the man was speechless.
"Then the king said to the servants, 'Bind him hand and foot, and throw him into the outer darkness; in that place there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth.'
"For many are called, but few are chosen."
Then the Pharisees went and plotted together how they might trap Him in what He said.
And they sent their disciples to Him, along with the Herodians, saying, "Teacher, we know that You are truthful and teach the way of God in truth, and defer to no one; for You are not partial to any.
"Tell us then, what do You think? Is it lawful to give a poll-tax to Caesar, or not?"
But Jesus perceived their malice, and said, "Why are you testing Me, you hypocrites?
"Show Me the coin used for the poll-tax." And they brought Him a denarius.
And He said to them, "Whose likeness and inscription is this?"
They said to Him, "Caesar's." Then He said to them, "Then render to Caesar the things that are Caesar's; and to God the things that are God's."
And hearing this, they were amazed, and leaving Him, they went away.
On that day some Sadducees (who say there is no resurrection) came to Jesus and questioned Him,
asking, "Teacher, Moses said, 'IF A MAN DIES HAVING NO CHILDREN, HIS BROTHER AS NEXT OF KIN SHALL MARRY HIS WIFE, AND RAISE UP CHILDREN FOR HIS BROTHER.'
"Now there were seven brothers with us; and the first married and died, and having no children left his wife to his brother;
so also the second, and the third, down to the seventh.
"Last of all, the woman died.
"In the resurrection, therefore, whose wife of the seven will she be? For they all had married her."
But Jesus answered and said to them, "You are mistaken, not understanding the Scriptures nor the power of God.
"For in the resurrection they neither marry nor are given in marriage, but are like angels in heaven.
"But regarding the resurrection of the dead, have you not read what was spoken to you by God:
'I AM THE GOD OF ABRAHAM, AND THE GOD OF ISAAC, AND THE GOD OF JACOB'? He is not the God of the dead but of the living."
When the crowds heard this, they were astonished at His teaching.
But when the Pharisees heard that Jesus had silenced the Sadducees, they gathered themselves together.
One of them, a lawyer, asked Him a question, testing Him,
"Teacher, which is the great commandment in the Law?"
And He said to him, " 'YOU SHALL LOVE THE LORD YOUR GOD WITH ALL YOUR HEART, AND WITH ALL YOUR SOUL, AND WITH ALL YOUR MIND.'
"This is the great and foremost commandment.
"The second is like it, 'YOU SHALL LOVE YOUR NEIGHBOR AS YOURSELF.'
"On these two commandments depend the whole Law and the Prophets."
Now while the Pharisees were gathered together, Jesus asked them a question:
"What do you think about the Christ, whose son is He?" They said to Him, "The son of David."
He said to them, "Then how does David in the Spirit call Him 'Lord,' saying,
'THE LORD SAID TO MY LORD, "SIT AT MY RIGHT HAND, UNTIL I PUT YOUR ENEMIES BENEATH YOUR FEET"'?
"If David then calls Him 'Lord,' how is He his son?"
No one was able to answer Him a word, nor did anyone dare from that day on to ask Him another question.

items.title: Matthew 23 Audio Bible
items.description:
Then Jesus spoke to the crowds and to His disciples,
saying: "The scribes and the Pharisees have seated themselves in the chair of Moses;
therefore all that they tell you, do and observe, but do not do according to their deeds; for they say things and do not do them.
"They tie up heavy burdens and lay them on men's shoulders, but they themselves are unwilling to move them with so much as a finger.
"But they do all their deeds to be noticed by men; for they broaden their phylacteries and lengthen the tassels of their garments.
"They love the place of honor at banquets and the chief seats in the synagogues,
and respectful greetings in the market places, and being called Rabbi by men.
"But do not be called Rabbi; for One is your Teacher, and you are all brothers.
"Do not call anyone on earth your father; for One is your Father, He who is in heaven.
"Do not be called leaders; for One is your Leader, that is, Christ.
"But the greatest among you shall be your servant.
"Whoever exalts himself shall be humbled; and whoever humbles himself shall be exalted.
"But woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites, because you shut off the kingdom of heaven from people; for you do not enter in yourselves, nor do you allow those who are entering to go in.
"Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites, because you devour widows' houses, and for a pretense you make long prayers; therefore you will receive greater condemnation.
"Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites, because you travel around on sea and land to make one proselyte; and when he becomes one, you make him twice as much a son of hell as yourselves.
"Woe to you, blind guides, who say, 'Whoever swears by the temple, that is nothing; but whoever swears by the gold of the temple is obligated.'
"You fools and blind men! Which is more important, the gold or the temple that sanctified the gold?
"And, 'Whoever swears by the altar, that is nothing, but whoever swears by the offering on it, he is obligated.'
"You blind men, which is more important, the offering, or the altar that sanctifies the offering?
"Therefore, whoever swears by the altar, swears both by the altar and by everything on it.
"And whoever swears by the temple, swears both by the temple and by Him who dwells within it.
"And whoever swears by heaven, swears both by the throne of God and by Him who sits upon it.
"Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you tithe mint and dill and cummin, and have neglected the weightier provisions of the law: justice and mercy and faithfulness; but these are the things you should have done without neglecting the others.
"You blind guides, who strain out a gnat and swallow a camel!
"Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you clean the outside of the cup and of the dish, but inside they are full of robbery and self-indulgence.
"You blind Pharisee, first clean the inside of the cup and of the dish, so that the outside of it may become clean also.
"Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you are like whitewashed tombs which on the outside appear beautiful, but inside they are full of dead men's bones and all uncleanness.
"So you, too, outwardly appear righteous to men, but inwardly you are full of hypocrisy and lawlessness.
"Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you build the tombs of the prophets and adorn the monuments of the righteous,
and say, 'If we had been living in the days of our fathers, we would not have been partners with them in shedding the blood of the prophets.'
"So you testify against yourselves, that you are sons of those who murdered the prophets.
"Fill up, then, the measure of the guilt of your fathers.
"You serpents, you brood of vipers, how will you escape the sentence of hell?
"Therefore, behold, I am sending you prophets and wise men and scribes; some of them you will kill and crucify, and some of them you will scourge in your synagogues, and persecute from city to city,
so that upon you may fall the guilt of all the righteous blood shed on earth, from the blood of righteous Abel to the blood of Zechariah, the son of Berechiah, whom you murdered between the temple and the altar.
"Truly I say to you, all these things will come upon this generation.
"Jerusalem, Jerusalem, who kills the prophets and stones those who are sent to her! How often I wanted to gather your children together, the way a hen gathers her chicks under her wings, and you were unwilling.
"Behold, your house is being left to you desolate!
"For I say to you, from now on you will not see Me until you say, 'BLESSED IS HE WHO COMES IN THE NAME OF THE LORD!'"

Now after the Sabbath, as it began to dawn toward the first day of the week, Mary Magdalene and the other Mary came to look at the grave.
And behold, a severe earthquake had occurred, for an angel of the Lord descended from heaven and came and rolled away the stone and sat upon it.
And his appearance was like lightning, and his clothing as white as snow.
The guards shook for fear of him and became like dead men.
The angel said to the women, "Do not be afraid; for I know that you are looking for Jesus who has been crucified.
"He is not here, for He has risen, just as He said. Come, see the place where He was lying.
"Go quickly and tell His disciples that He has risen from the dead; and behold, He is going ahead of you into Galilee, there you will see Him; behold, I have told you."
And they left the tomb quickly with fear and great joy and ran to report it to His disciples.
And behold, Jesus met them and greeted them. And they came up and took hold of His feet and worshiped Him.
Then Jesus said to them, "Do not be afraid; go and take word to My brethren to leave for Galilee, and there they will see Me."
Now while they were on their way, some of the guard came into the city and reported to the chief priests all that had happened.
And when they had assembled with the elders and consulted together, they gave a large sum of money to the soldiers,
and said, "You are to say, 'His disciples came by night and stole Him away while we were asleep.'
"And if this should come to the governor's ears, we will win him over and keep you out of trouble."
And they took the money and did as they had been instructed; and this story was widely spread among the Jews, and is to this day.
But the eleven disciples proceeded to Galilee, to the mountain which Jesus had designated.
When they saw Him, they worshiped Him; but some were doubtful.
And Jesus came up and spoke to them, saying, "All authority has been given to Me in heaven and on earth.
"Go therefore and make disciples of all the nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father and the Son and the Holy Spirit,
teaching them to observe all that I commanded you; and lo, I am with you always, even to the end of the age."

items.title: "Nature in our Backyard" Dallas, TX photography exhibition at Sun to Moon Gallery
items.description:
"Nature in our Backyard: The Trinity River & Great Trinity Forest"

Fine photographic prints by Dan Burkholder, Scot Miller, Jill Skupin Burkholder & R.P. Washburne

June 25 – August 22, 2015

The Trinity River and Great Trinity Forest have been receiving much attention, for a variety of reasons, but it’s no secret that the river dominated the spotlight recently. Thousands flocked to its banks to experience the sights of the flood waters. However, the reality is most people know little about the true nature of river and forest as they exist year-round. Sun to Moon Gallery and four talented photographers have worked to change that. For ten years now, the photographers have spent time on and along the river and in and around the forest, including many beautiful but lesser-known areas, creatively interpreting with their cameras. In the process, they have created an ever-expanding and changing body of work that includes engaging new photographs of the flooded Trinity by Scot Miller and R.P. Washburne.

From vivid digitally captured images, to stunning detail studies with film and a medium-format camera, to bromoil prints overlaid with color pigments, to 24k Gold Leaf Prints and more; a wide range of subject matter, artistic expression and photographic techniques form the basis of this eye-opening exhibition. Sun to Moon Gallery invites the public to come, be inspired, and see the river, forest and city in a new light!

New short films by Scot Miller –

Scot Miller, a contributor to the “Moment in Nature” videos, broadcast nationally on Emmy Award-winning CBS Sunday Morning, also spent many hours and days over the past months capturing stunning 4k video footage of the river and forest, including many time sequences. He has created several short films, including one featuring the floods, that will be screened in the gallery throughout the exhibition.

items.title: Letter To Our Subscribers Oct 2015
items.description:
It fell into my heart about two weeks ago to write you this letter. I sat down right away to do it but to me it felt superficial, and not really from my heart, so I put it on the back burner until now.

Then I was awakened from sleep and the words began to come to me concerning what I really wanted to say, so I came to jot them down.

I recently watched a video of a shepherdess caring for her sheep... she led them to good pasture where they grazed till their hearts were content. That's what canDEElicious Video Ministry is all about... preparing ground for you to graze on. Come over here the table is spread and the feast of the Lord is going on.

In the video there were also baby lambs that the shepherdess fed with a milk bottle, reminding me of Jesus' words to Peter, "Feed My Lambs."

Although the Lord did not call me to be a shepherd, He made me a hireling to feed His sheep and His  little lambs. With all my heart, I want to do my best and be a worthy vessel for His use. When you watch these videos, I want the Lord to touch your hearts and bring you a sense that He is speaking directly to you.

Heb 4:12 says the word of God is a discerner of the thoughts and intents of the heart. That's why it sounds like He is speaking directly to you.

- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -

Lately, I've been feeling like such a failure at living up to His calling and election. My attitude toward God and misunderstanding His will for my life has left me wanting.

One of the things that I never want to happen as I teach God's word to others is that I myself would not live up to it through my disobedience and obstinance.

A few years ago, I was so offended with God that I refused to pray. Prayer didn't seem practical because my expectations were not being met. So I weaned off. There were times when the Holy Spirit would unction me to pray and I would kindly decline, "No thank You." I didn't feel mad at God. Prayer just simply felt impractical so I failed to maintain a good prayer life.

But I woke up one morning the The Temptations fell in my heart and I couldn't shake it... 

I can fly like a bird in the sky
And I can buy anything money can buy
I can turn a river into a raging fire
I can live forever if I so desire
Unimportant are all the things I can do
Cause I can't get next to babe
Can't get next to you.

I felt that I had let my Lord down feeding Him from a long-handled spoon. He was knocking at the door of my heart but my pride kept me at a distance. But I thought it was so sweet that He said with all of His power to do anything He wants to do - the one thing escaping Him was getting me to open up.

Jesus said, "Behold I stand at the door and knock. If anyone hears My voice and opens the door, I will come in to him and dine with him, and he with Me."

God's love is poured out in our hearts by the Holy Spirit but we must first open our hearts to Him and invite Him in (or back in, if He's been pushed aside).

Perhaps today you have decided that you want to get closer to the Lord. Reach out to Him, let Him right the wrongs. He said His grace is sufficient... and He is strong where we are weak.

Let God arise and His enemies be scattered. Submit yourselves to God, resist the devil and he will flee from you.

Thank you, our Subscribers. We're praying for you and sincerely hoping these Bible teachings are helping you. We'll see you again soon.

May God bless and keep you and make His face shine upon you and be gracious to you. May the Lord lift up His countenance upon you and give you His peace.

items.title: WRA Architects Designed Village Tech Charter School New Campus
items.description:
Village Tech Schools, a charter school serving grades pre-K through 12, is in the design stage of their new permanent campus to be located near Belt Line Road in Cedar Hill's historic downtown. WRA Architects of Dallas is designing the school, and Northstar Builders of Coppell has been selected as the Construction Manager, or builder.
"We are thrilled to partner with WRA and the City of Cedar Hill on this exciting new project," said David Williams, Village Tech's founder and CEO. "When we're finished, the school will enclose 168,000 square feet in four separate buildings and will serve up to 1,040 students."
The four structures include a 3-story classroom building for grades 3-12, a preschool for grades PreK-2, a gymnasium and dining building, and "the Forge."
The Forge is the heart of the school and embodies Village Tech's educational philosophy. It includes maker spaces, art studios, computer labs, and presentation and demonstration space. This is where students from all grade levels will design and construct projects that relate to and illustrate their curriculum in all core subjects.
Keith Anderson, AIA, is WRA's director of design and principal-in-charge of the project. He commented, "Village Tech has a wonderfully innovative approach to education, and working with them on bringing their vision to life on a new campus has been very exciting for our design team."
The campus will be one of the first projects in the redevelopment of Cedar Hill's urban center and hopes to be a catalyst for further development of this area. The school will hold its "Home of Tomorrow" preview of the new campus on the future school site at 100 Carrell Street in Cedar Hill on Saturday, December 12, from 11 am to 2 pm.
Construction will start in mid-2016.

items.title: Massive landslide due to Earthquake in Nepal 2015
items.description:
Here is an incredibly heartbreaking footage shot by Chandra Mandil Yogal, Public Health Manager, Department of Community Programs, Dhulikhel Hospital, Nepal. Chandra along with a team of five from Dhulikhel Hospital left yesterday morning for Hindi Health Center for damage assessment and possibility of restoring clinical services and other activities run through this center. This center established in Nov 2011 is a satellite clinic of Dhulikhel Hospital and had collapsed completely due to the earthquake of 25th April. The earthquake of 12:50 pm yesterday set off a massive landslide. "We were caught unawares, the mountain fells and it was dark with dust. We walked for hours to find a place where we could get mobile signal and called Dhulikhel Hospital." says Chandra who was airlifted to safety yesterday. The rest of the team were brought safely in the helicopter today

Massive landslide due to Earthquake in Nepal 2015

items.title: Magnitude of Earthquake on Richter Scale. What it means? (Animation)
items.description:
This animated video explains what the Magnitude of the Earthquake on Richter Scale  means and how devastating it could be with every increment of every value.on Richter Scale.

What is Ricter Scale: The Richter magnitude scale (also Richter scale) assigns a magnitude number to quantify the energy released by an earthquake. The Richter scale is a base-10 logarithmic scale, which defines magnitude as the logarithm of the ratio of the amplitude of the seismic waves to an arbitrary, minor amplitude.

As measured with a seismometer, an earthquake that registers 5.0 on the Richter scale has a shaking amplitude 10 times that of an earthquake that registered 4.0, and thus corresponds to a release of energy 31.6 times that released by the lesser earthquake.

Developed in the 1930s, it was succeeded in the 1970s by the Moment Magnitude Scale (MMS) which is now the scale used to estimate magnitudes for all modern large earthquakes by the United States Geological Survey. However, earthquake magnitudes are still sometimes incorrectly reported as "an earthquake of XX on the Richter scale", when the correct terminology using the MMS is "a magnitude XX earthquake.

items.title: Findings from the 2015 Nepal Earthquake
items.description:
Knowledge Forum Talk on “Findings from the 2015 Nepal Earthquake” by Dr Roger Bilham, Professor, Department of Geological Sciences, University of Colorado, Boulder, USA

21 May 2015, ICIMOD Headquarters

Dr Bilham holds a PhD in Geophysics from Cambridge University. 
His research includes: Application of space geodesy and strain and tilt instrumentation to monitor deformation of the Earth at plate boundaries, mostly in southern Asia and western North America; Design and operation of new geophysical instruments to monitor strain and tilt in the Earth; Archival research into historical earthquakes; Statistics of urban earthquakes and global seismic hazards. 

He is currently working on two books: a book on urban earthquakes, and a book on Mt. Everest. The Everest book is linked to his work in deriving a new height for the mountain and discusses the geology, geodesy and geophysics of the Himalaya.

items.title: Life after earthquake in Phulkharka village Nepal
items.description:
The 7.8 magnitude earthquake of April 25 took over 8,500 lives and destroyed about 2,00,000 houses. Phulkharka village near the epicenter was one of the hard hit villages, where 27 people lost their lives, 95% houses were destroyed and hundreds of cattle were buried in rubble. 
Phulkharka is located in the foothills of Ganesh Himal (4,429 m), 135 km northwest of Kathmandu. The main income of the village is agriculture with majority of its men working in Middle East or in Kathmandu earning supplementary income for the family. Because of climate depended traditional farming, agriculture is subsistence.
The village is perched high up along the flank for 3,200 m mountain with scenic higher reaches offering panoramic view of Manaslu and Ganesh Himal range. Its pristine, forested higher reaches make a beautiful short trek. The village is also culturally rich with its ethnic diversity. Tamangs here still practice Shamanism in its intact form. Because of forested higher reaches, the village is source of water for surrounding 5 village development committees.   
Phulkharka village development with population of about 7,500 people has 7 primary schools and one high school. All school buildings were destroyed in the tremor sighting the need of more sophisticated, earthquake proof school buildings which could be used as shelters in case of natural disaster. 
Ganga Jamuna Youth club has been providing immediate relief materials and volunteers to erect temporary shelters. The aftershocks, government policies and soon coming monsoon will delay the construction of permanent structures by few months. We are planning to mobilize more volunteers to accomplish the task of rebuilding. 
We would like to request international and nation communities to support us in the campaign by technical or financial aid. 
We need skilled volunteers and technicians in construction. Please visit the link for further information. http://www.itournepal.com/volunteernepal.php

You can also support our cause financially at http://www.youcaring.com/emergency-fundraiser/rebuilding-school-damaged-by-nepal-earthquake-/354800

I like to show you how Thamel looks 45 days after the earthquake. The news about the earthquake in Nepal were so awful that it surprised me to see the town in this condition. On the one hand the news brought thick pockets to the NGOs and all helping organizations and on the other hand they killed the tourism entirely. Nepal had 2 disastrous earthquakes - but only in some parts of the country. 18 out of 75 districts feature earthquake-related damage.
There is no reason to stay away from Nepal. Yes, there are damages in the town and on the countryside, but there is enough space to find save places. Of course there are some trekking areas completely destroyed, but there are many areas unharmed by the earthquake.

items.title: Nepal Earthquake  Landslide After Earthquake in Sindhupalchok seen from helicopter.
items.description:
Nepal Earthquake  Landslide After Earthquake in Sindhupalchok.

The April 2015 Nepal earthquake (also known as the Gorkha earthquake)] killed more than 9,000 people and injured more than 23,000. It occurred at 11:56 NST on 25 April, with a magnitude of 7.8Mw[1] or 8.1Ms[2] and a maximum Mercalli Intensity of IX (Violent). Its epicenter was east of the district of Lamjung, and its hypocenter was at a depth of approximately 15 km (9.3 mi). It was the worst natural disaster to strike Nepal since the 1934 Nepal–Bihar earthquake.

The earthquake triggered an avalanche on Mount Everest, killing at least 19,[ making April 25, 2015 the deadliest day on the mountain in history. The earthquake triggered another huge avalanche in the Langtang valley, where 250 people were reported missing.

Hundreds of thousands of people were made homeless with entire villages flattened,[ across many districts of the country. Centuries-old buildings were destroyed at UNESCO World Heritage sites in the Kathmandu Valley, including some at the Kathmandu Durbar Square, the Patan Durbar Squar, the Bhaktapur Durbar Square, the Changu Narayan Temple and the Swayambhunath Stupa. Geophysicists and other experts had warned for decades that Nepal was vulnerable to a deadly earthquake, particularly because of its geology, urbanization, and architecture.

Continued aftershocks occurred throughout Nepal within 15–20 minute intervals, with one shock reaching a magnitude of 6.7 on 26 April at 12:54:08 NST. The country also had a continued risk of landslides.

A major aftershock occurred on 12 May 2015 at 12:51 NST with a moment magnitude (Mw) of 7.3.The epicenter was near the Chinese border between the capital of Kathmandu and Mt. Everest. More than 200 people were killed and more than 2,500 were injured by this aftershock.

A landslide, also known as a landslip, is a geological phenomenon that includes a wide range of ground movements. Rockfalls, deep failure of slopes and shallow debris flows were common. Landslides can occur in offshore, coastal and onshore environments. Although the action of gravity is the primary driving force for a landslide to occur, there are other contributing factors affecting the original slope stability. Typically, pre-conditional factors build up specific sub-surface conditions that make the area/slope prone to failure, whereas the actual landslide often requires a trigger before being released.

items.title: Scenes at dawn in devastated area, tsunami survivors
items.description:
1. Wide of dawn at Rikuzentakata where one tree survived the tsunami
2. Tilt up from water to tree
3. Mid of people praying, snow falling
4. Wide of people praying
5. Close of woman praying
6. Wide of woman leaving flowers on ground
7. SOUNDBITE: (Japanese) Mika Hashikai, resident of Rikuzentakata who lost her parents in the tsunami, and whose brother lost his wife and daughter:
"I only wish for my brother's happiness - now that he's lost everything and is alone. Maybe one day he can remarry and have children again."
8. SOUNDBITE: (Japanese) Naomi Fujino, resident of Rikuzentakata who lost her father in the tsunami:
"I wanted to save people but I couldn't. I couldn't even help my father. I cannot keep on crying. What can I do but keep on going."
9. Mid of Fujino walking away
10. Close of Santa Claus doll sitting on the ground, next to flowers, at roadside memorial to victim
11. Wide of Santa and the flattened land in the background where once buildings stood before the tsunami
STORYLINE
Dawn broke on Sunday over what remains of the fishing community of Rikuzentakata, which was devastated by the tsunami which hit Japan's north-east coast a year ago.
People came to pray in front of the symbolic pine tree that survived the tsunami and stands alone where the city used to be, just one building alongside it.
A magnitude 9.0 earthquake triggered the monstrous tsunami which roared across the coast, killing nearly 19-thousand Japanese people, and transforming once thriving towns into debris-strewn wastelands.
Rikuzentakata was one of the cities flattened, with a loss of more than 1,500 lives, and 41 people are still missing.
It was calculated that 3,159 houses were completely washed away and hundreds more were battered.
On the first anniversary of the tsunami, people returned to the spots where their houses used to be, to place flowers and small gifts for the loved ones they lost.
Mika Hashikai lost both her parents in the tsunami, and came to leave flowers in remembrance.
Her brother also survived the tsunami but lost his wife and daughter.
"I only wish for my brother's happiness - now that he's lost everything and is alone. Maybe one day he can remarry and have children again."
Resident Naomi Fujino was in tears recalling what had happened to her family on March 11 last year.
She was with her parents when they heard the sirens warning of the tsunami coming.
With her mother, she escaped to the closest hill and had promised to meet up with her father there.
Mother and daughter watched as the giant tsunami swept away their home, praying that the father had escaped.
They waited all night but he never came to meet them.
Two months later, with help of DNA testing, his body was found.
"I wanted to save people but I couldn't. I couldn't even help my father. I cannot keep on crying. What can I do but keep on going," Fujino said.
Later on Sunday, memorials will be held in all the locations that were destroyed, and tens of thousands of residents will come together in silent prayer at the exact moment when the earthquake struck, at 14:46 local time.
The devastating tsunami enveloped the north-eastern coast shortly afterwards.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/7e846cda2dbe399b0eca08cc87ca6380 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: City prepares to mark six months since devastating quake and tsunami
items.description:
FILE: Kesennuma, Miyagi Prefecture - 13 March, 2011
++AERIAL SHOTS++
1. Various aerial shots of Kesennuma city with destroyed, burnt buildings and large boats washed ashore
Kesennuma, Miyagi Prefecture - 11 September, 2011
++GROUND SHOTS++
2. Various of the port of Kesennuma
3. Various of the destroyed area with debris and heavy duty trucks parked 
4. Various of fisherman Masayuki Komatsu, resident of Kesennuma, on boat 
5. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Masayuki Komatsu, fisherman and resident of Kesennuma: 
"I would like to restart but I am unsure of the future. I can''t sell products that are inedible so I would like some sort of guarantee by the government. My business has gone bad with last year''s Chile tsunami, and this tsunami took my home away. I wonder if the government considers our horrible circumstances and the concerns of radiation for people in my business."
6. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Takeji Iwabuchi, 80-year-old resident of Kesennuma: 
"It still surprises me to see the amount of debris left. I wonder when this place will actually revive."
7. Wide of ship washed ashore and flowers on the ground where there used to be a house 
8. Close up of flowers 
9. Mid of flowers, washed up ship in the back
STORYLINE:
The small port city of Kesennuma, northeastern Japan, marked on Sunday six months since a disastrous earthquake and ensuing tsunami devastated it on March 11th this year.
The city was set to hold a memorial event at a civic centre including a minute''s silence for the deceased on Sunday at 14:45 (05:08 GMT), the time when the disastrous tsunami hit on March 11th, 2011.
The city was showing slow signs of recovery, with debris, wreckage from houses and shops, rusted vehicles and washed up boats still serving as a daily reminder of the ocean''s tremendous power and the disaster that struck this major fishing and shipping port.
The port city, situated on Japan''s north east coast, suffered 1,014 deaths whilst 392 people still remain missing.
Much of the neighbourhood around the port remains destroyed, dotted with piles of debris, crumbled cars, twisted metal, wooden planks and plastic buckets. 
Residents of Kesennuma are left with concerns of how long it would take to clear out the debris and if the city will ever get back its normal state again.
Fisherman Masayuki Komatsu explained his concerns about the future.
"I would like to restart but I am unsure of the future. I can''t sell products that are inedible so I would like some sort of guarantee by the government," he said.
Six months after the catastrophe, even though the fishing industry has restarted, Komatsu and other residents were still concerned about the radiation levels of the waters in the area.
Another resident, 80-year-old Takeji Iwabuchi, also expressed concern about the future of the city.
"It still surprises me to see the amount of debris left. I wonder when this place will actually revive," he said.

8. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Vox pop, Takashi Sugawara, 80, resident of Kesennuma
"Our lifeline is not completed yet, so I wish that it would be provided as soon as possible."
9. Pan down of people offering flowers 
10.  Close of man offering flower 
11.  Wide of the memorial ceremony
12.  Mid of people offering flowers
STORYLINE:
The small port city of Kesennuma, northeastern Japan, has marked six months since a disastrous earthquake and ensuing tsunami devastated it on March 11th this year.
The city held a memorial event at a civic centre including a minute''s silence for the deceased on Sunday at 14:45 (05:08 GMT), the time when the disastrous tsunami hit on March 11th, 2011.
The city was showing slow signs of recovery, with debris, wreckage from houses and shops, rusted vehicles and washed up boats still serving as a daily reminder of the ocean''s tremendous power and the disaster that struck this major fishing and shipping port.
The port city, situated on Japan''s north east coast, suffered 1,014 deaths whilst 392 people still remain missing.
Much of the neighbourhood around the port remains destroyed, dotted with piles of debris, crumbled cars, twisted metal, wooden planks and plastic buckets. 
Residents of Kesennuma are left with concerns of how long it would take to clear out the debris and if the city will ever get back its normal state again.

items.title: AP look at slow pace of reconstruction in Miyagi Prefecture
items.description:
Life has been put on hold for most residents of a small Japanese fishing town following the devastating earthquake and tsunami on 11 March.  
Three months after the disaster struck, Minamisanriku in Miyagi Prefecture largely remains flattened, with many complaining of painstakingly slow reconstruction efforts. 
Rubble still blankets the ground, while residents sit patiently in makeshift tents waiting for their homes to be rebuilt. 
"It's been three months�and I feel that time has frozen since the day of the disaster," construction manager Shoji Sato says.
As post-tsunami Japan strains under the enormous task of rebuilding many towns like Minamisanriku, the sheer extent of the devastation means resources are stretched. 
Some residents have tried to use debris lying around to rebuild their homes, including school teacher Yasuaki Yoshida. 
Out of a population of 17,666, at least 542 Minamisanriku residents have been confirmed dead and 664 still missing. 
Over four thousand people are still scattered in shelters. 
Others have moved themselves into temporary homes or left Minamisanriku to stay with relatives.   
The port city was once a busy town with supermarkets, shopping centres, banks, offices, schools and over 5-thousand houses.   
The tsunami swept away nearly every business, every job. 
Electricity returned in mid-May, but enough water is only running for washing dirty clothes and flushing toilets.   
The water contains too much salt to cook, but residents say they take baths in it anyway because that is all they have.    
Ikuko Abe lost her home and her livelihood, working in a hair salon, following the disaster. 
Now she works everyday as a volunteer making lunch and dinner for people living in an evacuation centre in the town.  
"How long will it take for us to get back everything that used to exist, like supermarkets, hospitals, the town hall�I have no idea how long it will take for us to get our town back. Probably decades," she says wearily.
Every day, bulldozers organise debris into separate piles; wood to be used as fuel, or piles of scrap metal to be hauled away.    
But no one knows when the city will get back on its feet and local residents don't appear hopeful about their town's future.
"I wonder if it will be any different in August," says a 92-year-old town resident, now living in temporary housing accomodation.
The pulverised coast is still being hit by hundreds of small aftershocks each day. 
Japan is located on the Ring of Fire, an arc of volcanoes and fault lines spanning the Pacific Basin, and is regularly hit by earthquakes.

items.title: Shrine one of few buildings to survive quake and tsunami in fishing village
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Wide of shrine gate 
2. Pan down of shrine
3. Pan of shrine
4. Wide of people looking at destroyed area from shrine
5. Various of destroyed area 
6. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Tomoyuki Matsuhashi, Shinto priest of Otsuchi Shrine:
"The shrine is located on high ground and has always been survived wildfires. I have to say that it is because of God." 
7. Various of evacuees inside of shrine
8. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Yasuhiro Usuzawa, local resident who fought the fire: 
"I used a wood stick to make a barrier and somehow we were able to stop the fire. I thought it was because of the shrine's God. It was really hot because of the fire. I prayed the God and the shrine would escape the fire." 
9. Various of burn marks close to shrine
10. Various of people visiting shrine 
11. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Nakao Sasaki, local resident:
"Although my relatives and I were affected by the tsunami, we were able to survive, so I came here to thank God.  Also, I prayed that we won't have more bad things and our recovery plan will go well."  
12. Pan of destroyed area and shrine in background
13. Close up of shrine gate.    
STORYLINE
The town of Otsuchi was almost entirely destroyed by the tsunami which hit Japan a month ago, but a shrine in the small fishing village was spared, something locals believe is nothing short of a miracle.
When the magnitude 9 earthquake hit the town of Otsuchi, many were evacuated to the shrine because it sits on higher ground. 
The tsunami which followed reached the shrine's outer gate and so people moved to even higher ground because they rightly believed a second tsunami would follow. 
The second wave swept the town, destroying thousands of homes, but again stopped just short of the shrine.
While most of the evacuees fled to higher ground, a group of five people stayed on and they were then forced to fight a fire caused by the tsunami, which again threatened the shrine.
The group managed to put out the fire but charred earth surrounds the building, testament to how close the shrine came to burning down.
"I used a wood stick to make a barrier and somehow we were able to stop the fire. I thought it was because of the shrine's God. It was really hot because of the fire. I prayed the God and the shrine would escape the fire," said Yasuhiro Usuzawa, a local resident who fought the fire.

items.title: AP cover: Japan holds moment of silence one month after the disasters
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Various of Japanese Self Defence Force (JSDF) holding a moment of silence for the victims of earthquake and tsunami in Kesennuma, Miyagi Prefecture, AUDIO: Siren
2. Mid of workers observing a moment of silence, AUDIO: Siren
3. Close of evening sun
4. Various of rubble with members of JSDF clearing debris and searching for bodies
5. Two members of JSDF talking
6. Member of JSDF standing on top of rubble
7. Member of JSDF shovelling mud
8. Interior of JSDF commanding operation centre
9. Colonel Toshiki Fujioka, regimental commander showing a map to another member
10. Close of JSDF member watching
11. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Colonel Toshiki Fujioka, Regimental commander:
"We are in a very difficult situation (in the search for missing) because it is impossible for us to remove the mass of rubble by just manpower, so we have to use heavy equipment but must do it very carefully. We are trying to retrieve bodies as cleanly as possible."  
12. Various of trucks at search operation
STORYLINE:
Sirens wailed and people bowed their heads and wept along Japan's devastated northeast coast on Monday as they marked a month since the tsunami that killed up to 25-thousand people and unleashed a persistent nuclear crisis.
In Kesennuma, among the worst-hit cities in Miyagi prefecture, members of Japan's Self Defence Force carrying out the search operation for the missing, gathered for the moment of silence ceremony at 2:46 p.m., (05:46 GMT) the exact moment of the magnitude-9.0 quake that spawned the tsunami March 11.
After an announcement by the city government on a speaker, soldiers and civilians stopped their work and took off their helmets as the noisy clatter of searching equipment ceased briefly.
With thousands of bodies yet to be found, a tsunami-flooded nuclear power plant still spewing radiation and more than 150-thousand people living in shelters, there was little time for reflection on Japan's worst disaster since World War II.
In Kesennuma, about 700 are confirmed dead and about 1,400 are still missing, according to city officials.
About 600 members of the Self Defence Force continue to search for bodies.
"It is impossible for us to remove the mass of rubble by just manpower, so we have to use heavy equipment but must do it very carefully. We are trying to retrieve bodies as cleanly as possible," Colonel Toshiki Fujioka, Regimental commander said.
The earthquake and tsunami flattened communities along hundreds of miles (kilometres) of coastline, causing what the government estimates could be as much as 310 (b) billion US dollars in damage. 
More than 158-thousand people are still without electricity and 210-thousand have no running water, although some of that is because of a 7.1-magnitude aftershock that rattled the area last week.
Adding to the misery is radiation spewing from the Fukushima Dai-ichi nuclear complex 140 miles (220 kilometres) northeast of Tokyo, which lost its cooling systems when water from the tsunami washed over it.
Government officials have already ordered the 70-thousand to 80-thousand people who live within 12 miles (120 kilometres) to leave.
On Monday Japan's government said it is urging even more people to evacuate the area with Chief Cabinet Secretary saying that residents of five additional communities, some more than 20 miles (30 kilometres) from the plant, are being urged to leave within a month.
He said it's not an emergency, but that high radiation levels have been detected in some places and there are concerns about long-term health risks as the crisis drags on.
Meanwhile workers at Fukushima Dai-ichi continue to struggle to remove contaminated water that has prevented them from restoring cooling systems. 


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/b2a2ec304778f0b847f53eca0a0c997c 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Recovery work continues in area where hundreds of bodies were found
items.description:
SHOTLIST :
1. Mid shot of a man with daughter searching through huge mound of debris, digger in background
2. Close up of above
3. Pan left of destroyed village of Rikuzentakata
4. Wide shot shot of diggers clearing debris
5. Various shot of debris being dumped onto military truck
6. Japanese soldiers watching
7. Close up of Japanese soldier sifting through debris with spade
8. Mid shot debris 
9. Recovery workers preparing to lift damaged car
10. Various shot of damaged car being loaded onto truck
11. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Kanno Hiroki, Volunteer Firefighter:
" When we first got here, we found around 200 bodies, all together in one group " 
12. Mid shot of Japanese police carrying stretcher
13. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Kanno Hiroki, Volunteer Firefighter:
" Maybe a lot of people we found... just didn't think the wave could reach this far " 
14. Mid shot of Japanese police with stretcher 
STORYLINE
Police, soldiers and volunteer recovery workers in the devastated town of Rikuzentakata in northern Japan, continue the grim task of clearing the debris caused by the March 11 earthquake and tsunami. 
They say around two hundred bodies have been found in the area so far.
Recovery workers say they hope to find more bodies, by moving huge piles of debris using mechanical diggers, and sifting through the rubble by hand.
The tsunami and the magnitude 9.0 earthquake that triggered it has claimed at least 11,578 lives in 12 Japanese prefectures and has left at least 16,451 people officially unaccounted for as of Friday morning.
Many of those who remain missing are believed to have been carried offshore after the tsunami struck the Pacific coast following the quake, which occurred off northeastern Japan.
The Japanese Self Defence Forces (SDF) and US military have started a three-day intensive search for those still missing.

items.title: US teachers talk about being caught up in tsunami nightmare
items.description:
Japan Earthquake
1. Wide top shot of devastated area of Minamisanriku 
2. Various top shots of damaged buildings and debris 
3. Wide of American teachers Mary Caitlin Churchill and Canon Purdy 
4. Mid of Churchill 
5. Wide top shot of devastation 
6. SOUNDBITE: (English) Mary Caitlin Churchill, 22-year old school teacher from Boston, Massachusetts: 
"It didn't quite feel real at that time, It was like 'I don't want to die, I don't want to die', it was kind of just 'run for your life' sort of moment, which I never really thought I'd have to deal with. It was still terrifying once we got to the top, we didn't know if more water was going to come, if there was going to be another tsunami, so we were kind at the highest point that we could get, so the whole evening was kind of terrifying, not knowing if we were high enough."
7. Wide of Churchill and Purdy 
8. Exterior of Shizugawa Junior High School, which was used as evacuation centre on hilltop when tsunami hit 
9. Wide of Churchill and Purdy in front of evacuation centre 
10. SOUNDBITE: (English) Canon Purdy, 25-year old teacher from San Francisco, California: 
"It, I mean, I wish I had a picture of what it used to look like as a beautiful healthy town. It was probably the most devastating thing I've ever seen, and I didn't lose my home, I didn't possibly lose a family member. So it was just overwhelming and I think everyone was so shocked and just couldn't believe what had happened."
11. Wide top shot of devastation and debris at Minamisanriku 
STORYLINE:
Mary Caitlin Churchill is a school teacher in Minamisanriku. She was in a school when the earthquake hit last Friday. She was in the teacher's room, with colleagues, when there was a tsunami warning, and they went out on the field. 
They thought they were safe at the field, but when they saw the water rising and going up the school, they had to run to higher ground, up in the mountains, behind the school. 
When she was in the mountains, she saw water filling up the fields, cars were floating, car alarms were going off, and the gym next to school was completely destroyed. 
She spent the rest of the day mostly in shock, but also tried to comfort elementary students terrified of what was happening to their home town. 
"It was still terrifying once we got to the top," Churchill said and she went on: "we didn't know if more water was going to come, if there was going to be another tsunami, so we were kind at the highest point that we could get." 
Canon Purdy was in Minamisanriku to attend a graduation ceremony for some of her former students at Shizugawa Junior High School. 
The school was located on top of a hill and is being used as an evacuation centre whenever a tsunami warning is raised. 
She was in the school when the quake hit. The students went out to the school grounds, and people started coming from the town. They all stayed in the gym.  
Twenty minutes after the warning, she came out to see what was happening and the valley where the town was located had already filled with water. 
She said she was overwhelmed by the experience, which seemed unreal. She never expected to see something like that. Everyone in the gym was shocked, people were worried, but people also immediately tried to get help. 
"It was probably the most devastating thing I've ever seen, and I didn't lose my home, I didn't possibly lose a family member. So it was just overwhelming," Purdy said. 
In Minamisanriku, 10-thousand people are still missing, according to a government spokesman. That is nearly two-thirds of the population.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/b0ccb9221681f626b0bd66c2515120f8

STORYLINE
Rescuers were searching through rubble of what was left of the coastal town of Minamisanriku on Tuesday, following the tsunami that ravaged the area on Friday.
In Minamisanriku, 10-thousand people have not been heard from since the tsunami wiped it out, according to a government spokesman.
That is nearly two-thirds of the population.
The death toll from last week's earthquake and tsunami jumped on Tuesday as police confirmed the number killed had topped 2,400, though that grim news was overshadowed by a deepening nuclear crisis. 
Officials have said previously that at least 10-thousand people may have died in Miyagi province alone.

items.title: Disasters and nuclear crisis major blow to fishing industry
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1.Wide of Shiogama port in Miyagi prefecture
2. Various of fishermen working inside boats
3. Mid of flags inside boats
4. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Mataichi Saito, 74 year-old fisherman:
"We were able to save these six boats but we cannot sail out to the sea. I guess we have to have these nuclear plans, but I really want the leaking of the radioactive materials into the sea to stop." 
5. Close of ropes tied to boats
6. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Mataichi Saito, 74 year-old fisherman:  
"Even if we catch fish, it is impossible for us to sell the fish because of the plant accident."
7. Various of empty Shiogama Fish Market
8. Pan of empty cases for fish
9. Various of empty baskets 
10. Tilt down of fish shop 
11. Tilt up of Tomoaki Sato, aquaculture farmer and shop owner 
12. Close of seaweed farmed by Sato
13. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Tomoaki Sato, 60 year-old aquaculture farmer and shop owner: 
"We have to clean the sea water first and it is difficult to rebuild local farms just by Shiogama city, so we need to get help from the Japanese government. Otherwise, it will take more than five years."
14. Various of Oysters that was farmed by Sato 
STORYLINE
Residents in the small seaside city of Shiogama in Miyagi, the prefecture that took the full impact of tsunami, face a long battle to restore their normal lives.
The city's fishermen still haven't managed to get out to sea after tsunami destroyed many of their boats and coastal radiation leaks cast a shadow on Japanese fisheries.
Following the March 11th earthquake and tsunami, the crippled Fukushima Dai-ichi nuclear plant has leaked radiation into the environment and radioactive water gushed into the Pacific Ocean.
This week, the government set its first-ever standard for the amount of radiation allowed in fish after levels in waters near the plant measured several million times the legal limit and elevated amounts were found in some fish.
Mataichi Saito, 74 year-old fisherman from Shiogama voiced the frustration of some of the fishermen from the city. 
"Even if we catch fish, it is impossible for us to sell the fish because of the plant accident," he said.
Aquaculture of oyster and seaweed is also the main industry in Shiogama city, but the farms were badly destroyed by Tsunami.
Tomoaki Sato, 60 year-old aquaculture farmer who owns a fish shop says farmers like him need to receive help from the government.
Cleaning piles of rubble on the ground is making remarkable progress, but not the contaminated sea water.  
At the plant, 140 miles (220 kilometres) northeast of Tokyo, workers finally halted a leak of highly contaminated water that raised worry about the safety of seafood caught off the coast.
But even that rare good news came with a caveat. 
Highly contaminated water pooling around the plant has often made it difficult or impossible for workers to access some areas because of concerns about radiation exposure. 
The Japanese government has announced that the government was taking the maximum allowable radiation limit for vegetables and extending it to fish.
The coastal areas hit by the 11 March tsunami make up about a fifth of Japan's huge fishing industry, but radiation fears could taint all of the country's catch through guilt by association. 
Japan imports far more fish than it exports, but it sent the world 2.3 (b) billion US dollars worth of seafood last year.

items.title: Tsunami survivor returns to ruins to salvage beloved motorbike
items.description:
1. Pan of partially destroyed Onagawa city
2. Mid of car that has been lifted by the tsunami onto the roof of a building
3. Wide of destruction    
4. Wide of Kiyoshi Hiratsuka and his family near the rubble that was their house    
5. Various of Hiratsuka and family walking through the rubble        
6. Wide of Hiratsuka lifting up rubble
7. Close up of Kiyoshi Hiratsuka trying to pull out his motorbike from the rubble    
8. Mid of Hiratsuka and family members trying to pull out the motorbike from the rubble    
9. Hiratsuka checking the motorbike    
10. SOUNDBITE: (Japanese) Kiyoshi Hiratsuka mechanic, 37 years old, from Oganawa:    
"I love my bike, I know the priority is the safety of my family but they are safe now. I almost gave up the search but it happened that I found it. I know that the motorbike would not work anymore but I want to keep it as a memorial."    
11. Close up of Hiratsuka's hand checking the motorbike   
12. Hiratsuka checking the motorbike
STORYLINE
One survivor on Sunday celebrated being reunited with a prized possession thought lost or destroyed in Japan's natural disasters.
Kiyoshi Hiratsuka searched all day for his much beloved Harley Davidson in the ruins of his hometown, Onagawa.
The once vibrant fishing town was obliterated when the devastating tsunami that followed the earthquake converted it into a landscape of death and destruction.
Residents say half of the town's' 10-thousand people are gone.
Digging in the rubble of what was once his home, Hiratsuka eventually found the handlebars of his Harley sticking out from the debris.
The 37-year-old mechanic explained his relief at finding the bike, saying he wanted to keep it as a memorial to the losses suffered by Japan in the disasters that struck on 11 March.

items.title: Temporary homes built to house those displaced by quake and tsunami
items.description:
SHOTLIST :
1. Wide pan from evacuation centre to construction site
2. Various of workers building prefabricated homes
3. Close up of builder on construction site 
4. Set up of construction manager, Tsutomu Nakai looking at map
5. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Tsutomu Nakai, Construction manager :
"The day before yesterday, on 19 March, at Rikuzentakata municipal junior high school, we started the construction of the housing and we plan to build one hundred and thirty six homes. Now it's the first stage so only thirty six homes will be built. We hope to complete the first stage by the end of March and in early April thirty six families will move into the houses."
6. Wide pan of people in evacuation centre
7. People, including evacuee Akiko Oikawa, in centre
8. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Akiko Oikawa, Evacuee :
"I think it will be difficult for us to move into the housing in early April but if the situation permits we'll move later and we'll have some privacy."
9. Akiko and family in evacuation centre
STORYLINE:
Construction of temporary housing has begun in Rikuzentakata, a coastal city which was severely damaged by last week's devastating earthquake and tsunami in which thousands of people were killed.
The 30 square metre (215 square feet) prefabricated houses, capable of accommodating two to three people, were being built in the grounds of a junior high school.
The port city of Rikuzentakata, was home to 20-thousand people before the disaster.  Now most of them have left the area or are staying in evacuations centres.
The construction site for the temporary housing is next to one of the area's largest evacuation centres.
Construction manager Tsutomu Nakai said they were building the first phase of housing and hoped it would be ready in April.
Evacuee Akiko Oikawa said she would be surprised if the housing was ready by then.
"I think it will be difficult for us to move into the housing in early April but if the situation permits we'll move later and we'll have some privacy," she said.
Japan is continuing to grapple with the overwhelming consequences of the cascade of disasters caused by a 9.0-magnitude earthquake on March 11.
The quake caused the tsunami which ravaged Japan's northeastern coast and also damaged the Fukushima Dai-ichi nuclear plant, which has since been leaking radiation.

items.title: Mass grave prepared for bodies of disaster victims
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Soldiers carrying coffin to mass grave, outskirt of Higashi Matsushima City
2. Soldiers putting down coffin 
3. Relatives praying beside mass grave
4. Close of woman weeping
5. Soldiers carrying coffin 
6. Wide of relatives standing next to coffins
7. Close of flower being placed on dead body
8. Woman crying
9. Pan interior of Higashi Matsushima city hall
10. Officials working
11. SOUNDBITE (Japanese) Takashi Takayama, 55 years old official:
"We have to get permission form the relatives before we send the dead victim to the mass grave."  
12. Wide of family members burying the victims
13. Close of coffin being buried
14. Woman burying her dead relative while crying
15. Low angle shot of soldiers carrying coffin 
STORYLINE
Relatives gathered to bury their loved ones during a burial ceremony at a mass grave in the outskirt of Higashi Matsushima city on Tuesday.
Hundreds of dead have washed ashore on Japan's devastated northeast coast since the earthquake and tsunami struck Japan earlier this month. 
Others were dug out of the debris earlier by firefighters using pickaxes and chain saws.
Funeral homes and crematoriums are overwhelmed, and officials have run out of body bags and coffins.
The tsunami triggered by the powerful earthquake on March 11 has killed 658 people and left more than 1000 people missing in Higashi Matsushima city in Miyagi prefecture.
Local city official Takashi Takayama said half of the city was flooded and they were trying to deal with the shortage of water, electricity and fuel.
Miyagi prefecture bore the full force of Friday's tsunami, and police has said several bodies were found scattered across its coast. 
In Miyagi, the police chief has estimated 10,000 deaths in his province alone.
Most Japanese opt to cremate their dead, and with so many bodies, the government has waived a rule requiring permission first from local authorities before cremation or burial to speed up funerals, according to a Health Ministry official.
But the permission from the victim's family is required before they send the bodies to the mass grave. 
According to Takayama, the city of Higashi Matsushima has only one crematorium that can handle a limited number of bodies a day.
The city government plans to hold burial ceremony four times a day and they have helped to bury 22 dead victims on Tuesday.

items.title: Doctors battle shortages in evacuation centre clinic
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Pan shot from Japanese Red Cross car to Japanese Red Cross Clinic
2. Close-up of medical staff working in clinic seen through window
3. Mid of sign for clinic in corridor with medical worker wearing face mask and patients in background
4. Tracking shot of patient Tetsuro Murakuni, being examined by doctor
5. Tilt up from chart to doctor's face
6. Pan from medical staff to doctor talking to Murakuni
7. SOUNDBITE: (Japanese) Tetsuro Murakuni, 73, patient:
"This clinic is very helpful for me. I don't have gasoline, roads are closed because of debris. It's really helped me." 
8. Various of medicine on shelf
9. Medium of nurses working
10. Close-up of nurses' hands
11. SOUNDBITE: (Japanese) Dr. Usui Tomomichi, 46, doctor at the Morioka Red Cross Hospital:
"It has been one week since the big earthquake hit the area. The situation here is calming down. The biggest problem here is shortage of medicine. The confusion among patients is calming down, because seriously injured patients are sent to big hospitals. The main mission of the clinic is to give regular medication to our patients." 
12. Cutaway of medical staff
13. SOUNDBITE (Japanese): Dr. Usui Tomomichi, 46, doctor at the Morioka Red Cross Hospital:
"I think numbers of patients with mental illness will increase from now on. They've lost their house, they've lost their family members, and they survived somehow. But they'll think how am I going to live from now on? What has happened to my goals for the future?' They will wonder, 'What's the purpose of my life?'" 
14. Wide of vehicles outside evacuation centre which houses the clinic
STORYLINE
A clinic in the northeastern Japanese city of Rikuzentakata was full to bursting point on Saturday with patients who need medicine, but that medicine was in short supply. 
The clinic has been set up by the Japanese Red Cross to treat survivors of last week's devastating earthquake and tsunami in which an estimated more than 10-thousand people were killed.
The port city of Rikuzentakata, was home to 20-thousand people before the disaster.
Tetsuro Murakuni, 73, said the clinic has been his lifeline.
He needs daily medicine for high blood pressure, but the tsunami ruined most of his supply. 
Murakuni could not drive to the hospital as there was no gas for his car, and even if there had been, the piles of debris clogging the road would make the journey impossible.
"This clinic is very helpful for me," he said. 
Transportation between Tokyo and the tsunami zone has been disrupted, meaning supplies aren't getting to those in need fast enough.
There are two shelves stocked with various boxes of pills, and two suitcases filled with gauze, syringes and bandages. But there is hardly enough to meet demand.
"The biggest problem here is shortage of medicine," said Dr. Usui Tomomichi, from the Morioka Red Cross Hospital. 
Tomomichi said it is not just the patients' physical health that is suffering, it is their mental health as well. 
Doctors are beginning to see a rise in both depression and anxiety.
"They've lost their house, they've lost their family members, and they survived somehow," said Tomomichi. 
"But they'll think how am I going to live from now on? What has happened to my goals for the future?' They will wonder, 'What's the purpose of my life?'" 
Japan is continuing to grapple with overwhelming consequences of the cascade of disasters caused by a 9.0-magnitude earthquake on March 11.
The quake caused a tsunami that ravaged Japan's northeastern coast, killing more than 7,200 people and knocking out backup cooling systems at a nuclear plant in Fukushima, which has been leaking radiation.

items.title: Fishing boat which became symbol of 2011 tsunami to be dismantled
items.description:
A symbolic landmark of the Japan's devastating tsunami - a 360-ton (330 metric ton) ship stranded inland - was shown to the media on Saturday for one last time before it is completely dismantled.
In March 2011, a magnitude 9.0 earthquake offshore of northeastern Japan, and the ensuing tsunami, killed more than 18-thousand people and devastated the coastline for hundreds of miles (kilometres).
The destruction caused by the tsunami came to be symbolised in a handful of iconic landmarks - including the 60 metre-long and 360-ton fishing vessel, the "No.18 Kyotokumaru." 
Workers began dismantling the stranded fishing boat early last month after a citywide vote showed the majority of the residents voted to have the ship destroyed.
A non-profit organisation based in Hokkaido was contracted for the dismantling process. 
Kazumichi Shimizu, Professor at the Muroran Institute of Technology who heads the non-profit organisation, said the dismantling process had taken longer than expected, but was nearly done.
"Within a week, most of the dismantling will be complete," he said.
Shimizu said the biggest task was to separate the large amounts of foam material used for padding in the ship's water tanks, from the scrap metal. 
This will need to be done by hand.
Workers began the dismantling process last month by first pumping out fuel and oil from the ship, followed by the dismantling of the ship's wheelhouse on the upper deck, cabin interiors, and the engine room, using gas burners to tear the steel apart.
Currently, large construction cutters are being used to cut away the central section of the ship.
All this is done behind a 3-metre-high enclosure, built as a safety precaution and in consideration for local residents.
About 500 metric tons of scrap metal from the ship will be recycled for various uses within Japan including vehicle parts, Shimizu said.
The dismantling comes after much debate among the city's residents and government officials over the fate of the "Kyotokumaru."
Kesennuma's mayor spent the last two years urging the ship's owners to allow the city to keep the vessel as a memorial for the devastation caused by the tsunami, but neither the ship's owner, nor many of the city's residents agreed.
Opinion on the ship had been so divided it had been put to a vote by the city residents in July. 
Of the 14,083 responses, 68 per cent, or 9,622 people, voted to have the ship destroyed. 
Only 16 per cent voted to keep it.
In light of the results, in August the city announced the vessel would be torn down.
Toshiko Chiba, a 73-year-old resident of Kesennuma, had voted to keep the ship, saying the vessel could have served as a reminder for future generations.
"That tsunami brought such an enormous ship (inland), and so I wished that people could see the sheer strength (of the tsunami)," she said.
For now, she keeps a postcard of the "No.18 Kyotokumaru" at home.

items.title: Sunrise over Kesennuma, a city devastated by the quake and tsunami two years ago
items.description:
11 March 2013
1. Wide of sunrise over Kesennuma city, Miyagi prefecture 
2. Pan across flattened city, covered in snow, during sunrise 
3. Wide of stranded ship on land 
4. Low shot of flowers placed on ground near ship
5. Tilt up of remains of buildings 
6. Pull focus from plant to excavator in distance 
7. Wide of remains of buildings, excavator 
8. Pan across Koushirou Sato, Kesennuma resident, walking along snow-covered street
9. SOUNDBITE: (Japanese) Koushirou Sato, 85, Kesennuma resident:
"The size of the community is going to be much smaller, but people who have been working in the fishing industry, the businesses, they know how to do it best here, so I think they'll stay."
10. Various of Kenichi Oi, Kesennuma resident, taking photos in port area
11. SOUNDBITE: (Japanese) Kenichi Oi, 75, Kesennuma resident:
"It's scary living here. When there is an earthquake, it's scary, but I don't plan to go anywhere else. I want to give my very best, somehow, towards the reconstruction of the city."
FILE: 13 March 2011
12. Various aerial shots show damage across Kesennuma city 
FILE: 11 March 2011
13. Various of the moment the tsunami hit the shoreline, cars in water
14. Various of fires burning
STORYLINE:
As Japan marks the second anniversary of a devastating earthquake and tsunami, residents of one affected city have been reflecting on the scale and complexity of the recovery effort. 
The 11 March 2011 disasters, which were followed by a nuclear catastrophe, left more than 1,000 people dead in Kesennuma in Miyagi prefecture. 
On Monday, a thin blanket of snow covered vast swathes of land in the city where buildings once stood. 
More than 15,000 homes were either damaged or destroyed, forcing survivors to live in temporary accommodation further inland.
Despite the scale of devastation, some residents hope they will be able to move back and rebuild their community - one that made its living from the fishing industry. 
"The size of the community is going to be much smaller, but people who have been working in the fishing industry, the businesses, they know how to do it best here, so I think they'll stay," said resident Koushirou Sato.
Kenichi Oi, who was born in Kesennuma, runs a fishing company. 
The tsunami washed away his boats in 2011, but he has since bought two new vessels and hopes to get his business up and running once again.  
"I want to give my very best, somehow, towards the reconstruction of the city," he said. 
Across all affected areas, more than 300,000 people are still displaced and virtually no rebuilding has begun.
The government plans to spend 25 trillion yen (268 billion US dollars) for the entire reconstruction effort. 
However, less than half of the eight trillion yen (85.7 billion US dollars) allocated so far has been used.
Memorial services are planned on Monday in Tokyo along the battered northeastern coast to mark the moment the magnitude-9.0 quake struck.
It was the strongest recorded in Japan's history, unleashing the massive tsunami that killed a total of nearly 19,000 people.
Some 160,000 evacuees remain uncertain if they will ever be able to return to abandoned homes around the Fukushima Dai-ichi nuclear power plant, where rectors melted down after the tsunami.
On Monday, about 800 people plan to file a lawsuit against the government and utility owner demanding compensation and that all land and homes be restored to their state before 11 March, 2011.

items.title: IAEA inspects Onagawa nuclear power plant hit by 2011 quake
items.description:
STORYLINE:
A group of experts from the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) on Tuesday inspected a Japanese nuclear power plant which avoided catastrophe when it was hit by last year's tsunami.
The Onagawa plant lies just north of the now-infamous Fukushima plant that was badly damaged when it was struck by the devastating March 2011 earthquake and tsunami.
The 20-member IAEA mission, the first to visit Onagawa nuclear plant since the disaster, aims to find out the extent of the damage caused by the magnitude 9.0 quake. 
Three reactors at Onagawa suffered temblors that exceeded the maximum they were designed to withstand.
The basement of one of the plant's reactor buildings flooded, but the plant was able to maintain its cooling capacity. 
The IAEA mission, led by seismologist Sujit Samaddar, will spend two weeks carrying out an inspection of the facilities within the compound.
Experts hope their findings will help to improve nuclear safety standards around the world.
Last year's tsunami caused seawater to flood the cooling system chamber, located three floors below ground level.
The pipes coming out of the wall burst and flooded the room with water levels reaching 2.5 metres (8 feet), but the damage to operations was minimal.
The anti-tsunami wall at Onagawa was built to be twice the height of what was considered necessary by its operator Tohoku Electric Power Co, which helped limit the damage.
The operator of Fukushima Dai-ichi nuclear plant, Tokyo Electric Power Co (TEPCO) has been criticised for failing to put defensive measures in place, despite a history of quakes and tsunamis in the region.
A series of investigation reports, including one released earlier this month by a government-appointed panel, partly blamed a lack of foresight for the crisis.
The reports also criticised collusion among the government, regulators and TEPCO. 
Strong anti-nuclear sentiment has been growing in recent weeks with daily peaceful demonstrations in the capital Tokyo.
But for people living near Onagawa, one of the areas most severely devastated by the tsunami, survival and recovery take precedence.
"Who has time to worry about the nuclear power plant?" said local fisherman Eiichi Inoue. 
"The tsunami took everything we owned. We just don't have time to think about it,"

items.title: Tsunami disaster - young apprentices help rebuild fisherman's ruined business ++REPLAY++
items.description:
LEADIN
The fishing industry in Northern Japan is still struggling with the challenges of recovering from the earthquake and tsunami disaster of 2011.
One fisherman has spent the last three years rebuilding his oyster farm.
Now, he's enlisted the help of a handful of young apprentices in the hope they'll bring some much-needed fresh blood to the industry.
STORYLINE
Like thousands of fishermen along the Pacific coastline of Northern Japan, oyster farmer Hiromitsu Itou lost his home, his fishing boats, and his farm of oysters to the tsunami of 2011.
With much of the distribution routes and fish markets still to be rebuilt, many fisheries are struggling to survive, 
But Itou is one of a small group of fishermen who are charting new paths with the hopes of expanding their business.
Having taken over his father's oyster farm in Ogatsu around a decade ago, Itou had just taken out a loan for new equipment when the quake hit.
With nothing remaining after the tsunami, he had to start his entire business from scratch, but he did so in a way unheard of in a small town known for passing the legacy of fishing down through generations.
Itou and a handful of business partners in the fishing industry formed their own company, and started selling straight to customers online and raising money through memberships.
The money raised meant some local fishermen could rebuild - and for Itou, an opportunity to expand his direct sales - a rarity in an industry which usually relies on a tradition of customs and rules.
"This year is the real deal, it's the make-it-or break-it year.  I think we do have the marketing power, but I want to expand on that and go head on," says Itou.
"Many people say we're in the phase of reconstruction, but we're really still in recovery phase - we're still far off from reconstructing. Real reconstruction will take 5 or 10 years, and then perhaps then, we may be able to look back and say "I'm glad I worked hard back then" - that's what reconstruction is."
To expand operations, Itou has enlisted the help of a handful of young city dwellers - one of them being his own nephew.
23-year-old Yuuki Miura had no plans to follow in his family's footsteps and was training to become a cook in Sendai city when the quake struck. 
The devastation prompted him to rethink his role in keeping the family business - he left his job just 8 months after the quake struck to join his uncle.
"When I was small, I lived with my grandfather and I grew up watching him work. But the tsunami came right after the business was handed over to his next generation - and so I thought, I have to help." says Miura.
The quake hasn't just brought one local youngster back into the industry, it's spurred a host of industry outsiders to get involved.
31-year-old Mitsuhiro Inoue worked as a forklift operator at a warehouse in Sendai city for more than 10 years, before an acquaintance introduced him to part-time fishery work - a position which turned full time last July.
Still less than a year into the job, he's hoping to do more.
"I'd like to try and haul the oysters myself - but I don't have a license yet, so all I can do is to get on the boat with them," he says.
28-year-old Sendai city native, Takayuki Yokota, was jobless when he met Itou at an oyster festival. 
A former baseball player, Yokota says he felt the younger generation had their part to play in sustaining the area's fishing industry.
He claims fishermen - like Itou - are often "stubborn" and not always the best at marketing when dealing directly with restaurant managers.
"I think we're right in the middle - in the sense that we can be a bridge between the wishes of fishermen and wishes of restaurants, and by doing so expand on marketing and find more clients," he says.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/94c2e2dde1093fdc13f37d0131ed283b 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: 仙石東北ライン 新型車両 HB-E210系 石巻駅・仙台駅 Debut of New Hybrid Train
items.description:
2015年6月8日撮影 東日本大震災から約4年2ヵ月、本年5月30日仙台～石巻間を結ぶ仙石線が全線で復旧し運行再開しました。これに伴い沿線の復興支援を目的に東北本線と仙石線を直通させた「仙石東北ライン」が新たに誕生。（接続線は東北本線側は塩釜駅～松島駅間から、仙石線側は松島海岸駅～高城町駅間から）
それぞれ電化方式が違う為、また接続線が非電化となる為、この新ルートで運行する新型ハイブリッド車両が誕生しました。
その新型ハイブリッド車両「HB-E210系」を石巻駅と仙台駅で撮影しました。

About four years and two months have passed since the Great East Japan Earthquake occurred.  On May 30 of this year, the Senseki Line that connects between Sendai and Ishinomaki was restored in the entire section, and resumed full operation.  At this opportunity, with the purpose of supporting the reconstruction of the areas along the Senseki Line, the “Senseki Tohoku Line,” which directly runs between the Tohoku Main Line and the Senseki Line, was newly born.

This is the video image of “HB-E210 Series,” a new hybrid train, running the new route.

Location:Ishinomaki Station,Sendai Station

撮影機材:SONY HDR -CX630V
