items.title: Tsunami Kuji-shi 久慈市 Miyagi, Japan 2011年3月11日 — Remastered
items.description: The official Japan Coast Guard 海上保安庁 video of the March 11, 2011 post 9.0MW earthquake tsunami making landfall striking Kuji City in Miyagi Prefecture, Japan at around 3:25 p.m. [JT]. The seismic events struck the Tōhoku Region on the Northeastern coastline of Japan. The earthquake was the largest in that nation’s written history. The video was released to the public in April 2011 by the Japan Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism that has oversight of the Coast Guard.

items.title: Tsunami Sendai-shi 仙台市 宮城県 Miyagi, Japan 2011年3月11日 NHK Live — Remastered Video
items.description:
On Friday, March 11, 2011 at 2:46 p.m. (JST), a 9.0 magnitude earthquake struck Japan. It was located in the Pacific Ocean 231 miles northeast of Tokyo at a shallow depth of 15.2 miles. It was the largest and longest earthquake in Japan's recorded history. The earthquake caused the most damage in the Tōhoku Region hitting the Miyagi Prefecture the worst.

The earthquake causes a tsunami that started hitting Japan's Northeastern coast between 10 to 50 minutes after the primary shaker ended. The tsunami waves reached nearly 70 feet in some seaside cities and towns and destroyed major harbors and ports.

On Friday, March 11, 2011 at 2:46 p.m. (JST), a 9.0 magnitude earthquake struck Japan. It was located in the Pacific Ocean 231 miles northeast of Tokyo at a shallow depth of 15.2 miles. It was the largest and longest earthquake in Japan's recorded history. The earthquake caused the most damage in the Tōhoku Region.

The earthquake caused tsunami started hitting Japan's Northeastern coast between 10 to 90 minutes after the primary shaker ended. The tsunami waves reached nearly 70 feet in some seaside cities and towns. Many major harbors and ports, including their breakwaters and dikes, were destroyed entire.

Ōtsuchi-chō is a town located in Kamihei District, Iwate, Japan. Since 1973, the University of Tokyo has maintained a marine research laboratory in Ōtsuchi. It is now called the International Coastal Research Center (ICRC) and is managed by the Atmosphere and Ocean Research Institute of Japan.

After the tsunami fuel used by the fishing boats spilled from ruptured storage tanks and caught fire. The flames engulfed the tanks containing the fuel and burned tsunami debris floating on the not completely receded waters. The fires spread and burned for four days. Officials said as of April 22, 2011 the city had confirmed 837 deaths with 1,196 missing.

The island of Oshima and its 3,000 residents are included in the city Kesennuma city limits. Oshima was isolated after the tsunami due to damaged ferry connections.

items.title: Tsunami Kesennuma 気仙沼市 Japan Coast Guard Video 2011年3月11日 — Remastered
items.description:
Kesennuma-shi 気仙沼市
Miyagi Prefecture 宮城県, Japan
Kesennuma Bay Narrows
Video recorded from the
     Japan Coast Guard Building
2011年3月11日

In background, the Miyagi Prefecture Building

On Friday, March 11, 2011 at 2:46 p.m. (JST), a 9.0 magnitude earthquake struck Japan. It was located in the Pacific Ocean 231 miles northeast of Tokyo at a shallow depth of 15.2 miles. It was the largest and longest earthquake in Japan's recorded history. The earthquake caused the most damage in the Tōhoku Region on Honshu Island the worst.

The earthquake caused tsunami started hitting Japan's Northeastern coast between 10 to 90 minutes after the primary shaker ended. The tsunami waves reached nearly 70 feet in some seaside cities and towns. Many major harbors and ports, including their breakwaters and dikes, were destroyed entire.

The island of Oshima and its 3,000 residents are included in the Kesennuma city limits. Oshima was isolated after the tsunami due to damaged ferry connections. After the tsunami fuel used by the fishing boats spilled from ruptured storage tanks and caught fire. The flames engulfed the tanks containing the fuel and burned tsunami debris floating on the not completely receded waters. The fires spread and burned for four days. Officials said as of April 22, 2011 the city had confirmed 837 deaths with 1,196 missing.

The Japan Coast Guard released this video into the public domain in April 2011.

REMASTERED & RESTORED:
Video returned to original quality level, contrast and saturation; audio corrected and repaired to two track stereo.

On Friday, March 11, 2011 at 2:46 p.m. (JST), a 9.0 magnitude earthquake struck Japan. It was located in the Pacific Ocean 231 miles northeast of Tokyo at a shallow depth of 15.2 miles. It was the largest and longest earthquake in Japan's recorded history. The earthquake caused the worst damage in the Tōhoku Region on Honshu Island.

The video recording here was made by a teenage schoolgirl at 南三陸町 Minamisanriku-chō in Miyagi Prefecture 宮城県 from the hill where her school was located. Nearly 90 percent of Minamisanriku was destroyed by tsunami. The neighboring cities of Mesennuma and Ishinomaki in Miyagi were also greatly impacted by the tsunami.

The earthquake caused tsunami started hitting Japan's Northeastern coast between 10 to 90 minutes after the primary shaker ended. The tsunami waves reached nearly 70 feet in some seaside cities and towns. Many major harbors and ports, including their breakwaters and dikes, were destroyed entire.

items.title: 仙石東北ライン HB-E210系 快速 石巻～仙台 ダイジェスト車窓 Scenery from a Train window
items.description:
再生リストhttps://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLG2FOfMxsIvmdRALi-JkJGZKUvVPJLzXc

2015年6月8日撮影 東日本大震災から約4年2ヵ月、本年5月30日石巻～仙台間を結ぶ仙石線が全線で復旧し運行再開しました。これに伴い沿線の復興支援を目的に仙石線と東北本線を直通させた「仙石東北ライン」が新たに誕生。（接続線は仙石線側は高城町駅～松島海岸駅間から、東北本線側は松島駅～塩釜間から）
それぞれ電化方式が違う為、また接続線が非電化となる為、この新ルートで運行する新型ハイブリッド車両が誕生しました。

その新型ハイブリッド車両「HB-E210系」快速の石巻駅～仙台駅間のダイジェスト車窓(進行方向右・陸側)です。

野蒜駅到着 08:10
高城町駅到着 12:30
東北本線接続地点 15:10
東仙台駅到着 30:50

About four years and two months have passed since the Great East Japan Earthquake occurred.  On May 30 of this year, the Senseki Line that connects between Sendai and Ishinomaki was restored in the entire section, and resumed full operation.  At this opportunity, with the purpose of supporting the reconstruction of the areas along the Senseki Line, the “Senseki Tohoku Line,” which directly runs between the Tohoku Main Line and the Senseki Line, was newly born.
This video is from the window of the Type HB-E210 Senseki Tohoku Line.

The video was taken from Ishinomaki station to Sendai station.

items.description:
震災の被害から完全復活！全線再開した仙石線の駅を途中下車。最初は多賀城駅です。
駅周辺には和歌の題材に使われた名所が数多くあるらしく、今回は末の松山や沖の井へ行ってみました。
----------------------------------------
Tagajo Station is located in Miyagi Prefecture in the Tohoku region .
When the Great East Japan Earthquake , tsunami flow back to Sunaoshi River near the station , the town was flooded .

items.title: 【駅トホ54】野蒜駅の旧駅舎(仙石線)2014年夏訪問-Nobiru【青春18きっぷ2015夏-3の1】
items.description:
青春18きっぷで仙石線巡り。多賀城駅の次に訪問したのは東名駅と野蒜駅なのですが、新駅舎をアップする前に2014年に訪問した
野蒜駅の旧駅舎を紹介します。復旧前に旧駅舎を見たことがきっかけで仙石線が気になり、2年連続で訪問しようと決めたので、流れ的に旧駅舎は先にご紹介したかったのです。
----------------------------------------
This video has been shooting the old station building of Nobiru Station . Nobiru Station was the base of the Okumatsushima tourism .
However , Nobiru Station received a serious damage by the Great East Japan Earthquake .
Currently , the old station building of Nobiru Station has been used as a resting place of citizens .

items.title: 【駅トホ55】新駅舎の東名～野蒜駅間を散策(仙石線)＆ラーメン-Nobiru【青春18きっぷ2015夏-3の2】
items.description:
前回の野蒜駅旧駅舎に引き続き、野蒜駅と東名駅の新駅舎です。2駅間では新たな町づくりが進んでいるみたいで駅前は絶賛開発工事中でした。
途中にラーメンが美味しいと有名な店があるそうなので、訪問。潮の香りがたっぷりのアサリラーメンを食べました。美味しかったです。
野蒜駅の新駅舎はまだまだ新築の香りがします。小高い丘の上にあるので、奥松島を見ることができました。キレイだったな。
----------------------------------------
I travel the Miyagi Prefecture . I walked between the Touna station and Nobiru Station .
Touna Station and Nobiru Station received a serious damage in the Great East Japan Earthquake of March 11, 2011 .
The old station building becomes unusable , now I have been using the new station building .
Currently , the previous is progressing land development new station building .

items.title: Massive 9.0 Earthquake and Japan Tsunami Iwate Prefecture March 11, 2011
items.description: I was visiting northern Japan as a volunteer for Ric O'Barry's Dolphin Project on March 11, 2011 when a record breaking 9.0 earthquake rocked the Japanese coast.   I was standing outside of my rented car when the quake initially struck and it was nearly impossible to remain standing, but over the next 3-minutes I was able to get back to the car to retrieve my camera and began documenting the shaking.  Without hesitation, I immediately sought a high point as a vertical shelter in case of a tsunami - that decision saved my life!  I documented the resulting tsunami from atop of a hill that overlooked Otsuchi Harbor.  This is a small percentage of the entire video that I recorded.

items.title: 【駅トホ56】石ノ森ワールド☆石巻駅(仙石線)-Ishinomaki【青春18きっぷ2015夏-4】
items.description:
石ノ森萬画館で有名な石巻駅は駅も町も石ノ森章太郎さんのキャラクターでいっぱい！
駅も町も可愛い感じになっています。宿泊のための下車だったので朝と夜しか散策の時間がとれず石ノ森萬画館は行けませんでした。
その代わり、朝から240段の階段をのぼって羽黒山鳥屋神社に参拝に行ってきました。
----------------------------------------
I visited Ishinomaki , Miyagi Prefecture .
Ishinomaki is famous as the land of the great cartoonist Shotaro Ishinomori of Shoen . 
Ishinomaki has received extensive damage in the Great East Japan Earthquake , now has regained vigor .

items.title: 【駅トホ車窓展望】石巻線・女川駅～小牛田駅間-Ishinomaki Line【青春18きっぷ2015夏-4】
items.description:
一時は東日本大震災によって、全線不通になった石巻線。
朝の8時3分に乗車したときは、学生でごったがえし、明るい笑い声に満ちていました。
田園風景と綺麗な海が同時に楽しめる、車窓マニアにはたまらない路線のひとつです。
----------------------------------------
Ishinomaki Line is a railway line in the Miyagi Prefecture .
Ishinomaki Line is devastated by the Great East Japan Earthquake , one time was a whole line interruption .
Ishinomaki Line was whole line restoration March 21, 2015 .
Currently, echoing laughter of local students in Ishinomaki Line

items.title: 【駅トホ57】女川駅(石巻線)新駅舎訪問-Onagawa【青春18きっぷ2015夏-4】
items.description:
｢新しい女川に生まれ変わるんだ｣というスローガンの通り、女川駅も生まれ変わりました。
宮城の杉板を使った温かみある駅舎には、物産展や町営温泉施設｢ゆぽっぽ｣など見所たくさん。
駅前も生まれ変わるために、絶賛開発中。テーマパークを彷彿されるムードの良さに、これからが楽しみになるのでした。
----------------------------------------
Onagawa is a port city located in Miyagi Prefecture .
When the Great East Japan Earthquake , Onagawa has suffered extensive damage .
However , Onagawa Station was restored on March 21, 2015 .
Around the station also redevelopment advances , Onagawa are beginning increments a new history .

The gunman apparently was cornered in a van along Interstate 45 near Hutchins. Unconfirmed reports indicated that more shots had been fired at that location.

People began reporting shortly before 12:30 a.m. that that a gunman had fired into Jack Evans Police Headquarters on Lamar Street, south of downtown, but authorities had not released any details officially.

Initial eyewitness reports indicated that no ambulances had been called to the police building, and there were no reports of injuries yet.

One woman who said she lives nearby posted online that the gunfire she heard sounded like a shootout.

items.title: TFT  Thought Field Therapy in Dallas, Plano, Richardson Texas and DFW
items.description:
Introduction to Thought Field Therapy (TFT) an early treatment utilizing acupressure for the mind and emotions.  The video provides some information on how TFT started and how powerful it is as a treatment for phobias, anxiety, trauma and panic attacks.  This is one of the therapy methods that Steve B. Reed, LPC, LMSW, LMFT uses to treat people in the Dallas, Plano, Richardson, Texas and DFW area.

Video Transcript:
TFT, 2003, www.psychotherapy-center.com
First, I probably need to go back to the work
of Dr. Roger Callahan who developed a method
call all Thought Field Therapy
TFT was one of the first acupressure
based interventions to help people
alleviate mental and emotional distress.
in fact all the work talking about today
might  neatly fall under the title of
acupressure for the mind and emotions.
In fact this is radically different paradigm
for treating mental and
emotional distress. In traditional therapies,
cognitive interventions, basically trying to change the way people
think about a problem has been utilized.  Behavioral interventions, changing
the way one behaves has been utilized, and other techniques as well.
Steve B. Reed, LPC, LMSW, LMFT.  But this is a very new
way of looking at intervening upon mental and emotional distress.
Start of TFT.  In the late 70s, Dr.
Roger Callahan was exposed to
some work that some chiropractors were doing.  And they had begun to experiment 
with the use of
acupuncture, rather than acupuncture, 
actually just a gentle pressure or tapping on the acupuncture point
rather than using needles, to try to intervene at an
emotional level. A friend of his invited him to a demonstration
and he was actually quite impressed with what he saw.
He took some training and
begin to work on his own then to experiment with and
explore the development of a method which
eventually became Thought Field Therapy.
Story of Mary.  One of the stories that he told when I took
training with him a number of years ago was about
a lady named Mary that he work with.  Mary was an
individually who had a tremendous fear of water.
She'd had this fear
water as long as she could remember.  She did not like
to bathe in it.  She did not like to look at it.  She didn't like to 
drink it. She really wanted nothing
to do water.  Dr. Callahan
tried cognitive therapy with her, he'd been a cognitive therapist
for 40 years and I think he had worked at Albert Ellis's Cognitive therapy 
institute in Chicago . But 
he had attempted cognitive therapy as an intervention
and that wasn't working.  So
he then was trying a behavioral
intervention system referred to as systematic desensitization.
It is a fairly simple idea.  It's a technique in 
which one behaviorally, gradually, begins to approach something
that they feel a sense of fear about and at the
point that the fear begins to rise, they will do some
relaxation exercises to try to restore a state of
relaxation.  The basic idea is that fear and tension
and relaxation are mutually exclusive and cannot exist
at the same place at the same time.  So if you can get a person
relaxed enough that can help actually desensitize
their overly
sensitive response to the object of their fear. He had
invited Mary to his home where he had a large swimming pool.
And the protocol was to see how close she could
walk toward the swimming pool before
that state of fear would begin to
come upon her.  Well, he'd never gotten her within
20 feet of it basically. And it really wasn't going very well
so he was at his wits end.  And he asked her, he said, 
Mary would you be willing to try something
a little different like an experiment.  
She said, sure Dr. Callahan, I'd be glad to.  I'll try anything. 
And what he asked her to do 
was to hold an acupressure point. A spot just
below the eyes on the
upper part of the cheekbone.  And he asked her to
hold that and to gently tap it while
she thought about her fear of water.  She did so, and
that went on for a few minutes. And then all of a sudden
he reported that she stopped and said that's weird.
And he said what's weird?  And she says, that feeling
that I get in my stomach when I feel this fear of 
water, it's not there.  While Dr. Callahan
was thinking about this, she gets up and
bolts toward the swimming pool.  Now that freaked him out.
He thought, oh my gosh, it looks like she's going to jump in.
His first thought was, Mary you can't swim stop.  He yelled
that out and she just broke down laughing.  She says Dr. Callahan,
I'm no I can't swim.  I 
haven't lost my mind, but she said
I may have lost my fear.  And she went and
literally sat down by the pool, and he reported that she dropped
her feet in and splashed her feet in the pool like a little kid.
At that moment she did lose her fear and never had
another moment of panic or
fear or any other phobic responses about water from that point forward.
Steve B. Reed, LPC, LMSW, LMFT
 375 Municipal Drive, Suite 230, Richardson, Texas 75080

items.title: Matthew 22 Audio Bible
items.description:
Jesus spoke to them again in parables, saying,
"The kingdom of heaven may be compared to a king who gave a wedding feast for his son.
"And he sent out his slaves to call those who had been invited to the wedding feast, and they were unwilling to come.
"Again he sent out other slaves saying, 'Tell those who have been invited, "Behold, I have prepared my dinner; my oxen and my fattened livestock are all butchered and everything is ready; come to the wedding feast."'
"But they paid no attention and went their way, one to his own farm, another to his business,
and the rest seized his slaves and mistreated them and killed them.
"But the king was enraged, and he sent his armies and destroyed those murderers and set their city on fire.
"Then he said to his slaves, 'The wedding is ready, but those who were invited were not worthy.
'Go therefore to the main highways, and as many as you find there, invite to the wedding feast.'
"Those slaves went out into the streets and gathered together all they found, both evil and good; and the wedding hall was filled with dinner guests.
"But when the king came in to look over the dinner guests, he saw a man there who was not dressed in wedding clothes,
and he said to him, 'Friend, how did you come in here without wedding clothes?' And the man was speechless.
"Then the king said to the servants, 'Bind him hand and foot, and throw him into the outer darkness; in that place there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth.'
"For many are called, but few are chosen."
Then the Pharisees went and plotted together how they might trap Him in what He said.
And they sent their disciples to Him, along with the Herodians, saying, "Teacher, we know that You are truthful and teach the way of God in truth, and defer to no one; for You are not partial to any.
"Tell us then, what do You think? Is it lawful to give a poll-tax to Caesar, or not?"
But Jesus perceived their malice, and said, "Why are you testing Me, you hypocrites?
"Show Me the coin used for the poll-tax." And they brought Him a denarius.
And He said to them, "Whose likeness and inscription is this?"
They said to Him, "Caesar's." Then He said to them, "Then render to Caesar the things that are Caesar's; and to God the things that are God's."
And hearing this, they were amazed, and leaving Him, they went away.
On that day some Sadducees (who say there is no resurrection) came to Jesus and questioned Him,
asking, "Teacher, Moses said, 'IF A MAN DIES HAVING NO CHILDREN, HIS BROTHER AS NEXT OF KIN SHALL MARRY HIS WIFE, AND RAISE UP CHILDREN FOR HIS BROTHER.'
"Now there were seven brothers with us; and the first married and died, and having no children left his wife to his brother;
so also the second, and the third, down to the seventh.
"Last of all, the woman died.
"In the resurrection, therefore, whose wife of the seven will she be? For they all had married her."
But Jesus answered and said to them, "You are mistaken, not understanding the Scriptures nor the power of God.
"For in the resurrection they neither marry nor are given in marriage, but are like angels in heaven.
"But regarding the resurrection of the dead, have you not read what was spoken to you by God:
'I AM THE GOD OF ABRAHAM, AND THE GOD OF ISAAC, AND THE GOD OF JACOB'? He is not the God of the dead but of the living."
When the crowds heard this, they were astonished at His teaching.
But when the Pharisees heard that Jesus had silenced the Sadducees, they gathered themselves together.
One of them, a lawyer, asked Him a question, testing Him,
"Teacher, which is the great commandment in the Law?"
And He said to him, " 'YOU SHALL LOVE THE LORD YOUR GOD WITH ALL YOUR HEART, AND WITH ALL YOUR SOUL, AND WITH ALL YOUR MIND.'
"This is the great and foremost commandment.
"The second is like it, 'YOU SHALL LOVE YOUR NEIGHBOR AS YOURSELF.'
"On these two commandments depend the whole Law and the Prophets."
Now while the Pharisees were gathered together, Jesus asked them a question:
"What do you think about the Christ, whose son is He?" They said to Him, "The son of David."
He said to them, "Then how does David in the Spirit call Him 'Lord,' saying,
'THE LORD SAID TO MY LORD, "SIT AT MY RIGHT HAND, UNTIL I PUT YOUR ENEMIES BENEATH YOUR FEET"'?
"If David then calls Him 'Lord,' how is He his son?"
No one was able to answer Him a word, nor did anyone dare from that day on to ask Him another question.

items.title: Matthew 23 Audio Bible
items.description:
Then Jesus spoke to the crowds and to His disciples,
saying: "The scribes and the Pharisees have seated themselves in the chair of Moses;
therefore all that they tell you, do and observe, but do not do according to their deeds; for they say things and do not do them.
"They tie up heavy burdens and lay them on men's shoulders, but they themselves are unwilling to move them with so much as a finger.
"But they do all their deeds to be noticed by men; for they broaden their phylacteries and lengthen the tassels of their garments.
"They love the place of honor at banquets and the chief seats in the synagogues,
and respectful greetings in the market places, and being called Rabbi by men.
"But do not be called Rabbi; for One is your Teacher, and you are all brothers.
"Do not call anyone on earth your father; for One is your Father, He who is in heaven.
"Do not be called leaders; for One is your Leader, that is, Christ.
"But the greatest among you shall be your servant.
"Whoever exalts himself shall be humbled; and whoever humbles himself shall be exalted.
"But woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites, because you shut off the kingdom of heaven from people; for you do not enter in yourselves, nor do you allow those who are entering to go in.
"Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites, because you devour widows' houses, and for a pretense you make long prayers; therefore you will receive greater condemnation.
"Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites, because you travel around on sea and land to make one proselyte; and when he becomes one, you make him twice as much a son of hell as yourselves.
"Woe to you, blind guides, who say, 'Whoever swears by the temple, that is nothing; but whoever swears by the gold of the temple is obligated.'
"You fools and blind men! Which is more important, the gold or the temple that sanctified the gold?
"And, 'Whoever swears by the altar, that is nothing, but whoever swears by the offering on it, he is obligated.'
"You blind men, which is more important, the offering, or the altar that sanctifies the offering?
"Therefore, whoever swears by the altar, swears both by the altar and by everything on it.
"And whoever swears by the temple, swears both by the temple and by Him who dwells within it.
"And whoever swears by heaven, swears both by the throne of God and by Him who sits upon it.
"Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you tithe mint and dill and cummin, and have neglected the weightier provisions of the law: justice and mercy and faithfulness; but these are the things you should have done without neglecting the others.
"You blind guides, who strain out a gnat and swallow a camel!
"Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you clean the outside of the cup and of the dish, but inside they are full of robbery and self-indulgence.
"You blind Pharisee, first clean the inside of the cup and of the dish, so that the outside of it may become clean also.
"Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you are like whitewashed tombs which on the outside appear beautiful, but inside they are full of dead men's bones and all uncleanness.
"So you, too, outwardly appear righteous to men, but inwardly you are full of hypocrisy and lawlessness.
"Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you build the tombs of the prophets and adorn the monuments of the righteous,
and say, 'If we had been living in the days of our fathers, we would not have been partners with them in shedding the blood of the prophets.'
"So you testify against yourselves, that you are sons of those who murdered the prophets.
"Fill up, then, the measure of the guilt of your fathers.
"You serpents, you brood of vipers, how will you escape the sentence of hell?
"Therefore, behold, I am sending you prophets and wise men and scribes; some of them you will kill and crucify, and some of them you will scourge in your synagogues, and persecute from city to city,
so that upon you may fall the guilt of all the righteous blood shed on earth, from the blood of righteous Abel to the blood of Zechariah, the son of Berechiah, whom you murdered between the temple and the altar.
"Truly I say to you, all these things will come upon this generation.
"Jerusalem, Jerusalem, who kills the prophets and stones those who are sent to her! How often I wanted to gather your children together, the way a hen gathers her chicks under her wings, and you were unwilling.
"Behold, your house is being left to you desolate!
"For I say to you, from now on you will not see Me until you say, 'BLESSED IS HE WHO COMES IN THE NAME OF THE LORD!'"

items.title: Matthew 28 Audio Bible
items.description:
Now after the Sabbath, as it began to dawn toward the first day of the week, Mary Magdalene and the other Mary came to look at the grave.
And behold, a severe earthquake had occurred, for an angel of the Lord descended from heaven and came and rolled away the stone and sat upon it.
And his appearance was like lightning, and his clothing as white as snow.
The guards shook for fear of him and became like dead men.
The angel said to the women, "Do not be afraid; for I know that you are looking for Jesus who has been crucified.
"He is not here, for He has risen, just as He said. Come, see the place where He was lying.
"Go quickly and tell His disciples that He has risen from the dead; and behold, He is going ahead of you into Galilee, there you will see Him; behold, I have told you."
And they left the tomb quickly with fear and great joy and ran to report it to His disciples.
And behold, Jesus met them and greeted them. And they came up and took hold of His feet and worshiped Him.
Then Jesus said to them, "Do not be afraid; go and take word to My brethren to leave for Galilee, and there they will see Me."
Now while they were on their way, some of the guard came into the city and reported to the chief priests all that had happened.
And when they had assembled with the elders and consulted together, they gave a large sum of money to the soldiers,
and said, "You are to say, 'His disciples came by night and stole Him away while we were asleep.'
"And if this should come to the governor's ears, we will win him over and keep you out of trouble."
And they took the money and did as they had been instructed; and this story was widely spread among the Jews, and is to this day.
But the eleven disciples proceeded to Galilee, to the mountain which Jesus had designated.
When they saw Him, they worshiped Him; but some were doubtful.
And Jesus came up and spoke to them, saying, "All authority has been given to Me in heaven and on earth.
"Go therefore and make disciples of all the nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father and the Son and the Holy Spirit,
teaching them to observe all that I commanded you; and lo, I am with you always, even to the end of the age."

items.title: "Nature in our Backyard" Dallas, TX photography exhibition at Sun to Moon Gallery
items.description:
"Nature in our Backyard: The Trinity River & Great Trinity Forest"

Fine photographic prints by Dan Burkholder, Scot Miller, Jill Skupin Burkholder & R.P. Washburne

June 25 – August 22, 2015

The Trinity River and Great Trinity Forest have been receiving much attention, for a variety of reasons, but it’s no secret that the river dominated the spotlight recently. Thousands flocked to its banks to experience the sights of the flood waters. However, the reality is most people know little about the true nature of river and forest as they exist year-round. Sun to Moon Gallery and four talented photographers have worked to change that. For ten years now, the photographers have spent time on and along the river and in and around the forest, including many beautiful but lesser-known areas, creatively interpreting with their cameras. In the process, they have created an ever-expanding and changing body of work that includes engaging new photographs of the flooded Trinity by Scot Miller and R.P. Washburne.

From vivid digitally captured images, to stunning detail studies with film and a medium-format camera, to bromoil prints overlaid with color pigments, to 24k Gold Leaf Prints and more; a wide range of subject matter, artistic expression and photographic techniques form the basis of this eye-opening exhibition. Sun to Moon Gallery invites the public to come, be inspired, and see the river, forest and city in a new light!

New short films by Scot Miller –

Scot Miller, a contributor to the “Moment in Nature” videos, broadcast nationally on Emmy Award-winning CBS Sunday Morning, also spent many hours and days over the past months capturing stunning 4k video footage of the river and forest, including many time sequences. He has created several short films, including one featuring the floods, that will be screened in the gallery throughout the exhibition.

items.title: Letter To Our Subscribers Oct 2015
items.description:
It fell into my heart about two weeks ago to write you this letter. I sat down right away to do it but to me it felt superficial, and not really from my heart, so I put it on the back burner until now.

Then I was awakened from sleep and the words began to come to me concerning what I really wanted to say, so I came to jot them down.

I recently watched a video of a shepherdess caring for her sheep... she led them to good pasture where they grazed till their hearts were content. That's what canDEElicious Video Ministry is all about... preparing ground for you to graze on. Come over here the table is spread and the feast of the Lord is going on.

In the video there were also baby lambs that the shepherdess fed with a milk bottle, reminding me of Jesus' words to Peter, "Feed My Lambs."

Although the Lord did not call me to be a shepherd, He made me a hireling to feed His sheep and His  little lambs. With all my heart, I want to do my best and be a worthy vessel for His use. When you watch these videos, I want the Lord to touch your hearts and bring you a sense that He is speaking directly to you.

Heb 4:12 says the word of God is a discerner of the thoughts and intents of the heart. That's why it sounds like He is speaking directly to you.

- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -

Lately, I've been feeling like such a failure at living up to His calling and election. My attitude toward God and misunderstanding His will for my life has left me wanting.

One of the things that I never want to happen as I teach God's word to others is that I myself would not live up to it through my disobedience and obstinance.

A few years ago, I was so offended with God that I refused to pray. Prayer didn't seem practical because my expectations were not being met. So I weaned off. There were times when the Holy Spirit would unction me to pray and I would kindly decline, "No thank You." I didn't feel mad at God. Prayer just simply felt impractical so I failed to maintain a good prayer life.

But I woke up one morning the The Temptations fell in my heart and I couldn't shake it... 

I can fly like a bird in the sky
And I can buy anything money can buy
I can turn a river into a raging fire
I can live forever if I so desire
Unimportant are all the things I can do
Cause I can't get next to babe
Can't get next to you.

I felt that I had let my Lord down feeding Him from a long-handled spoon. He was knocking at the door of my heart but my pride kept me at a distance. But I thought it was so sweet that He said with all of His power to do anything He wants to do - the one thing escaping Him was getting me to open up.

Jesus said, "Behold I stand at the door and knock. If anyone hears My voice and opens the door, I will come in to him and dine with him, and he with Me."

God's love is poured out in our hearts by the Holy Spirit but we must first open our hearts to Him and invite Him in (or back in, if He's been pushed aside).

Perhaps today you have decided that you want to get closer to the Lord. Reach out to Him, let Him right the wrongs. He said His grace is sufficient... and He is strong where we are weak.

Let God arise and His enemies be scattered. Submit yourselves to God, resist the devil and he will flee from you.

Thank you, our Subscribers. We're praying for you and sincerely hoping these Bible teachings are helping you. We'll see you again soon.

May God bless and keep you and make His face shine upon you and be gracious to you. May the Lord lift up His countenance upon you and give you His peace.

items.title: WRA Architects Designed Village Tech Charter School New Campus
items.description:
Village Tech Schools, a charter school serving grades pre-K through 12, is in the design stage of their new permanent campus to be located near Belt Line Road in Cedar Hill's historic downtown. WRA Architects of Dallas is designing the school, and Northstar Builders of Coppell has been selected as the Construction Manager, or builder.
"We are thrilled to partner with WRA and the City of Cedar Hill on this exciting new project," said David Williams, Village Tech's founder and CEO. "When we're finished, the school will enclose 168,000 square feet in four separate buildings and will serve up to 1,040 students."
The four structures include a 3-story classroom building for grades 3-12, a preschool for grades PreK-2, a gymnasium and dining building, and "the Forge."
The Forge is the heart of the school and embodies Village Tech's educational philosophy. It includes maker spaces, art studios, computer labs, and presentation and demonstration space. This is where students from all grade levels will design and construct projects that relate to and illustrate their curriculum in all core subjects.
Keith Anderson, AIA, is WRA's director of design and principal-in-charge of the project. He commented, "Village Tech has a wonderfully innovative approach to education, and working with them on bringing their vision to life on a new campus has been very exciting for our design team."
The campus will be one of the first projects in the redevelopment of Cedar Hill's urban center and hopes to be a catalyst for further development of this area. The school will hold its "Home of Tomorrow" preview of the new campus on the future school site at 100 Carrell Street in Cedar Hill on Saturday, December 12, from 11 am to 2 pm.
Construction will start in mid-2016.

items.title: Earthquake is Extreme Test for Stanford-trained Nepalese EMTs
items.description:
When Stanford emergency medicine chief Paul Auerbach and the SEMPER team heard the news about a 7.8 magnitude earthquake in Nepal, they wanted to help. The team has responded to natural disasters in Haiti and the Philippines and those experiences have built a special expertise. But Nepal was a bit different: A team of Stanford emergency medicine physicians had been there to work with Nepalis to create the first Nepalese ambulance service. The recent earthquake was a proverbial trial by fire for the service, which remains the only functioning ambulance service in the country. In this video, Auerbach shares his observations—and his feelings about what he saw and the people of Nepal.

Discover more at:
www.stanfordhealthcare.org

items.title: San Francisco before and after Earthquake
items.description:
Unique historical pre-disaster and San Francisco earthquake aftermath footage.

The 1906 San Francisco earthquake struck the coast of Northern California at 5:12 a.m. on Wednesday, April 18. Devastating fires broke out in the city that lasted for several days. As a result, about 3,000 people died and over 80% of San Francisco was destroyed.

The earthquake and resulting fire are remembered as one of the worst natural disasters in the history of the United States alongside the Galveston Hurricane of 1900 and Hurricane Katrina in 2005. The death toll from the earthquake and resulting fire remains the greatest loss of life from a natural disaster in California's history. At the time, 375 deaths were reported. Partly because hundreds of fatalities in Chinatown went ignored and unrecorded, the total number of deaths is still uncertain today, and is estimated to be roughly 3,000 at minimum. Most of the deaths occurred in San Francisco itself, but 189 were reported elsewhere in the Bay Area; nearby cities, such as Santa Rosa and San Jose, also suffered severe damage. Between 227,000 and 300,000 people were left homeless out of a population of about 410,000; half of those who evacuated fled across the bay to Oakland and Berkeley. Newspapers described Golden Gate Park, the Presidio, the Panhandle and the beaches between Ingleside and North Beach as covered with makeshift tents. More than two years later, many of these refugee camps were still in operation.

SF Cable cars
Andrew Smith Hallidie tested the first cable car at 4 o'clock in the morning, August 2nd, 1873, on Clay Street, in San Francisco. His idea for a steam engine powered - cable driven - rail system was conceived in 1869, after witnessing horses being whipped while they struggled on the wet cobblestones to pull a horsecar up Jackson Street. Hallidie entered into a partnership to form the Clay Street Hill Railroad, which began construction of a cable line on Clay Street in May of 1873. The contract to operate on city streets stated the line must be operational by August 1st. They launched on the 2nd. Even though they were a day late the cable car trials received great approval. Clay Street Hill Railroad began public service on September 1st, 1873. It was a tremendous success. Clay Street Hill Railroad was the sole cable car company for 4 years. A former horsecar company, Sutter Street Railroad, developed its own version of Hallidie's patented system and began cable service in 1877, followed by California Street Cable Railroad -1878, Geary Street, Park & Ocean Railroad -1880, Presidio & Ferries Railroad -1882, Market Street Cable Railway -1883, Ferries & Cliff House Railway -1888, and Omnibus Railroad & Cable Company -1889.

All totaled San Francisco companies had lay down 53 miles of track stretching from the Ferry Building to the Presidio, to Golden Gate Park, to the Castro, to the Mission.
April 18, 1906, the Great Earthquake & Fire devastated the city.
By this time the electric streetcar, perfected in1888 by Frank Sprague, had become the vehicle of choice for city transit. It only required half the investment to build and maintain, could reach more areas and was quicker. The cable cars were still able to traverse the steep hills better, so some of the lines were rebuilt. However, as the streetcars improved, even those lines were in jeopardy.
  
Market street, before and after. Dramatic scenes. Horse driven carriages, cable tram. Ferry terminal building. Urban history. Victorian park. Powell-Hyde line turnaround. Friedel Klussmann Memorial Turnaround.

items.title: 6915A San Francisco: Scientists are worried by the threat of another earthquake
items.description:
6915/A: SAN FRANCISCO: WILL THE QUAKE COME?

San Francisco is situated on a major geological fault,
and over the past twelve months or so scientists have
become increasingly worried by the threat of another
earthquake of the same magnitude that destroyed the
city back in 1906.  One rather wild notion current in the
area at the moment is that the whole Californian
seaboard could just slide away into the Pacific.  The
scientists are a good deal less pessimistic than that,
but there does seem to be cause for concern.  We
visited San Francisco, and nearby Hollister, "earth
quake capital of the nation", and interviewed three
scientists:  Karl Steinbrugge, a world authority on
structural damage caused by earthquakes; Richard
Jahns, Dean of Stanford University School of Earth
Sciences; and Doctor Don Tocker of the Earth Movement
Laboratories in San Francisco.

items.title: Japan Tsunami 2011 - Tohoku Earthquake Shocking Video
items.description:
Japan Tsunami 2011 - Tohoku Earthquake Shocking Video

An erupting volcanic island that is expanding off Japan could trigger a tsunami if its freshly-formed lava slopes collapse into the sea, scientists say.

The small, but growing, island appeared last year and quickly engulfed the already-existing island of Nishinoshima, around 1000 kilometres south of Tokyo.

It now covers 1.26 square kilometres.

The island's craters are currently spewing out 200,000 cubic metres of lava every day - enough to fill 80 Olympic swimming pools - which is accumulating in its east, scientists said.

"If lava continues to mount on the eastern area, part of the island's slopes could collapse and cause a tsunami," warned Fukashi Maeno, assistant professor of the Earthquake Research Institute at the University of Tokyo.

He said a rockfall of 12 million cubic metres of lava would generate a one metre tsunami that could travel faster than a bullet train, hitting the island of Chichijima - 130kms away - in around 18 minutes, he said.

Chichijima, home to about 2000 people, is the largest island in the Ogasawara archipelago, a wild and remote chain that is administratively part of Tokyo.

"The ideal way to monitor and avoid a natural disaster is to set up a new tsunami and earthquake detection system near the island, but it's impossible for anyone to land on the island in the current situation," Maeno added.

An official from the Japan Meteorological Agency, which monitors earthquakes and tsunamis, said the agency is watching for any signs of anything untoward.

"We studied the simulation this morning, and we are thinking of consulting with earthquake prediction experts ... about the probability of this actually happening, and what kind of measures we would be able to take," he said.

Japan's northeast was ravaged by a huge tsunami in March 2011, when a massive undersea earthquake sent a wall of water barrelling into the northeast coast, killing more than 18,000 people and wrecking whole towns.

Link Video http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TmGm8PlHnXs

items.title: Dawn service to remember victims of 1906 earthquake
items.description:
SHOTLIST
POOL 
San Francisco - 18 April 2006
1. Wreath laying ceremony 
Library of Congress, Prelinger Archive - No re-use/re-sale without clearance
2. Black & white footage of Market Street, San Francisco prior to earthquake
POOL 
San Francisco - 18 April 2006
3.  Wreath laying ceremony at earthquake memorial
Library of Congress, Prelinger Archive  - No re-use/re-sale without clearance
4. Black & white footage of Market Street following earthquake 
5. Black & white footage of residential boarding house area after earthquake
POOL
San Francisco - 18 April 2006
6. Tolling of bells on anniversary of earthquake
7. SOUNDBITE: (English) Gavin Newson, San Francisco Mayor: 
"Do you have any early memories of the quake?"
8. SOUNDBITE: (English) Mildred Morganstein, Quake Survivor:
"No, just that it was the biggest shock and a great deal of misery going on. People moving, losing their homes, and people having to sleep in the park and away things. Not being able to get back in their homes where they could cook and sleep and things like that."
Library of Congress - Prelinger Archive - No re-use/re-sale without clearance
9. Black & white footage of armed guard standing at intersection in San Francisco after quake
POOL
San Francisco - 18 April 2006
10. Wailing of sirens at earthquake memorial
11. SOUNDBITE: (English) Joanne Hayes White, San Francisco Fire Chief:
"And really, what today is about, as we commemorate and celebrate and look to our future, we look to a bright future, we want to make sure we''re the most prepared city that we can be. And we need all of you in our community to take that responsibility to become personally prepared, personally prepared in your homes, with your families and pets as well as in your workplaces. We want to do all we can, and, as a city collectively, we can be very prepared."
Library of Congress - Prelinger Archive - No re-use/re-sale without clearance
12. Black & white footage of makeshift housing following earthquake
POOL
San Francisco - 18 April 2006
13. UPSOUND (English) Gavin Newson, San Francisco Mayor, interviewing quake survivor Norma Norwood: 
Newson: "Well, how old are you now?"
Norwood: "I''m 99. I''m a result of the earthquake."
Newson: "Now you''re talking. I don''t want to pry into anyone''s personal life, but, what do you mean about being a result of the earthquake?"
Norwood: "I was born, I was conceived and born in a tent in Golden Gate Park."
Library of Congress - Prelinger Archive - No re-use/re-sale without clearance
17. Black & white footage of ruins of San Francisco following earthquake
STORYLINE
Sirens wailed through the city before dawn in San Francisco on Tuesday marking the moment 100 years earlier when the Great Quake shattered the city, killing thousands as it levelled buildings and touched off fires that burned for days.
A handful of centenarians who survived that devastation joined hundreds of residents for a moment of silence and a memorial ceremony to remember one of the worst natural disasters in U.S. history.
Most of the city''s 400,000 residents were still in bed when the magnitude-7.8 earthquake struck at 5:12 a.m. on April 18, 1906.
The epicentre was a few miles (kilometres) offshore of the city, but it was felt as far away as Oregon and Nevada. 
From cracked chimneys, broken gas lines and toppled chemical tanks, fires broke out and swept across the city, burning for days. 
Ruptured water pipes left firefighters helpless, while families carrying what they could fled to parks that had become makeshift morgues.
One hundred eleven year old Mildred Morganstein remembers the hardships that befell her family and neighbours immediately following the quake.
But they disagree over whether people should love the city or leave it.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/f80574dcaa53f2994473516cd8dac056 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Driver crashes into two homes, leaving car suspended in air
items.description:
1. Car wedged between two houses
2. Close shot, car stuck in wall
3. Zoom into damaged car 
4. SOUNDBITE: (English) Kim Macedo, resident of house hit by car:
"I thought it was an earthquake and I kind of was in my bed bracing for an aftershock or something, and then I heard my mom yelling there was someone in the yard, and she told me to call 911. So I did and I went downstairs to see what was going on and I saw that." 
5. Pull out of damage to house
6. Zoom into car 
7. Back view of car between houses
8. SOUNDBITE: (English) Officer M. Koons, Los Angeles Police Department:
"We responded to a call of a car stuck between two houses as we got here we were told that there was a DUI (driving under the influence) in custody by other officers and he is at the station now.  We do not know anything further."
(Q: "Anybody hurt?") 
"No."
9. Police looking at car
10. Pull out from driver of crashed car in back of police car
11. Zoom into car stuck between houses 
STORYLINE:
California police say one man is under arrest and another is being sought after an alleged drunk driver crashed into two homes, leaving his car suspended five feet (1.5 metres) above the ground in San Pedro early on Sunday morning. 
The car crashed into two houses at 1:30 am local time (0930 GMT). 
Police at the scene said the alleged drunk driver drove his car over a kerb and it then crashed sideways, ending up wedged between the walls of two houses.
One of the houses suffered a severed gas line.
A resident of one of the houses said he thought he was experiencing an earthquake and waited for an aftershock before realising the shaking was the result of the car crashing into their house.
Police arrested the driver at the scene for suspicion of driving under the influence. 
A crane was called to the scene to lift the car out of the houses.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/f1c944744832b45e05cec231e503f2a6

items.title: A look at how the earthquake has damaged the Napa Valley wine industry
items.description:
Businesses in California's wine capital mopped up thousands of dollars in high-end vintages on Monday, after an earthquake caused 1 billion US dollars in damage, according to official estimates.
In Napa Valley, two hotels and 12 wineries were still closed on Monday, as well as many of the businesses downtown, local officials said, amid a rush to get the tourist hotspot back in shape for the summer's final holiday weekend.
With the dust still settling from Sunday's magnitude-6.0 quake, centered near the city of Napa, government and tourism officials encouraged visitors to keep flocking to the charming towns, tasting rooms, restaurants and spas that drive the Napa Valley economy.
While cleanup will take time and broken water mains remained a problem, they said, the worst damage and disruption was confined to the city's downtown, where a post office, library and a 141-room hotel were among 150 homes and buildings deemed unsafe to occupy.
The strongest earthquake to hit the San Francisco Bay Area in a quarter of a century also caused several injuries, triggered fires that destroyed or damaged six mobile homes, and ruptured gas lines.



You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/a8b54d8ea576ce2eb5864535b135d42f 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Largest earthquake in 25 years hits the San Francisco Bay Area
items.description:
A large earthquake rolled through California's northern Bay Area early on Sunday, damaging some buildings, igniting fires, knocking out power to tens of thousands and sending residents running out of their homes in the darkness.
The 6.0-magnitude quake caused six significant fires, including at four mobile homes, according to a Napa Division Fire official.
The epicentre of the earthquake that struck Northern California, the strongest in the area in 25 years, was just six miles southwest of Napa, California, the centre of California's winemaking region.
The US Geological Survey (USGS) described the tremor as the largest earthquake to shake the Bay Area since the 6.9-magnitude Loma Prieta quake in 1989.
Several other smaller fires were reported and firefighting efforts were complicated by broken water mains.
Local residents counted the cost of the damage on Sunday.
"All my valuable stuff is in the bedroom so most of everything is gone," said 83-year-old Nola Rawlins whose mobile home was destroyed by fire.
Winemakers in California's storied Napa Valley woke up to thousands of broken bottles and barrels as a result of Sunday's earthquake.
The earthquake couldn't have come at a worse time for the region, which has just started harvesting the 2014 crop.

items.title: SJ Quakes Pres Dave Kaval Academy Conversation
items.description:
San Jose Earthquakes Club President Dave Kaval took some time out of his busy schedule to sit down with the guys from The Original Winger and have an in-depth conversation about the newest soccer specific stadium to come to Major League Soccer, the San Jose Earthquakes and their Academy system as well as the future of American Soccer.

Dave Kaval, a native of Cleveland, Ohio, who earned a Bachelor’s degree and an M.B.A. from Stanford University, was hired as the President of the San Jose Earthquakes in October of 2010. He oversees the business and technical sides of the franchise.

Kaval led the Quakes efforts to design, develop, and privately finance the new 18,000 seat, $100m soccer specific stadium that opened for the 2015 MLS season.

items.title: San Francisco earthquake Oakland  live report
items.description:
OAKLAND -- A magnitude-4.0 temblor that rattled nerves in the East Bay on Monday morning was a very shallow but routine geologic shrug in an area notorious for seismic risk -- and yet another reminder of the threat lurking from a fault that's the Bay Area's most overdue for a major quake.

A locked-up patch of rocks a mere 3 miles under Piedmont suddenly broke loose along the Hayward Fault, triggering a wake-up call felt from Santa Rosa to Santa Cruz.

"Because it was shallower than normal, people in the vicinity felt more intensified shaking than usual for an earthquake of this magnitude," said Keith Knudsen, deputy director of the Earthquake Science Center at the U.S. Geological Survey in Menlo Park.

 USGS Map
USGS Map
Monday's quake was the second magnitude-4.0 quake on the Hayward Fault in less than a month -- and comes almost a year after the magnitude-6.0 Napa temblor that was the region's biggest in 25 years -- but there is no indication it is a precursor of the Big One. While there was a flurry of aftershocks following Monday's 6:49 a.m. earthquake, there is only a 10 percent chance that it will be followed by a larger earthquake in the next week, Knudsen said.

items.title: San Francisco De Young Museum New Building 10th Anniversary
items.description: The de Young museum opened initially at the California Midwinter International Exposition of 1894. That building was damaged in the 1906 earthquake. It was housed in a new building in Golden Gate Park in 1919. This building was severely damaged by the Loma Prieta earthquake of 1989. This video is of the 10th anniversary party of the new building that replaced the old de Young. It was a free event on Saturday 10/18 that went until 10pm. Milton and I went after Milton got off work. We arrived around 8:30 pm and enjoyed wandering freely through the museum.

items.title: OJ Simpson in court in preliminary hearing regarding evidence
items.description:
1. OJ Simpson arriving at the court house with his legal team
2. Interior of court room with Walter Alexander, former co-defendant on the witness stand
3. SOUNDBITE: (English) Walter Alexander, former co-defendant: (++partially overlaid with close shot of Simpson++) 
UPSOUND (English): David Roger, District Attorney, Clark County:  
"What did he (OJ Simpson) tell you he needed you to do?"
A: "Once he, after he had asked me if we could watch his back, he kinda leaned forward and it was like, 'hey, do you think you can get some heat? Do you think you can get some heat, you know, just in case things go wrong. Just in case, you know, they may have heat, you know, can you bring some heat?'
Q:  What did that mean to you? 
A:"That meant that he wanted me to help him acquire some guns."
4. Mid of Simpson and attorney
5. SOUNDBITE: (English) Walter Alexander, former co-defendant:
"Mr. Simpson asked Spencer (Michael"Spencer" McClinton) to put the gun in his hand. He said, 'put the gun in your hand.' It changed the whole plan, cause at first the plan was that we were supposed to just show the guns, but right before we went in the room, he did tell Spencer to put his gun in his hand."
Q: "And Spencer did that?"  
A: "Yes, he did. So when he walked in that's why he already had it out and he was, you know, making commands." 
6. Mid of Simpson
7. Mid of David Roger, District Attorney 
8. Mid of Simpson
9.  Mid of Alexander UPSOUND: (English) Yale Galanter, OJ Simpson's attorney: (off camera)
"Certainly, Tom Scotto (Simpson's friend) didn't need your help, right?"
SOUNDBITE: (English) Walter Alexander, former co-defendant:
A:"That's true."  
Q: "What you're implying in this message is that you would give favourable testimony to Mr. Simpson if Mr. Scotto wrote you a check, or helped you out with bail, and lawyers, so on and so forth? Isn't that correct, sir?"
SOUNDBITE: (English)  Walter Alexander, former co-defendant:
A: "Not true."
Q: "Not true?  Would you like to hear it again?"
SOUNDBITE: (English) Walter Alexander, former co-defendant:
"No. I can tell you what I was saying. That's not what it says on there. What I was saying is that what I would say in court could definitely, you know, I really felt that he was set up. So, I felt like I could lean toward that angle rather than telling the exact truth."
10. Cutaway of Simpson smiling
11. Mid of Alexander on the stand 
12. Lawyer checking notes
STORYLINE:
O.J. Simpson's one-time golfing friend glared at him across a courtroom on Tuesday and said the former football star wanted him to bring "heat", a gun, to a confrontation with two sports memorabilia dealers in a Las Vegas hotel room.
Minutes later, Simpson's lawyer accused the friend, Walter Alexander, of being a liar, and the two wound up in a shouting match in the third day of a preliminary hearing in the armed robbery case.
A justice of the peace will decide after the hearing whether there is enough evidence for Simpson and two other men to stand trial.
Alexander's testimony was the strongest for prosecutors so far. He and Michael McClinton, who also testified against Simpson on Tuesday, struck deals with prosecutors and pleaded guilty to lesser charges, as did Charles Cashmore, who testified last week.
"After he asked me if I could watch his back, he leaned forward and it was kind of like, 'Hey, do you think you can get some heat?"' Alexander said. "'Just in case things go wrong, can you bring some heat?"'
Simpson, 60, has maintained in interviews and through his lawyers that he never saw any guns or asked anyone to bring them to the hotel room. 
He sometimes smiled but frequently shook his head as Alexander testified.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/c48385adcb1f15fb10325bc93671a292 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

British Airways flight catches fire at Las Vegas' McCarran International Airport

There was panic on a British Airways flight packed with passengers when a suspected engine fire engulfed the aircraft, just moments before it was due to take off. 

Around 159 passengers and 13 crew were evacuated from the Boeing-777 which caught fire on the tarmac at Las Vegas' McCarran International Airport.

The 275-seat aircraft, British Airways flight number 2276, was bound for London's Gatwick Airport.

items.title: Raw Video | British Airways plane catches fire at Las Vegas airport
items.description:
A British Airways jet has caught fire at Las Vegas airport, sending smoke billowing into the air, after suffering what the pilot described as a “catastrophic failure” of the left engine.



The plane – a Boeing 777 heading from the US city’s McCarran airport to London Gatwick – could be seen with flames around its fuselage.

There were 159 passengers and 13 crew on board. Seven people were treated for minor injuries as a result of the fire, which was swiftly put out by around 50 firefighters.

items.title: Very Successful Night Of UFO Hunting
items.description:
This video was captured in the northern mountains of the Las Vegas Valley on the night of September 15, 2015.

I am an average guy and no different than your next door neighbor, your brother, dad or uncle, but I have come to a point where I have to ask the question. Why me? Why is this happening? I don't know of anyone anywhere that has compiled even a fraction of what I am compiling on video and even in some photos. Sometimes I am just taking photos and they are there. UFOs showing up when I go places. What does this all mean and how could it even be possible? I think I have a pretty pure heart, but there's nothing special about me. I love all the good people of the world no matter what their race or social standing is but I am not even remotely religious and I don't believe in spirits and spooks. I detest and kind of violence and partisan politics. I respect everybody I meet until they prove they aren't worth of my respect. It's all about the children of the world and fairness. Nobody pounded anything into my head while I was growing up and I made my own rules and choices. The rules were simple and basically came down to what's right and what's wrong and how I should treat others. I am not dumb, but I am no genius either. I just don't get it. How could it be that I may end up having the distinction of being the most prolific UFO hunter in the world? I do have to ask this question! This particular video just blows me away just like many others I have and yet I am shunned and ignored by all the so called experts who could help. What are they afraid of? Why won't they even speak to me or take the time to investigate my videos? It doesn't make any sense.

items.title: Let The Camera Just Run And See What Happens
items.description:
Video shot on a quiet night in Las Vegas, Nevada on Monday, March 16, 2015. 

It was pretty quiet last night so I decided to turn the camera on and just let it run while I went indoors and ate some dinner. I aimed it at the area where these strange things always show up hoping to catch something unusual. Not a lot of activity but there were some unusual things about it. When objects showed up they usually arrived in the same spot they always do but some objects came over there from the right-hand side of the screen. They seemed to edge forward, then back and then forward again, There was also another bright object that shows up on the right and releases five of six smaller objects who proceed to turn around and go back to the right. Not the most exciting video in the world but cool enough.

items.title: #5a NICA Utah State Championships 2015 - Saint George, Utah 10:32 am
items.description:
PLEASE READ THE ENTIRE REMARKS SECTION FOR HOW TO BEST WATCH THE VIDEOS AND FOR THE BEST WAY TO FIND YOUR RIDER!

The best way to figure out if you are on the course is to look at the time the video was shot. With several different groups on the course at the same time sometimes I will not have any idea if I am filming JV or Varsity.  I shot 130 GB of drone video on race day... Uploading takes a while.

"Experience the fun and thrill of sweet desert riding. The course starts on a dirt road, providing racers ¾ mile to spread the field before turning into a small wash section. Followed by a dirt road connecting into to Rampage Wash, where the real fun happens with slick rock technical sections. Rampage does offer places to “go around” several technical sections for beginners. The climb then continues up a road, providing more  passing opportunities. The downhill single track offers a perfect combination of speed sections with technical sections. While we start on the classic I-cup race descent, we do not follow it the whole way down. Instead, we cross the road about halfway down and follow a more gradually descending single track to the left. The course heads back toward the finish area on single track."

I have about $10K worth of gear involved with doing this (more with the massive storage drives *60TB* and computers) and my son is on the PG team... I know how fun it is as a parent to see the actual course and race.  From the pit zone or the starting line you are so limited as to what you can see so... I have been trying to fly as much of the races as I can... I love doing it so... there is that but it does take time and there is some real expense involved.  

My real job where I earn my living (and the reason I can justify the equipment) is selling Real Estate in Utah County and the south end of the Salt Lake Valley. I have been doing this for 21 years and have been a broker since 1997. I am also the chair of the Pleasant Grove Planning Commission (and I am very excited about getting a new trail.)  My partner and I have sold over 2000 properties in our careers. We are very experienced. Help us out... If you or someone you know could use some help with Real Estate help us out and give us a quick call. 801-636-3739. 

The drone cuts video into 4.2 gig max size chunks so while the drone can film for about 15 minutes it cuts the video taken during one flight into smaller pieces. I'll indicate that a video is the second part of a particular flight by labeling the upload with the "a".  So... for example the first part of the first video is 1 and the second part of the same flight would be 1a. 

Also, these videos are 4K. The default for your computer is often set to show video from YouTube at 720p or less. If you look down in the corner of the video you can click on the gear symbol and crank the resolution way way up to 4k where you can actually see some amazing detail. 

Coaches, let me know if there is a clip you would like sent to you for a promotional video. We can figure that out...

Drone's are a blast to fly and use... but here is the deal. The more people who have them and want to use them the more risk there is of an accident occurring.  At the championship I only flew my Inspire1. The white drone with the black arms. 

I have a Phantom 3 Professional as well as my back up. Someone else had a phantom there as well. It was zipping back and forth over the start and finish line. I hope you notice that I do NOT fly the drone over the heads of spectators and or riders (if I can help it with the riders, sometimes I may inadvertently cross a path.) I enter and exit the pit zone over areas where there are NOT crowds. And I have a marked Landing Zone set up on the edge of the pit zones for safety. I also have about 500 flights under my belt at this point. 

I am very very pro-drone but these must be used responsibly if we are going to be able to continue to get this type of footage. I am going to see what I can do with NICA about creating a set of NICA rules or guidelines for drone use at these races (aside from the FAA rules) that will focus on safety while giving us an opportunity to get these great shots. If you are interested in giving me some input as to what you may be concerned about please email me at Drew@utahrealestate.net. 

There has to be a balance. Next year prior to flying I would hope that each of us who are interested in using our drone's at NICA events contact NICA to check to see if there are new set safety standards or rules before we fly. - Thanks... -Drew Armstrong 801-636-3739

items.description:
Raw Footage Malaysia Earthquake | Strong 6.0-Magnitude Quake Strikes Mount Kinabalu
Raw Footage Malaysia Earthquake | Strong 6.0-Magnitude Quake Strikes Mount Kinabalu
Raw Footage Malaysia Earthquake | Strong 6.0-Magnitude Quake Strikes Mount Kinabalu


A strong 6.0-magnitude earthquake rocked the state of Sabah on Malaysia's Borneo island early Friday, US geologists said, but there was no tsunami warning issued.

The US Geological Survey said the quake struck at a depth of 10 kilometres, with its epicentre located 19 kilometres from the town of Ranau and 54 kilometres from Kota Kinabalu in the district of Sabah.

The tremor, which lasted for about 30 seconds, caused minimal damage to buildings.

According to the Ranau police, several business premises in Ranau town reported shattered windows in the buildings.
https://youtu.be/Q68TkIYH5OU

Malaysian social media users uploaded photos showing damaged roads, shattered storefront windows and cracked walls and floors in Sabah.

But there were no initial reports of major damage.

Major earthquakes are rare in Malaysia, which lies just outside the Ring of Fire, the belt of seismic activity running around the Pacific basin

items.title: Body of British girl who died on Mt Kinabalu recovered.
items.description:
1. Ambulance arriving at hospital  
2. Wide shot of body inside ambulance - secured in stretcher 
3. Mid shot of body seen through rear window 
4. Close up of ambulance equipment attached to body
5. Hospital official in the ambulance checking on the body
6. Cutaway of journalists
7. Close-up of body - covered up - being wheeled into hospital past media crowd - close-up of body on stretcher 
8. Cutaway of journalists
9. Hospital staff moving body onto hospital stretcher
10. Close up of body's head, covered up but with blond hair visible
11. Body being wheeled away from camara and media and into morgue room  
12. SOUNDBITE (English) Datuk Lamri Ali, Director of Sabah Park: 
"Because we cannot pinpoint, I leave it to the medical examiner for the post mortem. They will know, maybe they can decide or maybe they will have a clue when this victim died - how many days before, and how."
13. Wide shot of Datuk Lamri Ali speaking to media 
14. SOUNDBITE (English) Datuk Lamri Ali, Director of Sabah Park: 
"Every time it happens like this, we have to conduct a post mortem, and then see what is the possible cause. And then maybe if it is human error or whatever then we have to look into it."
15. Various of ambulance parked in front of hospital

STORYLINE: 

Search teams in Borneo have found the body of the British teenage girl, Ellie James, who went missing on Southeast Asia's tallest mountain.

The girl's body was found on Wednesday on Mount Kinabalu, barely five hundred metres (yards) from where her brother was rescued a week before.  

But bad weather, with winds gusting up to a hundred kilometres (62 miles) per hour, hindered search parties. 

The weather also meant rescuers had to take several hours on Wednesday getting the body off the four thousand-one hundred and one metre (13,455-foot) mountain. 

Conditions were too poor for helicopters to be used. 

Ellie James was 17 and from Cornwall in the U.K. 

Her body was taken to a hospital in Kota Kinabalu city, about three hours drive from the mountain, where James' parents and two brothers were waiting. 

James and her brother, Henry, who is 15, went missing on August 16 in bad weather as they descended with their parents and other British trekkers. 

The boy was discovered six hours later at a spot where his sister had told him to wait while she went for help. 

Despite a search operation that totaled 70 people by Tuesday, she was not seen until rangers spotted her body, still clad in her pink jacket, during a brief spell of clear skies on Wednesday morning. 

She lay 500 meters (yards) from the spot where her brother was found, said Police Chief Zul Bahrain Ismail. Rescuers had searched the area previously, but seen nothing in the persistent thick mists.

A local mountain guide involved in the search told the national news agency, Bernama, that he had heard cries for help the day James was lost.

"We heard, `Help me ...help me...' and ran back and forth to try to locate the area from where the cries were coming, but our efforts were in vain because of the strong winds, the mountain echo and low visibility," Richard Adi was quoted as saying.

Zul dismissed suggestions that authorities had been slow in mounting a full-scale operation: "We were racing against time and were badly hampered by bad weather."

The body was discovered face down and without visible injuries on a steep, 65-degree slope near the summit, much higher up than searchers had expected after finding footprints and other clues at a lower altitude.


Chong Kah Kiat, chief minister of Sabah state, where the mountain is located, expressed condolences to the parents and said they understood the difficulties of the search, The Star newspaper's online site reported.






You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/bc040d6f017e7ce73e85bf6e32d2802e 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Mt Kinabalu Sabah
items.description:
Mount Kinabalu (Malay: Gunung Kinabalu) is a prominent mountain on the island of Borneo in Southeast Asia. It is located in the East Malaysian state of Sabah and is protected as Kinabalu Park, a World Heritage Site. Kinabalu is the highest peak in Borneo's Crocker Range and is the highest mountain in the Malay Archipelago as well as the highest mountain in Malaysia. Mount Kinabalu is also the 20th most prominent mountain in the world by topographic prominence.

In 1997, a re-survey using satellite technology established its summit (known as Low's Peak) height at 4,096 metres (13,438 ft) above sea level, which is some 6 metres (20 ft) less than the previously thought and hitherto published figure of 4,101 metres (13,455 ft).

Mount Kinabalu includes the Kinabalu montane alpine meadows ecoregion in the montane grasslands and shrublands biome. The mountain and its surroundings are among the most important biological sites in the world, with between 5,000 and 6,000 species of plants, 326 species of birds, and more than 100 mammalian species identified. Among this rich collection of wildlife are famous species such as the gigantic Rafflesia plants and the orangutan. Mount Kinabalu has been accorded UNESCO World Heritage status.

Low's Peak can be climbed quite easily by a person in good physical condition and there is no need for mountaineering equipment at any point on the main route. Other peaks along the massif, however, require rock climbing skills.

Info extract from Wikipedia : https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Kinabalu

items.title: Kota Kinabalu, Malaysia - Legend of the Seas Arrives in Kota Kinabalu HD (2015)
items.description:
Kota Kinabalu (Malaysian pronunciation: [ˈkota kinaˈbalu], Jawi: کوتا کينا بالو‎, Chinese: 亚庇; pinyin: Yàbì), formerly known as Jesselton, is the capital of the state of Sabah, Malaysia. It is also the capital of the West Coast Division of Sabah. The city is located on the northwest coast of Borneo facing the South China Sea. The Tunku Abdul Rahman National Park lies to its west and Mount Kinabalu, which gave the city its name, is located to its east. Kota Kinabalu has a population of 452,058 and, including the adjacent Penampang and Putatan districts, the metro area has an estimated population of 628,725.

Kota Kinabalu is often known as KK both in Malaysia and internationally. It is a major fishing destination and a popular gateway for travellers visiting Sabah and Borneo. Kinabalu Park is located about 90 kilometres from the city and there are many other tourist attractions in and around the city. Kota Kinabalu is also one of the major industrial and commercial centres of East Malaysia. These two factors combine to make Kota Kinabalu one of the fastest growing cities in Malaysia.
