items.title: BREAKING NEWS: EARTHQUAKE HITS NEPAL- Shocking Footage & Aftermath (April 2015)
items.description:
Ormer Nepalese Prime Minister Dr Baburam Bhattarai shared images on Facebook of homes in the Gorkha region demolished after Saturday’s 7.8-magnitude earthquake.
Officials said more than 2500 people have died, possibly including one Australian, and more than 6200 were injured after the quake tore through large parts of Nepal, levelling homes, toppling office blocks and triggering deadly avalanches at Everest base camp.
The death toll in India stands at 67, while Chinese officials say 18 people had been killed in the Tibet region.
As rescuers sift through the rubble searching for survivors, grief-stricken Nepalese are holding mass cremations in the devastated capital.
The horrific quake, the Himalayan nation’s worst disaster in more than 80 years, was followed by powerful aftershocks, including a including a 6.7 magnitude monster on Sunday.
The US Geological Survey reports the shock, which occurred in the Kathmandu region, registered at a shallow depth of 10 kilometres.
There are still grave fears for the safety of dozens of Australians travelling in Nepal.
Foreign Minister Julie Bishop said there were more than 500 Australians registered as travelling in Nepal, with the safety of 200 confirmed.
AFP correspondents in Kathmandu reported that tremors were felt throughout the night, including one strong aftershock at dawn.
AFP’s Nepal bureau chief Ammu Kannampilly, on an assignment at base camp, reported that six helicopters had managed to reach the mountain on Sunday morning after the weather had improved overnight.
Hospitals were so stretched on Sunday that medics had set up tents outside the buildings to treat patients.
Snowfalls on Saturday had thwarted efforts to airlift survivors from Everest base camp, where hundreds of mountaineers were gathered at the start of the annual climbing season, cancelled last year after the deaths of the 16 sherpa guides.
Offers of help have poured in from governments around the world, with the US and European Union announcing they were sending in disaster response teams. India flew out its stranded citizens in military planes.
“We have deployed all our resources for search and rescues,” Singh Bam said.
“Helicopters have been sent to remote areas. We are sifting through the rubble where buildings have collapsed to see if we can find anyone.”
The European Commission has released three million euros ($4.2 million) in emergency aid for Nepal, is in addition to assistance offered by individual EU nations and the deployment of European Commission humanitarian aid and civil protection experts to the crisis area.

items.title: SHOCKING FOOTAGE: EARTHQUAKE DEVASTATES NEPAL (April 26, 2015) Kathmandu Destruction
items.description:
ormer Nepalese Prime Minister Dr Baburam Bhattarai shared images on Facebook of homes in the Gorkha region demolished after Saturday’s 7.8-magnitude earthquake.
Officials said more than 2500 people have died, possibly including one Australian, and more than 6200 were injured after the quake tore through large parts of Nepal, levelling homes, toppling office blocks and triggering deadly avalanches at Everest base camp.
The death toll in India stands at 67, while Chinese officials say 18 people had been killed in the Tibet region.
As rescuers sift through the rubble searching for survivors, grief-stricken Nepalese are holding mass cremations in the devastated capital.
The horrific quake, the Himalayan nation’s worst disaster in more than 80 years, was followed by powerful aftershocks, including a including a 6.7 magnitude monster on Sunday.
The US Geological Survey reports the shock, which occurred in the Kathmandu region, registered at a shallow depth of 10 kilometres.
There are still grave fears for the safety of dozens of Australians travelling in Nepal.
Foreign Minister Julie Bishop said there were more than 500 Australians registered as travelling in Nepal, with the safety of 200 confirmed.
AFP correspondents in Kathmandu reported that tremors were felt throughout the night, including one strong aftershock at dawn.
AFP’s Nepal bureau chief Ammu Kannampilly, on an assignment at base camp, reported that six helicopters had managed to reach the mountain on Sunday morning after the weather had improved overnight.
Hospitals were so stretched on Sunday that medics had set up tents outside the buildings to treat patients.
Snowfalls on Saturday had thwarted efforts to airlift survivors from Everest base camp, where hundreds of mountaineers were gathered at the start of the annual climbing season, cancelled last year after the deaths of the 16 sherpa guides.
Offers of help have poured in from governments around the world, with the US and European Union announcing they were sending in disaster response teams. India flew out its stranded citizens in military planes.
“We have deployed all our resources for search and rescues,” Singh Bam said.
“Helicopters have been sent to remote areas. We are sifting through the rubble where buildings have collapsed to see if we can find anyone.”
The European Commission has released three million euros ($4.2 million) in emergency aid for Nepal, is in addition to assistance offered by individual EU nations and the deployment of European Commission humanitarian aid and civil protection experts to the crisis area.

items.description:
Fukushima 9.0 for Trumpet and Laptop
David Aguila

Annie Lemieux, Trumpet
David Aguila, Laptop
Blaine Nelson, Projections

Dramatizations of disasters can desensitize us to the catastrophes which occur on our planet. The events leading up to the meltdown of Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant; 9.0 Earthquake and Tsunami, devastated the country. This piece is in remembrance of those lives lost on March 11th 2011.

Performed at California Institute of the Arts Tuesday April 7th 2015

items.title: CHILE EARTHQUAKE : Earthquake 8.3 in Chile Rock Capital Santiago ~ Tsunami Warning Issued
items.description:
CHILE EARTHQUAKE : Earthquake 8.3 in Chile Rock Capital Santiago ~ Tsunami Warning Issued

https://youtu.be/tVdhznI8L0g

Earthquake in Chile rocks capital Santiago, Pacific tsunami warning issued

Reports of buildings swaying and people running into the street after quake which US Geological Survey measured at 8.3 magnitude
A powerful earthquake has shaken Chile’s capital, causing buildings to sway, thousands to take refuge in the streets and sparking a tsunami alert across the Pacific ocean.

The US Geological Survey initially reported the quake at a preliminary magnitude of 7.9 but quickly revised the reading to 8.3.

US officials said the quake struck just offshore in the Pacific at 7:54 pm (6:54 pm EDT, 1154 GMT) and was centered about 141 miles (227km) north-west of Santiago.
It said the quake was 4.8 miles (7.7km) below the surface.
Chile’s emergency office warned that big waves caused by the quake could hit the coast by 11pm.

The government has urged residents to evacuate the coastline although there were no immediate reports of injuries or damage.

Chile’s state copper miner Codelco said it was evacuating its workers at its Ventanas division asa precaution after the quake.

Meanwhile Reuters witnesses said the quake could be felt as far away as the Argentine capital, Buenos Aires, on the eastern seaboard of South America.

Hazardous tsunami waves from the quake were possible along the coasts of Chile and Peru within the next several hours, the Pacific Tsunami Warning Centre said.

A tsunami watch was issued for Hawaii.

The cenre said if tsunami waves impact Hawaii, the estimated earliest arrival time would be 2:28 am. Hawaii Standard Time (1228 GMT) on Thursday.

A magnitude-8.8 quake and ensuing tsunami in central Chile in 2010 killed more than 500 people, destroyed 220,000 homes, and washed away docks, riverfronts and seaside resorts.

That quake released so much energy, it shortened the Earth’s day by a fraction of a second by changing the planet’s rotation.

Chile is one of the world’s most earthquake-prone countries because just off the coast, the Nazca tectonic plate plunges beneath the South American plate, pushing the towering Andes cordillera to ever-higher altitudes.

The strongest earthquake ever recorded on Earth happened in Chile a magnitude-9.5 tremor in 1960 that killed more than 5,000 people.

items.title: Tsunami warning as Powerful 8.3-magnitude quake shakes Chile capital | Wednesday , Sep 16
items.description:
A powerful magnitude-8.3 earthquake hit off Chile's northern coast Wednesday night, causing buildings to sway in Santiago and other cities and sending people running into the streets. (Sept. 16)

A powerful 8.3-magnitude earthquake struck Chile Wednesday night in the community of Illapel, 142 miles north of Santiago, leaving at least three people dead.

The temblor caused buildings to sway in Santiago and sent people looking for refuge in the streets. A tsunami of at least 13-feet high hit Chile's central coast in the hours following the quake, The Weather Channel reported. Several aftershocks hit within minutes as tsunami alarms rang in the port community of Valparaiso and authorities issued a tsunami alert for the country's coast. There were no reports of damage.

The U.S. Geological Survey reported the quake had a magnitude of 8.3. The agency also reported at least two large aftershocks with magnitudes of 6.3 and 6.4.

The quake prompted the National Weather Service to issue a tsunami watch for Hawaii.

It was so strong that it was felt in Buenos Aires and other parts of Argentina, the Buenos Aires Herald was reporting.
"Based on all available data a tsunami may have been generated by this earthquake that could be destructive on coastal areas even far from the epicenter," the warning read. "An investigation is underway to determine if there is a tsunami threat to Hawaii."

U.S. officials said the quake struck just offshore in the Pacific at 7:54 p.m. and was centered about 141 miles (228 kilometers) north-northwest of Santiago. It said the quake was 4.8 miles (5 kilometers) below the surface.

Chile's emergency office warned that big waves caused by the quake could hit the coast by 11 p.m.

items.title: Opening of IWC meeting, Aus, NZ, Japanese comment
items.description:
1. Various of meeting
2. Close up of sign reading 59th Annual Meeting of the International Whaling Commission, Anchorage Alaska 2007"
3. SOUNDBITE: (English) Malcolm Turnbull, Australian Minister for Environment and Water Resources:
"I'm going to just say a few words about Japan's so called scientific whaling programme which we believe it is quite clear, that around the world this scientific whaling, so called, not only demeans science because it is scientific in name only, it demeans the IWC and i'm afraid to say it does undermine the standing and reputation of Japan around the world. There are no winners from this scientific whaling programme and we are as Australia together with other like minded nations, strongly opposed to this ongoing lethal research on whales under special permit."
4. Wide of meeting
5. Cameraman
6. SOUNDBITE: (English) Chris Carter, New Zealand Minister of Conservation:
"Well i'm saying to Japan on behalf of the people of New Zealand: Give up the proposal to kill 50 humpbacks. If you do that, we will regard that as a gesture of good will. We are asking you to do that to show that you are interested in dialogue, that you are interested in moving forward. For five years i've come to the IWC and i've seen very little dialogue between the conservation bloc and the small bloc of countries that continue to whale. This is a chance for Japan to show good will."
7. Wide shot of press conference
8. SOUNDBITE: (English) Joji Morishita, Director of International Negotiations, Fisheries Agency, Government of Japan:
"Our proposal this time is substantially different from previous proposals in many senses. For example we are saying that we are prepared to negotiate the number of minke whales to be allocated to our coastal communities."
9. Cutaway of reporters
10. SOUNDBITE: (English) Joji Morishita, Director of International Negotiations, Fisheries Agency, Government of Japan:
"We are prepared to establish a committee which will invite all other IWC members to actually observe the Japanese coastal whaling, so that there will be 100 percent transparency, and if something wrong happens this committee can make recommendations for change. 
15. Cutaway of press conference
STORYLINE:
A meeting of the International Whaling Commission in Anchorage, Alaska has brought out renewed calls for more protection for the marine mammals.  
The meeting convened amid heightened security for the first annual gathering held in the United States in almost two decades.
Scores of anti-whaling activists were in Anchorage to monitor the four-day proceedings and lobby for increased protection for the
marine mammals. 
They are keeping a close watch of important issues to be addressed, including the proposed renewal of bowhead whale quota for indigenous hunters, such as Alaska natives in 10 coastal villages.
The meeting is expected to end with a 21-year moratorium on commercial whaling formally still in place despite a symbolic
resolution to overturn the ban that was passed at last year's meeting. 
A 75 percent majority would be necessary to end the moratorium, but the vote fell short of that mark.
Several anti-whaling members have since been added to the commission.
The moratorium was enacted in 1986 to protect several vulnerable species. 
Pro-whaling nations, including Japan, Norway and Iceland, argue that it is no longer needed because whale populations have rebounded. 
Norway and Iceland do not recognise the ban and conduct commercial whaling, and Japan hunts whales under a research provision allowed by the IWC.
Activists oppose a program in which Japan kills about 1,000 whales each year for scientific research and then sells the meat.
The meeting continues through Thursday.

items.title: MAKING FIREWEED JELLY - [Living In Alaska 181]
items.description:
Alaska is an easy place to live off of the land if you know how to do it.  Especially in the summer!  With so many varieties of fruits, vegetables and proteins, anyone with a passion for the great outdoors, who knows how to build a shelter and can gather and prepare wild eatable foods can make by without a doubt.  At least until the winter comes.  That's when the REAL challenge begins!  It's been a year since we moved to this beautiful state and we've finally began to truly adjust to our new Alaskan lifestyle.  Last year was a year of discovery and adventure but this year will be a year of living the life I've always dreamed of as an outdoors man, family man and film maker.  There will be many more discoveries to be made and more adventures than my camera batteries will be able to keep up with.  So if you've enjoyed out last year in Alaska then wait until you see what we'll do this year now that we know how to do it RIGHT!

items.title: 20150721: Anchorage to Whittier, The tunnel!
items.description:
21 July 2015: This video is simply a travelogue depicting selected segments of the 1.5 hour trip from Anchorage to Whittier, AK where we were to meet a Phillips Cruises Tour aboard the M/V Klondike Express, the fastest catamaran in Alaska (said to be capable of speeds in excess of 45 mph) for the 12:30 PM "26 Glacier" tour of Prince William Sound.

We travelled the Seward Highway (Alaska I-1) from Anchorage to the Portage Glacier Highway where we continued passage through the "Anton Anderson Memorial Tunnel," otherwise known as the "Whittier Tunnel" on our way to Whittier. At 2.5 miles in length through Maynard Mountain, this tunnel is the 2nd longest highway tunnel and longest combined rail and highway tunnel in North America which shares both train and automotive traffic through a single bore. Ingenious! We've recorded and included the entire trip through the tunnel! Those with claustrophobia may not want to watch this segment!

We documented our travel along these two highways which comprise some of the most beautiful scenery in America with a Cobra Dash Cam recording every inch of our journey. This resulted in over 2 hours of video total, including that of Whittier as we toured the community looking for a place to park...as well as a stop at the Alaskan Maritime Highway office to pick up our ferry boat tickets for our 3rd of August 2015 ride to Bellingham, WA.The challenge was to shorten the length of this video to something time wise under 1 hour. We managed to do so while trying to keep some of the best video along the way intact. 

This video was taken beginning at 6:30 AM, which in part contributed to poor lighting along the way...resulting in sometimes not the best of video quality.

The trip begins 6:30 AM on 21 July 2015 at the JBER RV Park located near Anchorage, then continues into Anchorage where we admitted our two dogs to the "Hound Lounge" Kennels for the day while we travelled on to Whittier for the tour. We followed the Seward Highway to the Portage Glacier Highway located near the former village of Portage, destroyed by the 1964 earthquake. The trip continued to and through the Whittier Tunnel, an adventure in its own right...and on to Whittier. 

This segment actually was originally part of an over two-hour video, which included the glacier tour as well. We decided that just getting to Whittier was worth its own dedicated segment...which is what this video is all about. If you bore easily, and don't enjoy windshield tourism...then you may want to pass on this video. On the other hand, we hope you will watch it, and enjoy the scenery as we did!

Part 2 of this video effort, the 26 Glacier Tour out of Whittier, is in the works and will be uploaded soon!

items.title: WORK STRESS HAPPENS - [Living In Alaska 214]
items.description:
I typically spend 5 to 6 hours editing each day when most vloggers only spend 2 - 3.  Most of my time is spent color correcting, adjusting audio and adding special effects because I'm a bit of a perfectionist but most other vlogger don't go that far with quality.  They focus more on content which is very understandable.  While I do enjoy being a perfectionist, it is beginning to wear me down a bit because it's not giving me enough time to get out and live like I want to for myself and these vlogs.  Keep in mind that the time spent on editing doesn't include the time spent on uploading, sharing, replying to comments, emails and other business related stuff.  So when some people say "5 - 6 hours of editing is hardly work", they need to remember that I don't really get time off because even when I'm not editing, promoting or connecting with viewers, I'm still having to think about vlogging in every given moment that I'm "free".  My mind never gets a break.  Plus, as someone who is a die hard creative, it's hard not to overthink every situation.  To be a daily vlogger, I just need to live my life and share it how it is but as a creative, I always want to tell stories and experiment with new things but I can't seem to find the line between being a vlogger and story teller.  What that said, my vlogs aren't fake in any way.  I just find myself editing my real life events as if they're daily short films when they're not.  So I'm going to keep things simple for the next month and stick to being a "normal" vlogger until things with SMPFilms are worked out.  Things are tough for me right now because of that situation but soon it may be over.

items.title: My First Daddy Vlog! - [Living In Alaska 229]
items.description:
In case you haven't seen our last video (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LbwokYTj7sI), Kristen and I are having a baby!  We're currently about 7 weeks pregnant but we've only known for 2 weeks.  We just couldn't say anything to anyone until we told our parents but now that we've done that, we can finally share this amazing experience.  Most people say to wait at least 3 months to break the news because 80% of the problems that happen during a pregnancy, happen during that time.  However, we're confident that everything will go just fine.  If something does happen, then that's life and we'll deal with it but again, we're feeling pretty good about this.  So far this has been the most amazing experience and I've never been so happy and excited.  Kristen will be the best mother a child can have and I will undoubtedly be the best father that I can possibly be.  The baby isn't here yet and I already love it with everything I am.  Life is good!

items.title: VIDEO FOOTAGE McIntosh Skier Lost his footing rolled uncontrollably down the Neacola mountain.
items.description:
VIDEO FOOTAGE McIntosh Skier Lost his footing rolled uncontrollably down the Neacola mountain
VIDEO FOOTAGE McIntosh Skier Lost his footing rolled uncontrollably down the Neacola mountain
VIDEO FOOTAGE McIntosh Skier Lost his footing rolled uncontrollably down the Neacola mountain

Heart-stopping footage shows skier fall 1,600ft down sheer mountain face - and miraculously survive
Ian McIntosh lost his footing after swerving into a deep trench which sent him careering down the cliff side
A skier is lucky to be alive when he toppled 1,600 feet down a sheer mountain face after losing his footing in the snow.

Heart-stopping video footage captured Ian McIntosh's incredible escape as he rolled uncontrollably down the Neacola mountain range in Alaska, crying out in pain each time his body is bashed on the ground.

Onlookers watch in horror as Ian tumbles at speed, losing his ski equipment along the way.

But amazingly, the lucky skier sits straight back up at the end of his terrifying fall, shouting: "I'm OK, I'm OK!"
Afterwards, Ian said that he had fallen into a five foot-deep trench on one of his first turns which had caused him to lose his balance.
"From there, my slough took over and there was no way to stop, I pulled my airbag to help prevent against any possible trauma injuries as I tumbled to the bottom," he said.

But as he desperately attempted to regain his footing, Ian carried on falling, cartwheeling a terrifying 1,600ft in under a minute.
The breathtaking footage was uploaded to YouTube on November 5 by Teton Gravity Research (TGR) and has clocked up more than 99,000 views.

The extent of his injuries after the fall are not detailed.

More of Ian's more successful ski stunts can be seen on TGR's snowboard and skiing film , Paradise Waits.

items.title: I NEARLY CRASHED! - [Living In Alaska 240]
items.description:
Now I know why not to fly my HELLA-copter in sub-zero temperatures.  Lesson learned!

Here's my recipe for "HELLAbut For Days!":
First, make the sauce in a medium sized bowl
- 2/3 cups of Thai sweet chili sauce
- 3 Tbsp. fish sauce
- 1/2 cup of soy sauce
- about a 1/4 cup of ground coriander
- about 1/4 tsp. black pepper
- about a tablespoon of garlic powder
- 3 tablespoons of lemon juice
- 2 tablespoons of brown sugar
Be sure to mix all of that together well because the brown sugar will settle at the bottom otherwise.
When ready, lay your halibut fillets in a dish or bowl that just fits the fish and carefully pour the sauce over the fish until it's covers the fish 2/3 of the way.  Be sure to flip the fish to make sure it's covered completely.  Stick it in the fridge to marinate for about 10 minutes to 24 hours (doesn't matter too much as long as it's not in there TOO long).
When ready, remove the fish from the dish and lay them out evenly on a baking pan.  Once placed, pour half of the sauce left in the dish onto the halibut.  Stick them in the oven at 400ºF for 10 minutes, pour the rest of the sauce over the fish and continue to cook until the fish is white and flaky on the inside.  Serve with brown rice and broccoli for a nice compliment of flavors and enjoy!   Chances are you'll have a lot of sauce left over, so cook up more fish another night or share the sauce with a friend!

items.title: Beginning a Season 12 Dr Who scarf on a knitting machine
items.description:
Using a Silver Reed model 328 knitting machine, I begin to knit a Season 12 Dr Who scarf. To accomplish the garter stitch, I utilize a garter bar, an accessory for the machine that allows you to remove, flip and add the project back to the machine to turn stockinette to garter.

For this scarf, I am using the acrylic DK recommendations from http://www.doctorwhoscarf.com

KnitPicks Brava Sport:
For Red, Paprika
For Tan, Almond
For Brown, Brindle
For Purple, Currant
Stylecraft Double Knit Special:
For Gold, Gold
For Grey, Graphite
Hayfield Bonus DK Extra Value:
For Green, Moss Green

Watching the tutorial by Alex Murphy on his Doctored Knits site at https://doctoredknits.wordpress.com/ I was able to approximate the color joins.

Thanks to Richard Gamble, my good friend who turned me on to this project after I acquired the knitting machines and who tracked down and ordered the scarf while I went through skeins of waste yarn trying to perfect the procedures I discuss in this video.

I apologize for the light in the background at the beginning of the vlog. I did not notice how bright it was until I went to edit the video later on.

items.title: Eruption of Kilauea volcano in Hawaii
items.description:
1. Aerial, lava flowing from volcano, zoom to closer shot of same
2. Aerial, smoke rising from forested area
3. Aerial, close of lava flowing 
4. Aerial, wide of lava and smoke rising through trees
5. Aerial, streaks of lava flowing through forest
6. Various aerials of smoke rising through forest
7. Aerial, lava flowing through forest
STORYLINE:
A flow of lava from Kilauea volcano in Hawaii was again threatening an all-but-abandoned subdivision of Big Island on Thursday.
The new flow was entering the Royal Gardens subdivision, according to geologists at the Hawaiian Volcano Observatory. 
Most homes in the area have been abandoned or were destroyed in previous lava flows.
Two remaining occupied homes in the area, do not appear to be threatened, experts said. 
The volcano has been slowly erupting for more than 25 years.
Since it began in 1983, the eruption has destroyed 190 structures, covered nearly nine miles of roadway and has been responsible for the deaths of five sightseers.

items.title: Coast Guard rescue of 36 fishermen in the Pacific Ocean
items.description:
Coast Guard coordinates the rescue of 36 fishermen in the Pacific Ocean after their vessel catches fire.
Good Samaritans rescued 36 fishermen from the Pacific Ocean after their 229-foot commercial vessel caught fire 2,071 miles southwest from Hawaii.

The U.S. Coast Guard said in a release it received a request on Saturday (October 24) from the Rescue Coordination Center New Zealand to coordinate the rescue after the Papua New Guinea-flagged Glory Pacific No. 8 caught fire in the Pacific and the crew abandoned ship in two skiffs and several life rafts.

The Coast Guard sent an air crew to the area, which located the 215-foot fishing vessel Lomalo who agreed to assist in the rescue. The crew dropped smoke flares to help the Lomalo crew locate the fishermen and dropped water to the survivors.

The survivors spent more than 10 hours in the water, according to the Coast Guard, before the Lomalo brought them to another vessel to bring them to their next port of call in several days.

No injuries were reported.

items.title: Night Vision Capture of Comet Catalina Dec 9th 2015
items.description:
Image intensifiers are one of the few technologies that provide true, speed of light, real time imaging both direct and indirect.

This video presents true real time viewing captured at 30fps.

No gimmicks, stacking, averaging, stitching, stretching or other processing technique's used to impart a false perception of real time viewing. 

===========================

The use of image intensifiers by the world astronomy community predates solid state detectors such as cmos and ccd's by many decades. 

Vacuum tube photon detectors were the earliest devices used by astronomers to capture photon information from faint celestial bodies. Photon detectors soon progressed into a technology referred to as image intensifiers.

items.title: Aftermath of Gilgit quake
items.description:
Tattu, 100km south west of Gilgit
1. Aerial shot of dust covering landscape
2. Wide shot of the mountain
3. Pan down to destroyed houses
4. People standing in rubble of destroyed house 
5. Close up of man standing in rubble 
6. Pan to destroyed house
7. Man entering destroyed house 

STORYLINE:
Pakistan Army helicopters airlifted injured people to field hospitals on Saturday, while tents and blankets were delivered to thousands of people living outside in bitterly cold conditions after an earthquake in northern Pakistan.

The quake on Thursday destroyed most of five villages in the remote Astore Valley in the Himalayan foothills, killing at least 25 people and injuring hundreds. 

Officials said about 1000 homes were destroyed, and aftershocks that rumbled through the region for more than 24 hours left residents whose houses were still standing too scared to return to them.

Military helicopters have been ferrying medical aid, food and other supplies to the area after roads were cut by landslides caused by the tremors.

Officials said at least 14 children were among the dead, and that the death toll may rise as relief crews sift through the rubble.

Earlier this month, Pakistan's north was hit by a moderate earthquake that killed at least 10 people and injured 48 others.

items.title: DOCK THOUGHT TO HAVE BEEN WASHED AWAY BY JAPAN TSUNAMI COMES ASHORE
items.description:
A nearly 70-foot-long (21-metre) dock that floated ashore on an Oregon beach was torn loose from a fishing port in northern Japan by last year's tsunami and drifted across thousands of miles of Pacific Ocean, a Japanese Consulate official said Wednesday.
A commemorative plaque on the dock showed it was one of four owned by Aomori Prefecture at the port of Misawa on the northern tip of Japan.
One of the four docks turned up several weeks later on an island south of Misawa, but the other two are still missing, said Akihisa Sato, an engineer with Zeniya Kaiyo Service, the dock's Tokyo-based manufacturer. 
The docks weigh 165 tons each, Sato said. 
The one that floated to Oregon was first spotted floating offshore Monday, and mistaken by several people for a barge, said Chris Havel, spokesman for the Oregon Department of Parks and Recreation. 
Havel said it was "the first real verifiable evidence in Oregon of debris of this type." 
It washed ashore early Tuesday on Agate Beach, a mile north of Newport on the central Oregon Coast. 
It's made of concrete with a metal pontoon and measures 66 feet (20 metres) long, 19 feet (5.8 metres) wide and 7 feet (2.1 metres) high. 
The distance between Japan and Oregon is roughly 5,000 miles. (8,046 kilometres)
A radiation check of the dock came up negative, which was to be expected if the dock broke loose before the nuclear power plant accident triggered by the waves. 
The parks department was overseeing efforts to identify and remove the dock. 
State police were posted to keep people from climbing on the dock, said Mitch Vance, shellfish programme manager for the Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife.
Beach-goer Marjie Cannon described the event as "a piece of history, right here in front of us."
The Japanese coastal town of Misawa, where the dock originated, sustained extensive tsunami damage but is north of the most heavily hit areas in Iwate and Miyagi prefectures. 
The four docks that swept away from Misawa were installed four years ago, Sato said. 
They were used to transfer fish from fishing boats to trucks waiting to transport them to market.
Sato said the March 2011 tsunami also destroyed many buildings and structures around the port.
The bulk of the debris from the tsunami is not expected until winter, but fast-moving examples have been arriving on North America's shores. 
They include a soccer ball that washed up in Alaska and a shipping container holding a Harley-Davidson motorcycle with Japanese license plates that turned up in British Columbia earlier this year.

items.title: Genesis 41:50-57 | A Time to Forget | Rich Jones
items.description:
http://www.calvaryhillsboro.org/ 
http://www.calvarybeaverton.org/ 
Subscribe To Watch More: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCMljrvWnX5HWCHwB-GAbCsw
Thank you for watching. God bless you and your family!
We would love to hear your comments and please like and share this video. 

As we continue our study in Genesis we find Joseph’s life taking a dramatic turn. It seemed that everything that could go wrong did go wrong. After receiving a dream from God that he would rise above his brothers, his brothers didn’t think much of Joseph’s dream and plotted to kill him. This was changed into an opportunity to make some money and he was sold as a slave instead. 
 Being purchased by Potiphar, captain of the bodyguard, he found great success in Potiphar’s house. But Potiphar’s wife tried to trap him into a liaison, but he refused. As a result he was thrown into prison, his dreams seeming impossibly distant. 
 Here again he found success and was trusted to oversee other prisoners. He was asked to oversee the chief cupbearer and chief baker who then each had dreams. Joseph was given the interpretation that the cupbearer would be restored, so Joseph asked that he remember to help him get out of prison. But he did not remember for two more years.
 But then Pharaoh had a dream that no one could interpret, and the cupbearer remembered Joseph. When he appeared before Pharaoh he once again pointed toward God as the One to glorify and gave the interpretation – there would be seven years of prosperity followed by seven years of famine. He then suggested ways to prepare for the famine by storing up grain during the seven years of plenty. Pharaoh saw the wisdom of Joseph, set him in a place of authority that he might prepare for the nation for the years of famine. 
 He also gave Joseph an Egyptian wife and she bore him two sons. It is in the naming of these two sons that we focus our study this morning, because as he reveals his heart in the naming of these boys we gain insight into our own lives as well. 

Pastor Rich Jones
Rich Jones Sermons  
Rich Jones Calvary Chapel
Calvary Chapel Worship Center
Calvary Chapel Hillsboro
Calvary Chapel Beaverton

items.title: Extreme Woodturning - Cedar Lampshade
items.description:
http://www.AsWoodTurns.com
My best learning comes from watching someone turn a fantastic project and then making it myself. Soren Berger did a great demo of a lampshade. So I had to try one myself.
My lampshade is Atlas or Titan Cedar which is more dense than the more common western red cedar. It is about 7 1/2 inches in diameter and 8 inches high. I'm leaving it not sanded and without any finish.
With the depth inside the lampshade, this was tough going. I feared that at any moment a catch would destroy my work.
Yet both the lampshade and I survived the experience.
It was challenging.
Good turning.
Enter your email at http://www.AsWoodTurns.com & I'll let you know when the next easy woodturning project video is ready.

items.title: Portland to spend $170m on Washington Park
items.description:
Correction: The Powell Butte Reservoirs are working an operational they went over budget and might still cost more money but as of right now they are holding water. It took longer than planned.

The City Council today just learned that the Reservoir project at Washington Park will cost $100 million more than it was originally supposed to and take 2 years longer than planned. This shouldn't be surprising as these underground Reservoirs seem to be having some serious problems with them. 

The reason this is now going to cost $170 Million and take longer is because the ground is going to have to be stabilized and there is an earthquake concern that needs to be addressed so all of this is going to cost money and take time to complete. 

 http://jgpolitics.com/2015/09/portland-to-spend-on-washingtonpark

items.title: Solomon Islands - Tsunami
items.description:
518145 
POOL
Gizo - 3 April 2007
1. Various aerials of destruction in Gizo
STORYLINE:
At least 28 people were killed in the Solomons and neighbouring Papua New Guinea after a tsunami hit the region on Monday 2nd April, officials said the toll was likely to rise further as a detailed aerial assessment was made of Gizo and surrounding villages where only scattered radio reports have been collected so far.
Survivors picked through ruined stores on Tuesday 3rd looking for drinking water and food in a Solomon Islands town devastated by the tsunami, as an international relief effort started to get underway.
Thousands of people in the town of Gizo in the South Pacific country's far west spent Monday night sleeping under tarpaulins or in the open on a hill behind the town following a massive undersea earthquake that sent tsunami waves crashing through the town.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/6fa82cc6c1a5d2bce3976455408907d1 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Solomon Islands: Cash for work helps natural disaster recovery
items.description:
Climate change directly affects lives around the world, especially as extreme weather events become more common. In the Solomon Islands, villages were washed away when heavy torrential rains, caused two rivers to burst their banks. The ILO's Cash for Work program helps the government, and workers from those communities restore their villages and livelihoods.

** Iles Salomon : du travail contre rémunération pour aider à la reprise après une catastrophe naturelle **

Le changement climatique a un impact dans le monde entier, et notamment les phénomènes climatiques extrêmes sont plus fréquents. Dans les Iles Salomon, des villages ont été emportés par des pluies torrentielles qui ont provoqué la crue de deux rivières. Le programme de l’OIT Travail contre rémunération (Cash for Work) aide le gouvernement, et les travailleurs de ces communautés à reconstruire leurs villages et retrouver un gagne-pain.

** Islas Salomón: Dinero por trabajo para contribuir a la recuperación de desastres naturales **
  
El cambio climático afecta a la vida humana en todo el mundo, en particular los fenómenos meteorológicos extremos cada vez más frecuentes. En las Islas Salomón, varias localidades fueron arrasadas por las fuertes lluvias torrenciales y dos ríos se desbordaron. El programa "Dinero por trabajo" de la OIT ayuda al Gobierno y a los trabajadores de esas comunidades a reconstruir sus hogares y recuperar sus medios de subsistencia.

items.title: Australian FM tours scene of riots in Solomon Isles capital
items.description:
1. Various of Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer
touring the destroyed Chinatown area of Honiara
2. Pan from destroyed building to Downer walking past camera
3. SOUNDBITE: (English) Alexander Downer, Australian Foreign
Minister:
"Well, it''s tragic that the Chinese community has been targeted
in this way, and that Chinatown here in Honiara has been virtually
destroyed. I mean it''s a terrible, terrible thing."
4. Downer talking to Australian policewoman
5. Various of Downer talking with Australian policeman
6. Downer inspecting destroyed vehicles
STORYLINE:
Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer flew into the Solomon Islands early on Saturday, making his first point of call an inspection of the wrecked Chinatown district ahead of talks with the prime minster.
Police are hunting  the instigators of a violent riot that devastated much of the capital this week, a security official said on Saturday.
Tens of millions of dollars in damage was inflicted on businesses in Honiara''s Chinatown by riots, arson and looting which destroyed more than 90 percent of the area''s shops and premises.
"It''s tragic that the Chinese community has been targeted in this way, and that Chinatown here in Honiara has been virtually destroyed. I mean it''s a terrible, terrible thing," said Downer as he toured Chinatown.
The violence was sparked by rumours that China or Taiwan had paid lawmakers to support the election of the Pacific nation''s unpopular new prime minister, Snyder Rini.
The upheaval in the South Pacific nation forced ethnic Chinese to flee their homes and seek shelter under police protection.
Australia, New Zealand and Fiji have boosted police and troop numbers in the archipelago to more than 1,050 over recent days as police investigate who instigated the rioting.
Overnight on Friday, only one arrest and a sole bottle-throwing incident disturbed the fragile calm since the riots.
In talks with Rini, Downer was expected to emphasise the need for the government to fight corruption and strengthen its ability to enforce law and order.
Opposition parties plan a no-confidence motion against Rini on Wednesday, which he has said he expects to win.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/37d19eae17a64c8e958de490e1ffbca9 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Sunny Barbados / Sea Eagle,  Beach Bungalow
items.description:
Sea Eagle on our superb stretch of beautiful St James beach - superb seascapes, spectacular sunsets - Spacious, with excellent local facilities, transport and watersport connections. A privately owned, 'local living' property ideal for independent, easy-going holiday makers. Relax on our golden beach with major trees for shade. 
Welcome!
Situated in a very quiet cul-de-sac.The charming Sea Eagle Beach side Bungalow is a lovely beachfront cottage at Fitts Village, St James. Offering two bedrooms, air conditioned,  two en suite bathrooms, open plan lounge and two dining area, patio and outdoor dining. Direct access to a sandy beach. Ideal for those who love to dive, snorkel an enjoy watersports. The property is in a residential area with shops and restaurants within easy walking distance. 
'Sea Eagle' is  offered as accommodation of a very good 'local-living' standard, with white & light decoration, with white tiled floors throughout. 
You have private car parking also at the Bungalow a private garden, a gate directly onto our beach with trees for shade. 
With a breezy garden and veranda, perfect for BBQ's, cocktails and watching the turtles in the waves.
This district on the west coast of Barbados is ideal for a relaxing Caribbean vacation. It was its placement at the edge of a tranquil and clear blue ocean that would see the Fitts district become a predominantly fishing village. Fishing still goes on there to this day, extending toward its neighbouring Paynes Bay Fishing Market. The area contains several reefs and with clear blue waters its good for snorkelling. Occasionally you may even spot a turtle surface.
Sea-Eagle Beach Bungalow is ideal for the persons or couple, or family who are budget conscious but also want the luxury of being on the beach without the expense.
Fitts Village is 25-30 minutes drive from the airport. Fitts Village is a fishing village on the west coast, it has it's own white sandy beaches and stunning blue water. Fitts Village has its own supermarket & restaurants and is within easy access into Holetown and Bridgetown. The villa is ideally located for exploring the west coast and is within easy walking distance to local amenities.
Buses pass directly by the Beach Highway every 5 mins or so in both directions - taking one is a great experience.
For shopping Limegrove, Barbados' first mixed use lifestyle centre, is located in the heart of Holetown which is 5 minutes on the bus and is home to many of the world's leading retail brands. Unparalleled in Barbados and the Caribbean region, Limegrove incorporates a range of local and global retailers in a setting built around three distinctly different courtyards including boutiques, restaurants, delis, cafes, bars, gourmet foods, an art gallery, cinemas, a spa and salon, and a range of special event spaces. If you enjoy night life Holetown or Bridgetown are close by for late night entertainment and many other attractions.

items.title: FLOW Paints Barbados Blue  - Islandwide motorcade excites customers
items.description:
CWC took to the streets over the weekend with a mini Crop Over type motorcade as the company continued to “Paint Barbados Blue” launching its refreshed consumer brand, Flow. The motorcade was part of a series of events that were held across the island from July 16-19 to celebrate of the new Flow.  
Starting from St. Lucy in the north and St. Philip in the east, the brightly decorated convoy, which included Flow Brand Ambassador Anderson ‘Blood’ Armstrong, traversed the island, stopping in communities with give-aways and chances to win while introducing Barbadians to the new Flow, its products and services. 
Managing Director of Cable and Wireless Barbados, Niall Sheehy noted the brand had been officially launched on Thursday to employees and key stakeholders and on Friday and Saturday to customers in Flow retail stores and throughout communities island-wide. 

“Following exciting launch events earlier in the week, the ‘FLOWing’ motorcade is a fitting way to introduce the new Flow to the people of Barbados, so that they can get an up-close and personal look at the new brand. It is also a great way for our employees to meet our customers face-to-face, and for them to interact with us and share their perspectives,” he said.

Sheehy added, “We are proud to be able to offer to our customers, and potential customers, new and exciting quad play opportunities as we commit to putting our customers at the forefront of our business. We want to completely transform the customer experience and provide best-in-class service.”

Director of Marketing, Shelly-Ann Hee Chung, said that through the fun and entertainment provided by the ‘FLOWing’ motorcade, the company was able to bring Barbadians up to date on current developments and future plans surrounding the new Flow.
“The response from the public has been overwhelming and it was great to hit the streets with the Flow team. We are very excited about what the future holds,” she said. “Of course, we realize that our success will not only be dependent upon the technology available to us, but the way in which we deliver that technology to our customers.” 
After parading through the streets of Barbados, the motorcade culminated with a mini concert in Independence Square featuring Flow Brand Ambassadors, Lil Rick, Peter Ram, Kirk Brown, Blood and Shanta Prince, as well as a mini exposition, which showcased the new brand’s products and services. 

As part of its commitment to customer service, the new Flow honoured its very first residential customer since the new brand launch at the concert event. Carol Bradshaw took Flow’s TV Essential Watch services and bundled it with the Superfast Bundled Plus Broadband service. As a thank you, Carol was awarded three months of free service from Flow. Kyle Smith was also a winner as and received a 40 inch Samsung TV as he was the first customer to sign up for quad-play services – TV, Internet, Voice and Mobile.

The motorcade was part of the official introduction of Flow to the public in the first of several market launches set to take place across the Caribbean. Flow will now be the consumer brand operating in some 15 markets across the region including Cayman Islands, Trinidad and Tobago, Barbados and Jamaica among others.

With the integration of Columbus International Inc and Cable & Wireless, Flow is now poised to deliver quad play services - mobile, broadband, fixed voice and TV/video to its customers.

items.title: Evening News July 22, 2015
Powerful quake rocks eastern Caribbean
items.description:
SHOTLIST
1. Zoom out from partly collapsed house to wide
2. Wide of damaged house
3. Close of locals inspecting damage on ground
4. People looking from side of road
5. Various of cracks in the road
6. People under partly collapsed house inspecting damage
7. Various of man standing on collapsed wall of house
8. Zoom in on damaged house
9. Various of man by house
10. Zoom in on damage
11. Onlookers
12. Wide of onlookers looking at house, zoom in on partly collapsed wall
13. Zoom in on cracks in the ground near house
14. Various of people coming out of airport terminal
15. Various of people gathered outside terminal building
16. Exterior of airport
STORYLINE
A powerful earthquake on Thursday rocked the eastern Caribbean.
Roofs collapsed and panicked office workers and shoppers fled
into the streets of several islands.
In Barbados, a woman was trampled after she tripped in the chaos of leaving an office building in Bridgetown, the capital.  She is listed in a stable condition in hospital. 
Another woman broke her leg while trying to rush out of her home, according to a police report.
AP Television footage showed large cracks in the ground in the aftermath of the magnitude 7.4 quake.
It was centred 14 miles (23 kilometres) northwest of Martinique's coastline and lasted longer than 20 seconds.
It apparently took the worst toll on this French island, collapsing the roofs of a bank and a store in the capital, Fort-de-France, and leaving cracks in several other buildings.
Two people in Martinique were injured when they panicked and jumped through windows, government official Lorne Martin told Radio Martinique. 
Others were slightly injured when they tried to flee their homes, and dozens were receiving treatment for panic attacks, she said. 
Other islands in the Lesser Antilles including St. Lucia and St. Vincent reported cracks in homes and waterlines.
The quake struck at 1400 EST (1900 GMT) and was felt hundreds of miles (kilometres) away in Puerto Rico to the west, and Venezuela and Suriname to the south.
Experts said the depth of the quake, at 90 miles (145 kilometres), spared the region from severe destruction.
The Pacific Tsunami Warning Center in Hawaii said the quake was too deep to generate a destructive tsunami.
Government officials announced schools would be closed on Friday and that some roads on the northern end of the island have been blocked because of cracks.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/496b461d45e578bd7add3ba5b2c93a20

items.title: WRAP British PM's eldest son briefly hospitalised; adds Minister of Health
items.description:
1. Wide of entrance to the Queen Elizabeth Hospital
2. Pan of hospital sign
3. People entering hospital
4. SOUNDBITE (English) Doctor Jerome Walcott, Barbados Minister of Health:
"I received information yesterday that (British Prime Minister) Tony Blair's son had been admitted to QEH (Queen Elizabeth Hospital) with abdominal pain. On further discussion with his physician, the surgeon who looked after him, today, I was informed that he was admitted yesterday with abdominal pain, and he underwent certain investigations - ultrasounds, x-rays and blood investigations. At one stage surgery was contemplated but this was not done - when he was reviewed later in the day it was found that his condition had improved considerably. So surgery was considered but was never done as the patient was settling, he settled."
5. Zoom out from a panel
6. Ambulance entering hospital 
7. Various of exteriors of the hospital
8. Ambulance outside gate
9. Cars parked outside hospital
10. Close up of name on one side of the ambulance
STORYLINE:
British Prime Minister Tony Blair's eldest son was discharged on Friday after being treated in a Caribbean hospital for a stomach ailment, officials said. 
Blair's Downing Street office said Euan Blair, 22, was admitted while vacationing with his family in Barbados, but gave no further details. 
A spokeswoman, speaking on condition of anonymity in line with official policy said Blair had later been released. 
Tony Blair returned to work in London on Friday. 
Doctor Jerome Walcott, Barbados Minister of Health, commented, "I was informed that he was admitted yesterday with abdominal pain, and he underwent certain investigations - ultrasounds, x-rays and blood investigations."
"At one stage surgery was contemplated but this was not done - when he was reviewed later in the day it was found that his condition had improved considerably," he continued.
Euan Blair is expected to attend Yale University in the United States this year. 
He has completed an undergraduate degree course in ancient history at Bristol University in England. 
Euan Blair, one of the prime minister's four children, has attracted considerable media attention in the UK. 
He was arrested in 2000 when police found him drunk in central London after celebrating the end of school exams.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/89fd5a8ded35d070db7f7b52e002d634

12. Policeman pushing back and beating crowd outside warehouse distributing chlorine pills and soap
13. Various of crowd outside warehouse
14. Various of people receiving soap an chlorine pills
15. Various of water purification plant being installed in the town
STORYLINE
A cholera outbreak that has killed more than 250 people in rural Haiti is stabilising, health officials said on Monday, as aid groups and the government race to prevent it from spreading to the capital's squalid camps of earthquake survivors.
The outbreak was expected to continue spreading, but aid groups and the government said a drop in the death rate and the number of new cases suggested it could progress more gradually than feared.
Yet the shortage of doctors or government officials in Haiti's countryside make these assertions difficult to verify.
In the small town of Petite Riviere, not far from St. Marc, the epicentre of the outbreak, crowds of people poured into a small clinic at the local hospital where a team of Doctors Without Borders had arrived the previous day.  
Ovely Boucher, leading the team, said efforts were ongoing to make clean water available, as well as providing treatment, and medical supplies including soap and water purification tablets.
Cholera can cause vomiting and diarrhoea so severe it can kill from dehydration in hours.
Aid workers say the risk of cholera is magnified by the extreme poverty faced by people displaced by the 12 January quake, which killed as many as 300-thousand people and destroyed much of the capital city. 
Haitians living in the camps risk disease by failing to wash their hands, or scooping up standing water and then proceeding to wash fruits and vegetables.
Health Ministry Director Gabriel Timothee said the outbreak has killed 259 people and sickened 3,342.
At a news conference on Monday he said only 2,981 people were hospitalised in the Artibonite region, a smaller number than in previous days.
Water purification tablets and oral rehydration salts _ used to counteract potentially lethal dehydration caused by
diarrhea _ have been widely distributed in the region where the river or rainwater remain the only water source for
many, said an official with the aid group Partners in Health.
Haiti, which had not suffered a cholera outbreak in at least 50 years, is the latest developing country to be
afflicted by the disease that sickens an estimated 3 million (m) to 5 million (m) people a year and kills 100,000.

items.title: Thousands of Catholics flock to mountainside for religious gathering
items.description:
Thousands of pilgrims flocked to a barren mountainside in central Haiti for a two-day religious gathering over the weekend.
Organised by Our Lady of Fatima Bible Centre, the event in the town of Bois-Neuf drew clergy and parishioners alike, in order to encourage conversion to Catholicism or a renewal of faith.
The priests marched up the mountain on Sunday, blessing pilgrims with holy water, and were followed by a procession of women who danced behind them carrying baskets of fruit and vegetables on their heads as an offering.
Pilgrims listened intently, many holding rosary beads, as priest Jules Campion called on people to convert to Catholicism.
Campion used the devastating earthquake that hit Haiti in 2010 to call on people to convert.
"If we don't convert, we will have another 12 January 2010 - but worse. If we don't convert Port-au-Prince won't be destroyed - it will disappear completely. You must convert," he implored the crowd.
The earthquake killed tens of thousands of people and displaced 1.5 (m) million others.
The pilgrims sang and danced and also took part in group prayers.
"Prayer is really important, it helps you to recharge mentally and spiritually with god," said pilgrim Micheal Cherilus.
Some of the pilgrims also carried their passports with them in hopes that they may secure a visa to a country with more opportunities than what deeply impoverished Haiti has to offer.

items.title: Shocking Bizarre moment || News reporter is licked || passerby Licks neck || Video goes viral 2015
items.description:
If there’s one sure-fire way to get your 15 seconds of fame (and two days of people thinking you’re an idiot), it’s to mess with a reporter on live TV.

 

Some people shout swearwords, some lick reporter’s necks, some just stand there.

Maybe it’s the thrill of messing with someone trying to do a job, maybe it’s just an excuse for a cool story, but people love messing around with news reporters (and we love watching them).

Bizarre moment TV news reporter is licked by passerby live on air

    1 comment
    15:20, 16 September 2015
    Updated 15:28, 16 September 2015
    By Elle Griffiths

Tim Becker was reporting on a vote to legalise marijuana when a blonde woman appeared behind him and took a fancy to him

    21 Shares
    Share
    Tweet
    +1
    Pinterest

A news reporter in the US got a shock when he was LICKED by a passerby during a report live on air.

Tim Becker was reporting on a vote to legalise marijuana for KOIN 6 , a local station in Portland Oregon , when a blonde woman appeared behind him.

Speaking to the hosts in the studio and facing the camera, Becker was completely unaware the woman was stood there.

Without warning she licked the journalist's neck and understandably took him by surprise.

Looking completely confused he recoiled in shock before taking a look to see who or what was behind him.

He then took a second to compose himself, saying: "excuse me".

But the consummate professional wasn't rattled and continued his report smoothly.

items.description:
Footage has surfaced of a newborn baby being rescued after it was dumped in a black bin bag on the side of the road.

The video shows a passers-by desperately trying to save the baby - which still had its umbilical cord attached.

One woman, wearing pink, puts on protective gloves and delicately tries to manoeuvre the baby onto a blanket.

After she has picked the baby up, the baby's umbilical cord is revealed.

There is also more contents in the bag which could possibly be the mother's placenta.

The video emerged on LiveLeak and is believed to have been filmed in the Philippines.

Amazingly, the baby has survived its traumatic entry into the world.

items.title: California highway interchange collapses after tanker catches fire
items.description:
No Access USA
++NIGHT SHOTS++
1. Wide shot damaged bridge, flames and smoke
2. Close-up of flames
3. Wide shot damaged bridge, flames and smoke
4. Various of collapsed bridge and flames
5. Close-up charred bridge support
6. Wide of flames
7. Wide of onlookers on bridge
8. Wide of onlookers and truck on bridge
9. Wide of flames and collapsed bridge 
10. Close-up flames
11. Wide of scene
STORYLINE:
A section of freeway that funnels traffic onto the San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge in California collapsed early on Sunday after a gasoline tanker truck overturned and caught fire.
The heat from the fire was intense enough to melt part of the freeway and cause the collapse.
The truck's driver managed to walk away from the scene with second-degree burns.
No other injuries were reported, which officials said principally because the accident happened so early on a Sunday morning. 
Police said the truck driver took a taxi to a nearby hospital.
The tanker, carrying 8,600 gallons (32,545 litres) of gasoline, ignited around 3:45 am (10:45 GMT) after crashing into a pylon on the interchange, which connects westbound lanes of Interstate 80 to southbound I-880, about half a mile from the Bay Bridge's toll plaza.
The fire melted a second interchange from eastbound Interstate 80 to eastbound Interstate 580 located above the first interchange, causing a 250-yard (230-metre) section of the roadway to collapse onto the roadway below.
Witnesses reported flames from the blaze reached up to 200 feet (60 metres) high.
The Bay Bridge consists of two heavily travelled, double-decked bridges about two miles (3.2 kilometres) long, straddling San Francisco Bay. 
State transportation officials said 280-thousand commuters take the bridge into San Francisco each day.
Authorities said the accident on a highway interchange could take months to repair, and that it would cause the worst disruption for Bay Area commuters since a 1989 earthquake damaged a section of the Bay Bridge itself.

items.title: 6915A San Francisco: Scientists are worried by the threat of another earthquake
items.description:
6915/A: SAN FRANCISCO: WILL THE QUAKE COME?

San Francisco is situated on a major geological fault,
and over the past twelve months or so scientists have
become increasingly worried by the threat of another
earthquake of the same magnitude that destroyed the
city back in 1906.  One rather wild notion current in the
area at the moment is that the whole Californian
seaboard could just slide away into the Pacific.  The
scientists are a good deal less pessimistic than that,
but there does seem to be cause for concern.  We
visited San Francisco, and nearby Hollister, "earth
quake capital of the nation", and interviewed three
scientists:  Karl Steinbrugge, a world authority on
structural damage caused by earthquakes; Richard
Jahns, Dean of Stanford University School of Earth
Sciences; and Doctor Don Tocker of the Earth Movement
Laboratories in San Francisco.


You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/841104b5233f08bbaedc93715db05c59

items.title: Japan Tsunami 2011 - Tohoku Earthquake Shocking Video
items.description:
Japan Tsunami 2011 - Tohoku Earthquake Shocking Video

An erupting volcanic island that is expanding off Japan could trigger a tsunami if its freshly-formed lava slopes collapse into the sea, scientists say.

The small, but growing, island appeared last year and quickly engulfed the already-existing island of Nishinoshima, around 1000 kilometres south of Tokyo.

It now covers 1.26 square kilometres.

The island's craters are currently spewing out 200,000 cubic metres of lava every day - enough to fill 80 Olympic swimming pools - which is accumulating in its east, scientists said.

"If lava continues to mount on the eastern area, part of the island's slopes could collapse and cause a tsunami," warned Fukashi Maeno, assistant professor of the Earthquake Research Institute at the University of Tokyo.

He said a rockfall of 12 million cubic metres of lava would generate a one metre tsunami that could travel faster than a bullet train, hitting the island of Chichijima - 130kms away - in around 18 minutes, he said.

Chichijima, home to about 2000 people, is the largest island in the Ogasawara archipelago, a wild and remote chain that is administratively part of Tokyo.

"The ideal way to monitor and avoid a natural disaster is to set up a new tsunami and earthquake detection system near the island, but it's impossible for anyone to land on the island in the current situation," Maeno added.

An official from the Japan Meteorological Agency, which monitors earthquakes and tsunamis, said the agency is watching for any signs of anything untoward.

"We studied the simulation this morning, and we are thinking of consulting with earthquake prediction experts ... about the probability of this actually happening, and what kind of measures we would be able to take," he said.

Japan's northeast was ravaged by a huge tsunami in March 2011, when a massive undersea earthquake sent a wall of water barrelling into the northeast coast, killing more than 18,000 people and wrecking whole towns.

Link Video http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TmGm8PlHnXs

items.title: Dawn service to remember victims of 1906 earthquake
items.description:
SHOTLIST
POOL 
San Francisco - 18 April 2006
1. Wreath laying ceremony 
Library of Congress, Prelinger Archive - No re-use/re-sale without clearance
2. Black & white footage of Market Street, San Francisco prior to earthquake
POOL 
San Francisco - 18 April 2006
3.  Wreath laying ceremony at earthquake memorial
Library of Congress, Prelinger Archive  - No re-use/re-sale without clearance
4. Black & white footage of Market Street following earthquake 
5. Black & white footage of residential boarding house area after earthquake
POOL
San Francisco - 18 April 2006
6. Tolling of bells on anniversary of earthquake
7. SOUNDBITE: (English) Gavin Newson, San Francisco Mayor: 
"Do you have any early memories of the quake?"
8. SOUNDBITE: (English) Mildred Morganstein, Quake Survivor:
"No, just that it was the biggest shock and a great deal of misery going on. People moving, losing their homes, and people having to sleep in the park and away things. Not being able to get back in their homes where they could cook and sleep and things like that."
Library of Congress - Prelinger Archive - No re-use/re-sale without clearance
9. Black & white footage of armed guard standing at intersection in San Francisco after quake
POOL
San Francisco - 18 April 2006
10. Wailing of sirens at earthquake memorial
11. SOUNDBITE: (English) Joanne Hayes White, San Francisco Fire Chief:
"And really, what today is about, as we commemorate and celebrate and look to our future, we look to a bright future, we want to make sure we''re the most prepared city that we can be. And we need all of you in our community to take that responsibility to become personally prepared, personally prepared in your homes, with your families and pets as well as in your workplaces. We want to do all we can, and, as a city collectively, we can be very prepared."
Library of Congress - Prelinger Archive - No re-use/re-sale without clearance
12. Black & white footage of makeshift housing following earthquake
POOL
San Francisco - 18 April 2006
13. UPSOUND (English) Gavin Newson, San Francisco Mayor, interviewing quake survivor Norma Norwood: 
Newson: "Well, how old are you now?"
Norwood: "I''m 99. I''m a result of the earthquake."
Newson: "Now you''re talking. I don''t want to pry into anyone''s personal life, but, what do you mean about being a result of the earthquake?"
Norwood: "I was born, I was conceived and born in a tent in Golden Gate Park."
Library of Congress - Prelinger Archive - No re-use/re-sale without clearance
17. Black & white footage of ruins of San Francisco following earthquake
STORYLINE
Sirens wailed through the city before dawn in San Francisco on Tuesday marking the moment 100 years earlier when the Great Quake shattered the city, killing thousands as it levelled buildings and touched off fires that burned for days.
A handful of centenarians who survived that devastation joined hundreds of residents for a moment of silence and a memorial ceremony to remember one of the worst natural disasters in U.S. history.
Most of the city''s 400,000 residents were still in bed when the magnitude-7.8 earthquake struck at 5:12 a.m. on April 18, 1906.
The epicentre was a few miles (kilometres) offshore of the city, but it was felt as far away as Oregon and Nevada. 
From cracked chimneys, broken gas lines and toppled chemical tanks, fires broke out and swept across the city, burning for days. 
Ruptured water pipes left firefighters helpless, while families carrying what they could fled to parks that had become makeshift morgues.
One hundred eleven year old Mildred Morganstein remembers the hardships that befell her family and neighbours immediately following the quake.
But they disagree over whether people should love the city or leave it.

items.title: Driver crashes into two homes, leaving car suspended in air
items.description:
1. Car wedged between two houses
2. Close shot, car stuck in wall
3. Zoom into damaged car 
4. SOUNDBITE: (English) Kim Macedo, resident of house hit by car:
"I thought it was an earthquake and I kind of was in my bed bracing for an aftershock or something, and then I heard my mom yelling there was someone in the yard, and she told me to call 911. So I did and I went downstairs to see what was going on and I saw that." 
5. Pull out of damage to house
6. Zoom into car 
7. Back view of car between houses
8. SOUNDBITE: (English) Officer M. Koons, Los Angeles Police Department:
"We responded to a call of a car stuck between two houses as we got here we were told that there was a DUI (driving under the influence) in custody by other officers and he is at the station now.  We do not know anything further."
(Q: "Anybody hurt?") 
"No."
9. Police looking at car
10. Pull out from driver of crashed car in back of police car
11. Zoom into car stuck between houses 
STORYLINE:
California police say one man is under arrest and another is being sought after an alleged drunk driver crashed into two homes, leaving his car suspended five feet (1.5 metres) above the ground in San Pedro early on Sunday morning. 
The car crashed into two houses at 1:30 am local time (0930 GMT). 
Police at the scene said the alleged drunk driver drove his car over a kerb and it then crashed sideways, ending up wedged between the walls of two houses.
One of the houses suffered a severed gas line.
A resident of one of the houses said he thought he was experiencing an earthquake and waited for an aftershock before realising the shaking was the result of the car crashing into their house.
Police arrested the driver at the scene for suspicion of driving under the influence. 
A crane was called to the scene to lift the car out of the houses.

items.title: A look at how the earthquake has damaged the Napa Valley wine industry
items.description:
Businesses in California's wine capital mopped up thousands of dollars in high-end vintages on Monday, after an earthquake caused 1 billion US dollars in damage, according to official estimates.
In Napa Valley, two hotels and 12 wineries were still closed on Monday, as well as many of the businesses downtown, local officials said, amid a rush to get the tourist hotspot back in shape for the summer's final holiday weekend.
With the dust still settling from Sunday's magnitude-6.0 quake, centered near the city of Napa, government and tourism officials encouraged visitors to keep flocking to the charming towns, tasting rooms, restaurants and spas that drive the Napa Valley economy.
While cleanup will take time and broken water mains remained a problem, they said, the worst damage and disruption was confined to the city's downtown, where a post office, library and a 141-room hotel were among 150 homes and buildings deemed unsafe to occupy.
The strongest earthquake to hit the San Francisco Bay Area in a quarter of a century also caused several injuries, triggered fires that destroyed or damaged six mobile homes, and ruptured gas lines.



You can license this story through AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/a8b54d8ea576ce2eb5864535b135d42f 
Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

items.title: Largest earthquake in 25 years hits the San Francisco Bay Area
items.description:
A large earthquake rolled through California's northern Bay Area early on Sunday, damaging some buildings, igniting fires, knocking out power to tens of thousands and sending residents running out of their homes in the darkness.
The 6.0-magnitude quake caused six significant fires, including at four mobile homes, according to a Napa Division Fire official.
The epicentre of the earthquake that struck Northern California, the strongest in the area in 25 years, was just six miles southwest of Napa, California, the centre of California's winemaking region.
The US Geological Survey (USGS) described the tremor as the largest earthquake to shake the Bay Area since the 6.9-magnitude Loma Prieta quake in 1989.
Several other smaller fires were reported and firefighting efforts were complicated by broken water mains.
Local residents counted the cost of the damage on Sunday.
"All my valuable stuff is in the bedroom so most of everything is gone," said 83-year-old Nola Rawlins whose mobile home was destroyed by fire.
Winemakers in California's storied Napa Valley woke up to thousands of broken bottles and barrels as a result of Sunday's earthquake.
The earthquake couldn't have come at a worse time for the region, which has just started harvesting the 2014 crop.

items.title: SJ Quakes Pres Dave Kaval Academy Conversation
items.description:
San Jose Earthquakes Club President Dave Kaval took some time out of his busy schedule to sit down with the guys from The Original Winger and have an in-depth conversation about the newest soccer specific stadium to come to Major League Soccer, the San Jose Earthquakes and their Academy system as well as the future of American Soccer.

Dave Kaval, a native of Cleveland, Ohio, who earned a Bachelor’s degree and an M.B.A. from Stanford University, was hired as the President of the San Jose Earthquakes in October of 2010. He oversees the business and technical sides of the franchise.

Kaval led the Quakes efforts to design, develop, and privately finance the new 18,000 seat, $100m soccer specific stadium that opened for the 2015 MLS season.

items.title: San Francisco earthquake Oakland  live report
items.description:
OAKLAND -- A magnitude-4.0 temblor that rattled nerves in the East Bay on Monday morning was a very shallow but routine geologic shrug in an area notorious for seismic risk -- and yet another reminder of the threat lurking from a fault that's the Bay Area's most overdue for a major quake.

A locked-up patch of rocks a mere 3 miles under Piedmont suddenly broke loose along the Hayward Fault, triggering a wake-up call felt from Santa Rosa to Santa Cruz.

"Because it was shallower than normal, people in the vicinity felt more intensified shaking than usual for an earthquake of this magnitude," said Keith Knudsen, deputy director of the Earthquake Science Center at the U.S. Geological Survey in Menlo Park.

 USGS Map
USGS Map
Monday's quake was the second magnitude-4.0 quake on the Hayward Fault in less than a month -- and comes almost a year after the magnitude-6.0 Napa temblor that was the region's biggest in 25 years -- but there is no indication it is a precursor of the Big One. While there was a flurry of aftershocks following Monday's 6:49 a.m. earthquake, there is only a 10 percent chance that it will be followed by a larger earthquake in the next week, Knudsen said.

The San Andreas Fault ~ Natural Beauty Masks Hidden Dangers
items.description: The San Andreas Fault is the world's longest earthquake fault, stretching more than 800 miles through California, into the Pacific Ocean. I recorded this video while walking along The Sawyer Camp Trail, a San Mateo County Park. The deer in this video are a prime example of hidden dangers amidst the natural beauty of this area of the San Andreas Fault.  Anytime you can see deer in this area, you can be certain that mountain lions are also in the immediate vicinity.  This is mountain lion territory and deer are the main source of food for mountain lions. Hikers are warned never to walk alone on The Sawyer Camp Trail, as well as on all San Mateo County Park Trails.

Milton and I went after Milton got off work. We arrived around 8:30 pm and enjoyed wandering freely through the museum.

items.title: Work In Progress: Investigations South of Market | YBCA
items.description:
See more at http://ybca.org/work-progress

Emerging from a desire to create a dynamic, nontraditional experiment in our galleries, Work in Progress: Investigations South of Market forefronts the process of art making and opens up a conversation about site, both within and beyond YBCA’s doors. Responding to a prompt from YBCA, six artists take a unique point of departure from which to explore the SOMA neighborhood. Inspirations include the events that have shaped the neighborhood including the 1906 earthquake and fire, which physically and psychologically transformed the landscape of San Francisco, the more recent changes that have come about since the opening of AT&T Park in 2000, and the environmental impacts of the building boom. Other projects look at the people who have inhabited the neighborhood over the years, from the Ohlone to the wealthy landowners of the 19th century to those who work and live here today.

Work in Progress is an examination of place, artistic practice, and space. For the project, we invited a group of artists to submit proposals that address San Francisco’s South of Market neighborhood through research-based inquiry. The selected participants—Terry Berlier, Val Britton, Tom Loughlin, Jenny Odell, Stadium Projects (Joshua Peder Stulen, Monte Masi, and Lex Kosieradzki), and Weston Teruya—have been grouped into three sequential residencies, and the galleries are effectively becoming a working studio for them during their time at YBCA. As each residency rotates out, the works produced remain on site, with each residency building on the last and presenting a new layer of the cumulative experience.

YBCA’s neighborhood has long been a locus of change, contention, and renewal. The newly commissioned works for this exhibition aim to deepen our understanding of, and connect back to, this rich history and legacy. Even as the artists investigate a specific locale within San Francisco, they also look beyond it, exploring broader themes of generosity, urban planning, environmental impact, and historical change.

items.title: earthquake raw video  British Columbia
items.description:
B.C.'s South Coast was hit by an earthquake that shook many people from their sleep just before midnight, in what one seismologist called the largest quake in the region in years.

Some people near the epicentre northeast of Victoria reported their homes shifted, and others were knocked off their feet.

"The house moved seriously to the right, came back, it was loud. The aquarium had a mini-tsunami and overflowed. We were in the kitchen and got tossed into the counter," wrote one commenter on the CBC website.

Many reported feeling a large impact that felt like a truck hitting their homes, while others in Metro Vancouver reported windows rattling and items on walls shaking.

"I'm about 6 km from the epicentre and it felt like a truck had crashed into my house," wrote another commenter.

"I felt it in the West End here of Vancouver and I looked out my window to see if a truck had hit the side of my building! It was quite a sharp jolt that made my walls bend and creak, but nothing really shook or swayed," wrote another.
