items.title: Earthquake 26 October, 2015 - Pakistan T.V news
items.description:
8.1 magnitude quake felt in Pakistan, India, Afghanistan
Published on Oct 26, 2015.
ISLAMABAD: A powerful earthquake of 7.7 magnitude has struck major cities of Pakistan, causing tremors in the country. The quake was also felt in the neighbouring countries.

Buildings Islamabad rattled for at least two minutes, while tremors were also felt in the Afghan capital Kabul.

According to initial reports, some buildings collapsed in Peshawar, Dir, Swat and Shangla while rescue officials feared there could be casualties.

The National Disaster Management Authority, in a statement, said next 24 hours were crucial.

Tremors were also felt as far away as Islamabad in Pakistan and the Afghan capital Kabul, but not in neighbouring Nepal which was hit by a major quake in April, according to AFP.

Hundreds of people raced from buildings onto the streets in several Pakistani cities while the quake was also felt in the Himalayan region of Kashmir.

According to the US Geological Survey, an earthquake with magnitude 7.5 occurred at 2.09pm (PST) on Oct 26, 2015. It said the quake was 212.5 km deep and centred 82 km southeast of Feyzabad in a remote area of Afghanistan in the HinduKush mountain range.

The Pakistan Meteorological Department said the magnitude of the quake was 8.1

items.description:
الحمدللہ رب العالمین والصلوٰۃ والسلام علیٰ سید المرسلین
اما بعد فاعوذ باللہ من الشیطٰن الرجیم بسم اللہ الرحمٰن الرحیم

اَلصَّلوٰةُ وَالسَّلَامُ عَلَيْكَ يَارَسُوْلَ اللهِ وَعَلٰى اٰلِكَ وَأَصْحٰبِكَ يَاحَبِيْبَ اللهِ
صلوا علی الحبیب! 
صلی اللہ تعالٰی علٰی محمد صلی اللہ تعالٰی علیہ وآلہ وسلم

نیکی کی دعوت
ہم اللہ عزوجل کے عاجز بندے اور اس کے پیارے حبیب صلی اللہ تعالٰی علیہ وسلم کے ادنی غلام ہیں۔ یقینا زندگی بے حد مختصر ہے ہم لمحہ بہ لمحہ موت کے قریب ہوتے جارہے ہیں۔ عنقریب ہمیں اندھیری قبر میں اتار دیا جائے گا۔ نجات تمام جہانوں کے پالنے والے اللہ رب العٰلمین عزوجل کی اطاعت اور مومنین پر رحم و کرم فرمانے والے رسول کریم رئُ وفٌ رحيم صلی اللہ تعالٰی علیہ وسلم کی سنتوں کی اتباع میں ہے
اللہ عزوجل ہمیں اور آپ کو دونوں جہان کی بھلائیاں نصیب فرمائے ۔
۔اٰمين بجاه النبي الامين صلی الله تعالٰي عليه وسلم

items.title: Modi Surprise Diplomacy
items.description:
Narendra Modi became the first Indian prime minister in more than a decade to visit Pakistan when he made a surprise stop in Lahore on Friday to meet his Pakistani counterpart, Nawaz Sharif, on his birthday
It started with a private phone call by the Indian prime minister, Narendra Modi, to Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif of Pakistan on Friday morning to wish him a happy birthday.

About four hours later, Mr. Modi landed in the Pakistani city of Lahore for an impromptu visit with Mr. Sharif, giving such little notice that Mr. Sharif’s national security adviser could not make the journey from Islamabad in time.

It was the first visit to Pakistan by an Indian premier in almost 12 years. The tense relations between India and Pakistan, both nuclear-armed nations, have long worried American policy makers, who fear that proxy wars between the two countries could flare into a real one. Mr. Modi is also highlighting India’s role in Afghanistan, including providing military assistance, which risks angering Pakistani leaders.

Continue reading the main story
RELATED COVERAGE

Pakistan Cancels Talks With India, Citing RestrictionsAUG. 22, 2015
Modi Rebukes Pakistan After Cancellation of TalksAUG. 29, 2014
Narendra Modi, the Indian prime minister-elect who was the chief minister of Gujarat State, addressed a special farewell session of the state Legislative Assembly in Gandhinagar on Wednesday.Before Taking Office in India, Modi Sends an Invitation to PakistanMAY 21, 2014
But with his flash of spontaneous personal diplomacy on Friday, Mr. Modi appeared to send a strong public message that the ambiguous course he has taken toward Pakistan has shifted to embrace engagement, not confrontation. It is a message that his administration has hinted at in recent weeks, seeking to sketch out a road map for talks with Pakistan

items.title: 6.3 earthquake hits southeast Indonesia near East Timor capital Dili
items.description:
Earthquake in Dili East Timor Magnitudo 6,3
The earthquake, at 12:44 p.m. local time on Wednesday, was centered on the coast of Alor Island, about 77 kilometers (48 miles) west-northwest of Dili, which is located on Timor Island. It struck about 14.3 kilometers (8.9 miles) deep, making it a relatively shallow earthquake, according to the United States Geological Survey (USGS).

Witnesses on the islands reported feeling the earthquake, but there was no immediate information about possible damage or casualties.

There was no threat of a tsunami as a result of Wednesday's earthquake, according to Indonesia's seismological agency, BMKG.

Menurut sejarahnya, sebelum datang ke Aceh, kapal ini pernah bertugas di Pontianak (1997, 2001) dan Bali (1999). Setahun lebih bertugas, perjalanan kapal tersebut harus terhenti pada 26 Desember 2004. Saat merapat di Pelabuhan Ulee Lheue untuk mengisi bahan bakar, tiba-tiba tsunami datang menghantam dan membawanya ke Gampong Punge Blang Cut.

PLTD Apung telah manjadi salah satu tujuan wisata utama di Banda Aceh. Wisatawan hampir saban hari berdatangan, baik lokal maupun turis mancanegara. Kini situs ini telah memiliki sebuah museum unik di lambung kapalnya. Pengunjung yang datang bisa masuk ke dalam dan melihat anaka data.

Museum PLTD Apung yang belum lama ini dibuka menyajikan berbagai informasi penting. Bagian dalam didominasi dengan warna orange yang terbagi atas dua lantai. Tertarik untuk mengunjunginya?

items.title: Drim Greece Ep. 1: Chestnuts and Climbing | VAUDE
items.description:
DRIM! GREECE
 
With Francisco and the children we dreamt of travelling in the mountains, of making discoveries, meeting people and taking pictures. This is our dream, our DRIM Project (“Decouvertes, Rencontres, Images, Montagnes).
The DRIM! Adventure began in Greece last automn. Follow us on our trip through this travel diary. 

Production: Sandra
Photographs: Sandra and Francisco
Videos (production and editing): Francisco
Sponsors: Edelrid and Vaude.

Introduction
 
Last year we discovered, with some professional climbers, climbing in Greece, at Météores, on the island of Kalymnos and at Leonido. Greece, a wonderful country, nowhere flat: a heaven for mountain lovers. Warm people, exquisite local specialities, and a great climate during the fall. We had to get back to Greece!
 
This year we decided to go to the Peloponnese, the southern part of continental Greece, but not just to climb. We wanted to discover the wonders that we only caught a glimpse of last year. We didn’t want to rush from one place to another, but instead to follow a small country road, then another, then a roadsign, an arrow, any direction that tempted us. In a nutshell, we wanted to wander the Peloponnese Mountains with only our van and a couple of spare weeks. So we bought a return  ticket for the ferry between Ancône, in Italy, and Patras in Greece. Our trip had begun!
 
EPISODE 1.
Chestnuts and Climbing
 
For a couple of days we left the Peloponnese behind us and headed to Kalymnos, a Greek island off the Turkish coast. On our way back, we stopped near Athens, at Fili. We camped on the upper part of the city, next to the cliff. Early in the morning, we took time to enjoy a great site for novice climbers : no approach on foot, easy routes and even a bench at the bottom.  
 
From here we went to the heart of the Peloponnese, in Arcadia. Then, one evening sitting around the campfire at the Loussios gorge : “Anna, can you imagine that the other children are already in bed because tomorrow they will have to go to school ?”. She smiles back at me, and I continue : “And we, we are eating chestnuts next to a campfire and a river, in Greece”. She smiles again… But the rains interrupts us. We rush to gather our things and get back to the van to avoid getting soaked, and especially to finish off the chestnuts.

Some informations:
● Filí (climbing site). Coordinates: 38.103597, 23.668803. About 20 kilometres from Athena. Near the Mount Parnitha, the highest on the peninsula of Attica.
● Loussios gorge. Coordinates: 37.514350, 22.032700. Between the villages of Dimitsana and Stemnitsa, in Arcadia.
● Corinth. Coordinates: 37.895149, 22.870287. The fortress is being on a steep of a rocky hill 575 meters high at its highest peak.

items.title: Unprocessed Drone-based Video Footage Following the 2015 Lefkada Earthquake
items.description:
Within less than 48 hrs following the Mw 6.4 earthquake that occurred near Lefkada island in Greece, on November 17th 2015, engineers from Geoengineer.org, the University of Michigan (USA) and the University of Patras (Greece) mobilized to quickly perform condition assessment at select sites that are of potential scientific interest. The team deployed an Unmanned Aerial Autonomous Vehicle (UAAV) that was able to collect footage of affected areas. The UAAV successfully by-passed roads that were closed by landslides and other damaged infrastructure that impacted accessibility. This unprocessed video is launched immediately following UAAV deployment to make available data and footage that may prove valuable to first responders, engineers, rescue operators and damage assessors. It includes footage from the port of Vasiliki, the village of Ponti, and the famous beach of Egkremni that was devastated by landslides.

Video sections:

port of Vasiliki (@0:00) https://youtu.be/CR4WYNc_vEQ
town of Vasiliki (@7:00) https://youtu.be/CR4WYNc_vEQ?t=418
Damaged pier in Vasiliki port (@12:00) https://youtu.be/CR4WYNc_vEQ?t=724
Ponti village rock fall (@16:00) https://youtu.be/CR4WYNc_vEQ?t=962
Landsliding in Egremni beach (@24:00) https://youtu.be/CR4WYNc_vEQ?t=1441

For more information contact Prof. Dimitrios Zekkos, University of Michigan at  http://www.dimitrioszekkos.org or Prof. George Athanasopoulos, University of Patras at : http://www.civil.upatras.gr/en/Proswpiko/faculty/entry/AthanasopoulosGeorge/?PageNo=0

items.title: Afteli Beach | Lefkada's Best Beaches
items.description:
Afteli Beach Lefkada on map: https://www.google.ro/maps/place/Afteli/@38.6958506,20.5510549,11z/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x135db77bac2118bd:0x68a17aed1c9d20e?hl=en

Lefkada has many beautiful beaches that you could explore. It makes no sense to visit Lefkada and just go to the beach near to your accomodation. Try to go to as many beaches as you can, Afteli Beach could be one of them. It's a special place that I love, that's why I made this video with pictures and my personal opinion about it. 

Afteli Beach is one of my favourites is Lefkada. It’s a small quiet bay, with clear tourqouise water, away from big crowds, a place that is a good holiday starting point for me. 

Afteli Beach is located in the South of Lefkada. From Vasiliki, the windsurfer’s spot it is 10 km away, that is around 18 minutes by car, from Nidri, the largest touristic region of Lefkada it is 18 km away, meaning a half an hour ride and from Lefkada City, the capital, you are 34 km away, that is around a 45 minute ride by car. From the main road to Afteli Bay you have 4 km of road to ride, so it’s best if you have a car, scooter or ATV. I don’t recommend walking. The road is pretty good, maybe except a small portion which is through Evgiros Village, it’s a bit tight here. As you descent to the beach the road is a little steepier and curvy. 

The area feels like a botanical garden, being surrounded by trees which gives you that cosy feeling of being surrounded by nature. Usually, there are few people here, just enough so you don’t feel lonely and less to make you feel claustrophobic. The guys who take care of Afteli Beach live here in this house and also own a bar and a restaurant, where you can drink beers and grab a meal. The olive trees on the beach are beautiful to watch and they offer you the privilege of a fresh piece of natural shade. 

Afteli Beach is covered with pebbles, so don’t forget to take your beach shoes with you.

Getting closer, you can almost feel the calm and cool state of just being here. No rules other than common sense. Everybody is enjoying their piece of scenery. It’s just my personal opinion that it’s best not to come in big groups here, the place is too small and serene for larger numbers of people. It’s ideal for couples, groups of 4 to 6 people or even families with small children because you can keep an eye on them all the time and the water is protected by the sea currents, so there aren't any big waves. 

A little tip: I suggest you go there in the first part of the day. The closer you get to the sunset time the shadier the bay gets. 
They can give you free umbrellas if you need any, but don’t expect to find sun beds here. There are just a few of them. Instead you can bring your towels, or beach chairs and place them wherever you want, nobody will ask you for money just for sitting here. 

You have a free shower which is fun to use. Showers on the beach are useful in Lefkada, because the water is pretty salty and it sticks to your skin after you bathe. 

You will find the owner’s fishing boats here which are part of the whole landscape. If I was to go there and these boats were gone I would feel that something was missing. 

You shouldn't worry about parking places. There are plenty. We could always find a spot. The owners did a pretty good job in this respect. They even painted the stone, so that you will park only on one spot to make room for others to enjoy the place too. 

Then there’s the beach bar well equipped with everything you could need to drink. I also appreciate that they didn't use these type of traditional Greek chairs, which I personally hate … they are the most unconfortable chairs I’ve ever sat on. Instead, Afteli’s bar has nice outdoor bar furniture where you can relax as much as you want, drinking beers or coffees or whatever you wish. The prices at the bar are reasonable, it’s like everywhere else in Lefkada. There’s also some good music playing in sourdine. If you are keen on reading, taking your book or your kindle here will be a delight for you.

I hope my video helps in empowering your travel experience in Lefkada!

Description:

300 Spartans - The Real Story, is adapted from the 8-Episode Epic Documentary Drama called The First War for the West, available on DVD:
https://www.trepstar.com/purchase.asp?idprod=148280&mode=itemlist
Video on Demand and Streaming via Vimeo at:

The legend is fabulous, the real story is astonishing!
300 Spartans - The Real Story, is presented by Dr Michael Scott (NOVA, BBC, PBS, History Channel, etc), with contributions from nine other experts and four researchers and using the latest research, satellite positioning, and imagery, the series gives complete coverage of the story. Included is a detailed analysis of two of the oldest mysteries in history itself, what really happened at the Battle of Marathon and what really happened to King Leonidas and his 300 Spartans at Thermopylae.  Re-reading the 2500 year old text of Herodotus, the  Father of History , has revealed some missing conclusions.

What was the real mission of Leonidas and the 300 Spartans?
Were they always on a suicide mission?

Presented by Dr Michael Scott of Cambridge University, with contributions from nine other experts and four researchers and using the latest research, satellite positioning, and imagery, the series gives complete coverage of the story. Included is a detailed analysis of one of the oldest mysteries in history itself, what really happened to King Leonidas and his 300 Spartans at Thermopylae.  Re-reading the 2500 year old text of Herodotus, the  Father of History, has revealed some missing conclusions.

Putting aside the myths and legends surrounding the 300 Spartans, this documentary takes a detailed look at The Battle of Thermopylae in 480 BC, leading to the last stand of the 300 Spartans, other Greeks and the Great Spartan King, Leonidas. The legend passed down is that Leonidas went to Thermopylae with a picked band of 300 Spartans to defend the narrow pass with units from other Greek cities. Then on the 3rd day of the battle, when he found out he was being surrounded, he sent most of his troops away and covered their retreat with a last stand because Spartans never retreated. 

Using the original text of Herodotus, the only "contemporary" source, it examines the actions of Leonidas as commander of the Greek force of over 7000 men facing 150-200,000 Persians. Why they were there and what eventually led to the most famous last stand in history. Focusing on six key passages in the text, the real story gives a completely different picture than the legend we all know. Leonidas did not stay because Spartans never retreated, they had already retreated once in this war. He had plenty of time to retreat if he wanted to, but his actions on the last day point to something completely different. The documentary concludes that while the legend is fabulous, the real story is astonishing. Leonidas had plans for the last day, and they did not involve a suicidal last stand!

items.title: Remember Egremni Beach Lefkada ... After earthquake feelings
items.description:
I was heart strucked when I saw that one of my beloved beaches had colapsed... Egremni Beach in Lefkada will never be the same after the earthquake of a 6.5 magnitude that happened in Lefkada, on the 17th of November 2015. 

I was just about to continue my video series of the best beaches in Lefkada I recently started, when I saw this. Now … all I can do is pay a tribute to Egremni by remembering our wonderful experience, although it’s hard to transmit the feelings thay you get when you forget about it all and just surround your whole being in enjoying the present.  

The reviews on Tripadvisor recommend Egremni Beach as the no.1 attraction in Lefkada. Also it seems to have been voted no. 2 in the 2015 Travelers’ Choice Award on the Top 10 Beaches in Greece. It was one of the first beaches I saw, with this almost unreal dramatic blue color. That’s probably the reason why I instantly got tears in my eyes, just for having the chance to see this place in my lifetime. And after the tears of happiness were gone, the nature’s work of art put a big smile on my face, which I kept during the entire stay there. This kind of places bring that child inside back to life – it’s just pure unspoiled happiness.

We were lazy that day and we chose the easy way and got there with a boat trip from Vasiliki, so we missed the opportunity of going up and down on those 350 steps.

I was amused on how small the people on the beach looked from our boat. The thing was huge. The rocks were indeed massive and impressive. I later found out that Egremni used to be one of the longest beaches on the island stretching for about 2.5 km. And also that because of it’s width of 20 – 50 m it was impossible to get crowded. Some wild campers used to set their tents here… Just imagining how their days passed by gives me shivers. 

I wish I had more footage and with better quality, but when I went there I didn't imagine I would share this with the world :) 

In the end I just wanna say this …I love you … my dearest Egremni, I will remember you always!

items.title: Γέφυρα Ρίου Αντιρρίου - Rio Antirio bridge
items.description:
© Konstantinos Mil. Anagnostou - www.chiosphotos.gr

Εναέρια λήψη γέφυρας Ρίου-Αντιρρίου - Aerial view of Rio-Antirio bridge
Περιγραφή
Η Γέφυρα Ρίου-Αντιρρίου ή, επίσημα, Γέφυρα Χαρίλαος Τρικούπης είναι καλωδιωτή γέφυρα που ολοκληρώθηκε το 2004 μεταξύ του Ρίου (κοντά στην Πάτρα) και του Αντιρρίου, που συνδέει την Πελοπόννησο με τη δυτική ηπειρωτική Ελλάδα και προς τα πάνω με το υπόλοιπο της Ευρώπης. Κατασκευάστηκε από την Γαλλική εταιρεία Vinci. Το μήκος της γέφυρας που στηρίζεται σε τέσσερις πυλώνες, ανέρχεται στα 2.252 μέτρα, ενώ μαζί με τις προσβάσεις φτάνει γύρω στα 2.883 μέτρα. Η γέφυρα αναπτύχθηκε και ολοκληρώθηκε, παρά τις δυσμενείς περιβαλλοντικές συνθήκες, ενώ το μέγιστο βάθος θεμελίωσης φθάνει τα 65 μέτρα υπό την επιφάνεια της θάλασσας. Πρόκειται για μία καλωδιωτή γέφυρα, οι αντοχές της οποίας είναι εντυπωσιακές. Περιλαμβάνει και πεζόδρομο/ποδηλατόδρομο η χρήση των οποίων απαλλάσσεται πληρωμής διοδίων.
Description
The Rio-Antirio Bridge, officially the Charilaos Trikoupis Bridge after the statesman who first envisaged it, is one of the world's longest multi-span cable-stayed bridges and the longest of the fully suspended type. It crosses the Gulf of Corinth near Patras, linking the town of Rio on the Peloponnese peninsula to Antirrio on mainland Greece by road. 
The 2,880 m (9,449 ft) long bridge (approximately 1.8 miles) dramatically improves access to and from the Peloponnese, which could previously be reached only by ferry or via the isthmus of Corinth in the east. Its width is 28 m (92 ft) - it has two vehicle lanes per direction, an emergency lane and a pedestrian walkway. Its five-span four-pylon cable-stayed portion of length 2,252 m (7,388 ft) is the world's second longest cable-stayed deck; only the deck of the Millau Viaduct in southern France is longer at 2,460 m (8,071 ft). However, as the latter is also supported by bearings at the pylons apart from cable stays, the Rio-Antirrio Bridge deck might be considered the longest cable-stayed "suspended" deck.

items.title: Drim Greece Ep. 1: Chestnuts and Climbing | VAUDE
items.description:
DRIM! GREECE
 
With Francisco and the children we dreamt of travelling in the mountains, of making discoveries, meeting people and taking pictures. This is our dream, our DRIM Project (“Decouvertes, Rencontres, Images, Montagnes).
The DRIM! Adventure began in Greece last automn. Follow us on our trip through this travel diary. 

Production: Sandra
Photographs: Sandra and Francisco
Videos (production and editing): Francisco
Sponsors: Edelrid and Vaude.

Introduction
 
Last year we discovered, with some professional climbers, climbing in Greece, at Météores, on the island of Kalymnos and at Leonido. Greece, a wonderful country, nowhere flat: a heaven for mountain lovers. Warm people, exquisite local specialities, and a great climate during the fall. We had to get back to Greece!
 
This year we decided to go to the Peloponnese, the southern part of continental Greece, but not just to climb. We wanted to discover the wonders that we only caught a glimpse of last year. We didn’t want to rush from one place to another, but instead to follow a small country road, then another, then a roadsign, an arrow, any direction that tempted us. In a nutshell, we wanted to wander the Peloponnese Mountains with only our van and a couple of spare weeks. So we bought a return  ticket for the ferry between Ancône, in Italy, and Patras in Greece. Our trip had begun!
 
EPISODE 1.
Chestnuts and Climbing
 
For a couple of days we left the Peloponnese behind us and headed to Kalymnos, a Greek island off the Turkish coast. On our way back, we stopped near Athens, at Fili. We camped on the upper part of the city, next to the cliff. Early in the morning, we took time to enjoy a great site for novice climbers : no approach on foot, easy routes and even a bench at the bottom.  
 
From here we went to the heart of the Peloponnese, in Arcadia. Then, one evening sitting around the campfire at the Loussios gorge : “Anna, can you imagine that the other children are already in bed because tomorrow they will have to go to school ?”. She smiles back at me, and I continue : “And we, we are eating chestnuts next to a campfire and a river, in Greece”. She smiles again… But the rains interrupts us. We rush to gather our things and get back to the van to avoid getting soaked, and especially to finish off the chestnuts.

Some informations:
● Filí (climbing site). Coordinates: 38.103597, 23.668803. About 20 kilometres from Athena. Near the Mount Parnitha, the highest on the peninsula of Attica.
● Loussios gorge. Coordinates: 37.514350, 22.032700. Between the villages of Dimitsana and Stemnitsa, in Arcadia.
● Corinth. Coordinates: 37.895149, 22.870287. The fortress is being on a steep of a rocky hill 575 meters high at its highest peak.

items.title: Unprocessed Drone-based Video Footage Following the 2015 Lefkada Earthquake
items.description:
Within less than 48 hrs following the Mw 6.4 earthquake that occurred near Lefkada island in Greece, on November 17th 2015, engineers from Geoengineer.org, the University of Michigan (USA) and the University of Patras (Greece) mobilized to quickly perform condition assessment at select sites that are of potential scientific interest. The team deployed an Unmanned Aerial Autonomous Vehicle (UAAV) that was able to collect footage of affected areas. The UAAV successfully by-passed roads that were closed by landslides and other damaged infrastructure that impacted accessibility. This unprocessed video is launched immediately following UAAV deployment to make available data and footage that may prove valuable to first responders, engineers, rescue operators and damage assessors. It includes footage from the port of Vasiliki, the village of Ponti, and the famous beach of Egkremni that was devastated by landslides.

Video sections:

port of Vasiliki (@0:00) https://youtu.be/CR4WYNc_vEQ
town of Vasiliki (@7:00) https://youtu.be/CR4WYNc_vEQ?t=418
Damaged pier in Vasiliki port (@12:00) https://youtu.be/CR4WYNc_vEQ?t=724
Ponti village rock fall (@16:00) https://youtu.be/CR4WYNc_vEQ?t=962
Landsliding in Egremni beach (@24:00) https://youtu.be/CR4WYNc_vEQ?t=1441

For more information contact Prof. Dimitrios Zekkos, University of Michigan at  http://www.dimitrioszekkos.org or Prof. George Athanasopoulos, University of Patras at : http://www.civil.upatras.gr/en/Proswpiko/faculty/entry/AthanasopoulosGeorge/?PageNo=0

items.title: Afteli Beach | Lefkada's Best Beaches
items.description:
Afteli Beach Lefkada on map: https://www.google.ro/maps/place/Afteli/@38.6958506,20.5510549,11z/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x135db77bac2118bd:0x68a17aed1c9d20e?hl=en

Lefkada has many beautiful beaches that you could explore. It makes no sense to visit Lefkada and just go to the beach near to your accomodation. Try to go to as many beaches as you can, Afteli Beach could be one of them. It's a special place that I love, that's why I made this video with pictures and my personal opinion about it. 

Afteli Beach is one of my favourites is Lefkada. It’s a small quiet bay, with clear tourqouise water, away from big crowds, a place that is a good holiday starting point for me. 

Afteli Beach is located in the South of Lefkada. From Vasiliki, the windsurfer’s spot it is 10 km away, that is around 18 minutes by car, from Nidri, the largest touristic region of Lefkada it is 18 km away, meaning a half an hour ride and from Lefkada City, the capital, you are 34 km away, that is around a 45 minute ride by car. From the main road to Afteli Bay you have 4 km of road to ride, so it’s best if you have a car, scooter or ATV. I don’t recommend walking. The road is pretty good, maybe except a small portion which is through Evgiros Village, it’s a bit tight here. As you descent to the beach the road is a little steepier and curvy. 

The area feels like a botanical garden, being surrounded by trees which gives you that cosy feeling of being surrounded by nature. Usually, there are few people here, just enough so you don’t feel lonely and less to make you feel claustrophobic. The guys who take care of Afteli Beach live here in this house and also own a bar and a restaurant, where you can drink beers and grab a meal. The olive trees on the beach are beautiful to watch and they offer you the privilege of a fresh piece of natural shade. 

Afteli Beach is covered with pebbles, so don’t forget to take your beach shoes with you.

Getting closer, you can almost feel the calm and cool state of just being here. No rules other than common sense. Everybody is enjoying their piece of scenery. It’s just my personal opinion that it’s best not to come in big groups here, the place is too small and serene for larger numbers of people. It’s ideal for couples, groups of 4 to 6 people or even families with small children because you can keep an eye on them all the time and the water is protected by the sea currents, so there aren't any big waves. 

A little tip: I suggest you go there in the first part of the day. The closer you get to the sunset time the shadier the bay gets. 
They can give you free umbrellas if you need any, but don’t expect to find sun beds here. There are just a few of them. Instead you can bring your towels, or beach chairs and place them wherever you want, nobody will ask you for money just for sitting here. 

You have a free shower which is fun to use. Showers on the beach are useful in Lefkada, because the water is pretty salty and it sticks to your skin after you bathe. 

You will find the owner’s fishing boats here which are part of the whole landscape. If I was to go there and these boats were gone I would feel that something was missing. 

You shouldn't worry about parking places. There are plenty. We could always find a spot. The owners did a pretty good job in this respect. They even painted the stone, so that you will park only on one spot to make room for others to enjoy the place too. 

Then there’s the beach bar well equipped with everything you could need to drink. I also appreciate that they didn't use these type of traditional Greek chairs, which I personally hate … they are the most unconfortable chairs I’ve ever sat on. Instead, Afteli’s bar has nice outdoor bar furniture where you can relax as much as you want, drinking beers or coffees or whatever you wish. The prices at the bar are reasonable, it’s like everywhere else in Lefkada. There’s also some good music playing in sourdine. If you are keen on reading, taking your book or your kindle here will be a delight for you.

I hope my video helps in empowering your travel experience in Lefkada!

Description:

300 Spartans - The Real Story, is adapted from the 8-Episode Epic Documentary Drama called The First War for the West, available on DVD:
https://www.trepstar.com/purchase.asp?idprod=148280&mode=itemlist
Video on Demand and Streaming via Vimeo at:
http://vimeo.celebrategreece.com

The legend is fabulous, the real story is astonishing!
300 Spartans - The Real Story, is presented by Dr Michael Scott (NOVA, BBC, PBS, History Channel, etc), with contributions from nine other experts and four researchers and using the latest research, satellite positioning, and imagery, the series gives complete coverage of the story. Included is a detailed analysis of two of the oldest mysteries in history itself, what really happened at the Battle of Marathon and what really happened to King Leonidas and his 300 Spartans at Thermopylae.  Re-reading the 2500 year old text of Herodotus, the  Father of History , has revealed some missing conclusions.

What was the real mission of Leonidas and the 300 Spartans?
Were they always on a suicide mission?

Presented by Dr Michael Scott of Cambridge University, with contributions from nine other experts and four researchers and using the latest research, satellite positioning, and imagery, the series gives complete coverage of the story. Included is a detailed analysis of one of the oldest mysteries in history itself, what really happened to King Leonidas and his 300 Spartans at Thermopylae.  Re-reading the 2500 year old text of Herodotus, the  Father of History, has revealed some missing conclusions.

Putting aside the myths and legends surrounding the 300 Spartans, this documentary takes a detailed look at The Battle of Thermopylae in 480 BC, leading to the last stand of the 300 Spartans, other Greeks and the Great Spartan King, Leonidas. The legend passed down is that Leonidas went to Thermopylae with a picked band of 300 Spartans to defend the narrow pass with units from other Greek cities. Then on the 3rd day of the battle, when he found out he was being surrounded, he sent most of his troops away and covered their retreat with a last stand because Spartans never retreated. 

Using the original text of Herodotus, the only "contemporary" source, it examines the actions of Leonidas as commander of the Greek force of over 7000 men facing 150-200,000 Persians. Why they were there and what eventually led to the most famous last stand in history. Focusing on six key passages in the text, the real story gives a completely different picture than the legend we all know. Leonidas did not stay because Spartans never retreated, they had already retreated once in this war. He had plenty of time to retreat if he wanted to, but his actions on the last day point to something completely different. The documentary concludes that while the legend is fabulous, the real story is astonishing. Leonidas had plans for the last day, and they did not involve a suicidal last stand!

items.title: Remember Egremni Beach Lefkada ... After earthquake feelings
items.description:
I was heart strucked when I saw that one of my beloved beaches had colapsed... Egremni Beach in Lefkada will never be the same after the earthquake of a 6.5 magnitude that happened in Lefkada, on the 17th of November 2015. 

I was just about to continue my video series of the best beaches in Lefkada I recently started, when I saw this. Now … all I can do is pay a tribute to Egremni by remembering our wonderful experience, although it’s hard to transmit the feelings thay you get when you forget about it all and just surround your whole being in enjoying the present.  

The reviews on Tripadvisor recommend Egremni Beach as the no.1 attraction in Lefkada. Also it seems to have been voted no. 2 in the 2015 Travelers’ Choice Award on the Top 10 Beaches in Greece. It was one of the first beaches I saw, with this almost unreal dramatic blue color. That’s probably the reason why I instantly got tears in my eyes, just for having the chance to see this place in my lifetime. And after the tears of happiness were gone, the nature’s work of art put a big smile on my face, which I kept during the entire stay there. This kind of places bring that child inside back to life – it’s just pure unspoiled happiness.

We were lazy that day and we chose the easy way and got there with a boat trip from Vasiliki, so we missed the opportunity of going up and down on those 350 steps.

I was amused on how small the people on the beach looked from our boat. The thing was huge. The rocks were indeed massive and impressive. I later found out that Egremni used to be one of the longest beaches on the island stretching for about 2.5 km. And also that because of it’s width of 20 – 50 m it was impossible to get crowded. Some wild campers used to set their tents here… Just imagining how their days passed by gives me shivers. 

I wish I had more footage and with better quality, but when I went there I didn't imagine I would share this with the world :) 

In the end I just wanna say this …I love you … my dearest Egremni, I will remember you always!

items.title: Γέφυρα Ρίου Αντιρρίου - Rio Antirio bridge
items.description:
© Konstantinos Mil. Anagnostou - www.chiosphotos.gr

Εναέρια λήψη γέφυρας Ρίου-Αντιρρίου - Aerial view of Rio-Antirio bridge
Περιγραφή
Η Γέφυρα Ρίου-Αντιρρίου ή, επίσημα, Γέφυρα Χαρίλαος Τρικούπης είναι καλωδιωτή γέφυρα που ολοκληρώθηκε το 2004 μεταξύ του Ρίου (κοντά στην Πάτρα) και του Αντιρρίου, που συνδέει την Πελοπόννησο με τη δυτική ηπειρωτική Ελλάδα και προς τα πάνω με το υπόλοιπο της Ευρώπης. Κατασκευάστηκε από την Γαλλική εταιρεία Vinci. Το μήκος της γέφυρας που στηρίζεται σε τέσσερις πυλώνες, ανέρχεται στα 2.252 μέτρα, ενώ μαζί με τις προσβάσεις φτάνει γύρω στα 2.883 μέτρα. Η γέφυρα αναπτύχθηκε και ολοκληρώθηκε, παρά τις δυσμενείς περιβαλλοντικές συνθήκες, ενώ το μέγιστο βάθος θεμελίωσης φθάνει τα 65 μέτρα υπό την επιφάνεια της θάλασσας. Πρόκειται για μία καλωδιωτή γέφυρα, οι αντοχές της οποίας είναι εντυπωσιακές. Περιλαμβάνει και πεζόδρομο/ποδηλατόδρομο η χρήση των οποίων απαλλάσσεται πληρωμής διοδίων.
Description
The Rio-Antirio Bridge, officially the Charilaos Trikoupis Bridge after the statesman who first envisaged it, is one of the world's longest multi-span cable-stayed bridges and the longest of the fully suspended type. It crosses the Gulf of Corinth near Patras, linking the town of Rio on the Peloponnese peninsula to Antirrio on mainland Greece by road. 
The 2,880 m (9,449 ft) long bridge (approximately 1.8 miles) dramatically improves access to and from the Peloponnese, which could previously be reached only by ferry or via the isthmus of Corinth in the east. Its width is 28 m (92 ft) - it has two vehicle lanes per direction, an emergency lane and a pedestrian walkway. Its five-span four-pylon cable-stayed portion of length 2,252 m (7,388 ft) is the world's second longest cable-stayed deck; only the deck of the Millau Viaduct in southern France is longer at 2,460 m (8,071 ft). However, as the latter is also supported by bearings at the pylons apart from cable stays, the Rio-Antirrio Bridge deck might be considered the longest cable-stayed "suspended" deck.

items.title: When the Railroad Comes to Town: Pratt, Kansas
items.description:
When large teams of Union Pacific track improvement employees enter a small community, the impact is hard to miss.

More than 200 employees on the tie south 9161 and 9162 gangs are replacing more than 50,000 ties in the Pratt, Kansas, area in the last two months of 2015. For a community of about 7,000, the economic boost to local restaurants, gas stations and hotels is powerful.

Synopsis of Bagus/Bagus:
We start off the day by walking to the field to harvest the rice, then we cross over to Nusa Lembongan Island to wait for the tide to roll in. We then embark on the «Kerinci» a passenger ship of the Pelni company. We finally arrive in Banda Neira in the Moluccas Islands.
All this in less than five minutes.

Synopsis de Bagus/Bagus:
Nous commençons la journée en récoltant le riz, puis nous nous rendons sur l’île de Nusa Lembongan d’où nous attendons la marée montante. Nous nous embarquons ensuite sur le Kerinci, un navire de la compagnie Pelni.
Nous terminons notre voyage aux îles Banda dans les Moluques.
Tout ça en moins de 5 minutes.
